{"title_page": "VROC", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=October 2014}}\n{{notability|Organizations|date=October 2014}}\n{{third-party|date=October 2014}}\n}}\n\n'''Virtual Researcher on Call''' ('''VROC''') is a [[Canada|Canadian]] educational program administered by [[Partners in Research]].  The program connects students with knowledge partners \u2014 researchers and professionals \u2014 in [[health science|health]] and [[natural sciences]], [[technology]], [[engineering]], and [[mathematics]] ([[STEM fields]]) through [[video conferencing]] and [[podcast|video podcasts]].<ref>[http://www.vroc.ca/video/ VROC Video Podcasts]</ref>\n\n==Video conferencing==\nVideo conferencing technology is used to connect researchers and professionals in the STEM fields with [[elementary school|elementary]] and [[secondary school]] classrooms for real time, interactive discussion.\n\n==Partners==\nVROC is partnered with over 40 universities, colleges and institutions as well as school boards across the country.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.vroc.ca/vroc/en/partner/| title=Partnered Institutions| publisher=VROC| date=30 August 2010| accessdate=1 September 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430091932/http://www.vroc.ca/vroc/en/partner/| archive-date=30 April 2013| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nVROC began with a \"Reaching Higher\" [[government grant|grant]] from the Ontario [[Ministry of Training, Colleges and Universities]] in 2006 under the [[Dalton McGuinty]] government.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://ogov.newswire.ca/ontario/GPOE/2006/04/03/c1712.html?lmatch=&lang=_e.html| title=McGuinty Government Investing in Science Students| author=CNW Group| date=3 April 2006| accessdate=4 September 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Partners in Research was awarded a nearly million dollar grant from the Federal Economic Development Agency for Southern Ontario to teach southern Ontarian students about careers in science, technology, engineering and mathematics.<ref>[http://www.feddevontario.gc.ca/eic/site/723.nsf/eng/00682.html Government of Canada Supports Science and Tech Programming for Southern Ontario Youth]</ref>\n\nPartners in Research hosts a national annual awards reception and ceremony entitled The PIR National Awards to celebrate Canadian research in the STEM fields.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pirweb.org/pir/en/pir-event/| title=PIR National Awards| publisher=Partners in Research| access-date=9 January 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425070426/http://www.pirweb.org/pir/en/pir-event/| archive-date=25 April 2013| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Proceeds from this evening support the Virtual Researcher On Call Program.\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 2006 VROC was named a \"New and Noteworthy Initiative\" by the [[Canadian Education Association]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.cea-ace.ca/apps/index.cfm?fuseaction=ini.dspDetails&newsid=9b544723-65bf-6b7c-7d99-97691060d227&year=2006| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921151908/http://cea-ace.ca/apps/index.cfm?fuseaction=ini.dspDetails&newsid=9b544723-65bf-6b7c-7d99-97691060d227&year=2006| url-status=dead| archive-date=21 September 2010| title=Virtual Researcher on Call| publisher=Canadian Education Association| date=19 December 2006| accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nVROC was awarded the [[ORION (research and education network)|ORION]] Discovery Award of Merit in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.orion.on.ca/2010awards/pdf/VROC.pdf| title=2008 ORION Discovery Award of Merit| publisher=ORION| accessdate=1 September 2010}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vroc.ca VROC web page]\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Martinovic |first1=Dragana |last2=Pugh |first2=Timothy |last3=Magliaro |first3=Jelena |year=2010 |title=Pedagogy for Mobile ICT Learning Using Video-Conferencing Technology |journal=Interdisciplinary Journal of Information, Knowledge, and Management |volume=5 |issue= |pages=375\u2013392 |url=http://www.ijikm.org/Volume5/IJIKMv5p375-394Martinovic518.pdf}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vroc}}\n[[Category:Educational organizations based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Science education]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=October 2014}}\n{{notability|Organizations|date=October 2014}}\n{{third-party|date=October 2014}}\n}}\n\n'''Virtual Researcher on Call''' ('''VROC''') is a [[Canada|Canadian]] educational program administered by [[Partners in Research]].  The program connects students with knowledge partners \u2014 researchers and professionals \u2014 in [[health science|health]] and [[natural sciences]], [[technology]], [[engineering]], and [[mathematics]] ([[STEM fields]]) through [[video conferencing]] and [[podcast|video podcasts]].<ref>[http://www.vroc.ca/video/ VROC Video Podcasts]</ref>\n\n==Video conferencing==\nVideo conferencing technology is used to connect researchers and professionals in the STEM fields with [[elementary school|elementary]] and [[secondary school]] classrooms for real time, interactive discussion.\n\n==Partners==\nVROC is partnered with over 40 universities, colleges and institutions as well as school boards across the country.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.vroc.ca/vroc/en/partner/| title=Partnered Institutions| publisher=VROC| date=30 August 2010| accessdate=1 September 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430091932/http://www.vroc.ca/vroc/en/partner/| archive-date=30 April 2013| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nVROC began with a \"Reaching Higher\" [[government grant|grant]] from the Ontario [[Ministry of Training, Colleges and Universities]] in 2006 under the [[Dalton McGuinty]] government.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://ogov.newswire.ca/ontario/GPOE/2006/04/03/c1712.html?lmatch=&lang=_e.html| title=McGuinty Government Investing in Science Students| author=CNW Group| date=3 April 2006| accessdate=4 September 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Partners in Research was awarded a nearly million dollar grant from the Federal Economic Development Agency for Southern Ontario to teach southern Ontarian students about careers in science, technology, engineering and mathematics.<ref>[http://www.feddevontario.gc.ca/eic/site/723.nsf/eng/00682.html Government of Canada Supports Science and Tech Programming for Southern Ontario Youth]</ref>\n\nPartners in Research hosts a national annual awards reception and ceremony entitled The PIR National Awards to celebrate Canadian research in the STEM fields.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pirweb.org/pir/en/pir-event/| title=PIR National Awards| publisher=Partners in Research| access-date=9 January 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425070426/http://www.pirweb.org/pir/en/pir-event/| archive-date=25 April 2013| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Proceeds from this evening support the Virtual Researcher On Call Program.\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 2006 VROC was named a \"New and Noteworthy Initiative\" by the [[Canadian Education Association]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.cea-ace.ca/apps/index.cfm?fuseaction=ini.dspDetails&newsid=9b544723-65bf-6b7c-7d99-97691060d227&year=2006| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921151908/http://cea-ace.ca/apps/index.cfm?fuseaction=ini.dspDetails&newsid=9b544723-65bf-6b7c-7d99-97691060d227&year=2006| url-status=dead| archive-date=21 September 2010| title=Virtual Researcher on Call| publisher=Canadian Education Association| date=19 December 2006| accessdate=1 September 2010}} </ref>\n\nVROC was awarded the [[ORION (research and education network)|ORION]] Discovery Award of Merit in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.orion.on.ca/2010awards/pdf/VROC.pdf| title=2008 ORION Discovery Award of Merit| publisher=ORION| accessdate=1 September 2010}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vroc.ca VROC web page]\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Martinovic |first1=Dragana |last2=Pugh |first2=Timothy |last3=Magliaro |first3=Jelena |year=2010 |title=Pedagogy for Mobile ICT Learning Using Video-Conferencing Technology |journal=Interdisciplinary Journal of Information, Knowledge, and Management |volume=5 |issue= |pages=375\u2013392 |url=http://www.ijikm.org/Volume5/IJIKMv5p375-394Martinovic518.pdf}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vroc}}\n[[Category:Educational organizations based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Science education]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VROC"}
{"title_page": "Vuestar Technologies", "text_new": "{{notability|date=January 2014}}\n'''Vuestar Technologies Pte Ltd''' is a [[Singapore]]-incorporated subsidiary owned by Australian parent Goldspirit Investments Pty Ltd. The owner of both companies, Ronald Neville Langford,<ref>[http://web20.telecomtv.com/pages/?newsid=43241&id=e9381817-0593-417a-8639-c4c53e2a2a10&view=news TelecomTV - TelecomTV One - News<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223012806/http://web20.telecomtv.com/pages/?newsid=43241&id=e9381817-0593-417a-8639-c4c53e2a2a10&view=news |date=23 December 2008 }}</ref> applied for a number of [[patent]]s around the world relating to search techniques using [[hyperlink]]ed images to other [[websites]] or web pages.<ref name=\"inquirer\">[http://www.theinquirer.net/gb/inquirer/news/2008/05/28/singapore-firm-owns-pictures All your Interwibble is belong to us], Silvie Barak, [[The Inquirer]], 28 May 2008</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, Vuestar sent invoices to owners of several Singaporean websites demanding licensing fees if the websites wished to continue using \"visual images\" to link to other web pages.<ref name=\"slashdot-may27\">[http://tech.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=08/05/27/1643258 Singapore Firm Claims Patent Breach By Virtually All Websites], [[Slashdot]], 27 May 2008</ref><ref name=\"zdnet-may27\">[http://www.zdnetasia.com/news/internet/0,39044908,62041802,00.htm S'pore firm claims patent to image search], Eileen Yu, [[ZDNet]] Asia, 27 May 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.vuestar.biz/faq.php#w-user VueStar.biz] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222102521/http://www.vuestar.biz/faq.php#w-user |date=22 December 2008 }} Frequently Asked Questions: Why do I need a User Licence?</ref> A Singapore law firm advised people to carefully analyse the wide claims being made by Vuestar as to the intellectual property covered by their patent.<ref name=\"zdnet-may27\" /><ref name=\"Keystone\">[http://www.keystonelawcorp.com/downloads/Singapore%20Keystone%20Law%202008%20Ed%204A.pdf Keystone Law Alert] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828171559/http://www.keystonelawcorp.com/downloads/Singapore%20Keystone%20Law%202008%20Ed%204A.pdf |date=28 August 2008 }}, Visual Images Search Patent</ref>\n\n==Company claims==\nVuestar's website states that it has obtained granted patents for \"a method of locating web-sites using visual images\" in Singapore, [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=\"legal-heritage\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Vuestar Technologies\n  | title = Legal heritage\n  | year = 2008\n  | url = http://vuestar.biz/legal.php\n  | accessdate = 2008-05-28\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080529211225/http://www.vuestar.biz/legal.php\n  | archive-date = 29 May 2008\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> It says that website owners who \"use visual [[image]]s which hyperlink to other web-pages or web-sites in accordance with the patent ... whether on the first page or subsequent pages of a web-site\" require a license from them to continue doing so legally.<ref name=\"services\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Vuestar Technologies\n  | title = Services\n  | year = 2008\n  | url = http://www.vuestar.biz/services.php\n  | accessdate = 2008-05-28\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527193126/http://www.vuestar.biz/services.php\n  | archive-date = 27 May 2008\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> User licenses are issued for one year and restricted to Singapore.<ref name=\"faq\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Vuestar Technologies\n  | title = Frequently asked questions\n  | year = 2008\n  | url = http://vuestar.biz/faq.php\n  | accessdate = 2008-05-28\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080526173907/http://www.vuestar.biz/faq.php\n  | archive-date = 26 May 2008\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> Annual licensing fees depend on [[web traffic]] as well as the extent of image hyperlinking<ref name=\"faq\" /> and range from nothing for governments, charities and non commercial enterprises to \"millions\".<ref name=\"patent-breach\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Chua\n  | first = Hian Hou\n  | title = Patent breach by 'virtually all websites'? Pay up, firm demands\n  | newspaper = The Straits Times\n  | pages = H5\n  | date = 2008-05-27 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, in a move which has sparked criticism among [[online community|online communities]], Vuestar sent invoices to owners of several Singaporean websites demanding licensing fees if the websites wished to continue using visual images to link to other web pages.<ref name=\"slashdot-may27\" /><ref name=\"zdnet-may27\" /> Vuestar has stated that it also intends to enforce its rights in [[Australia]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=\"slashdot-may27\" /><ref name=\"patent-breach\" />\n\n==Response==\nOwners of [[Arowana]] community site Arofanatics.com were sent an invoice for S$5,350, but they have said that they do not intend to pay.<ref name=\"patent-breach\" />\n\nThe actions of Vuestar have been called [[patent troll]]ing by some.<ref name=\"ars-technica-may28\">[https://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20080528-patent-troll-sending-out-invoices-for-image-hyperlinks.html Patent troll sending out invoices for image hyperlinks], Jacqui Cheng, [[Ars Technica]], 28 May 2008</ref><ref name=\"wash-techcr\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/05/29/AR2008052901211.html Today in Patent Trolling: VueStar], John Biggs, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' ([[TechCrunch]]), 29 May 2008</ref> Ronald Langford, the inventor and a major shareholder of Vuestar Technologies, has stated that \"there has been no law broken\" and that his company is seeking payment for the use of its technology \"because the company has been 'damaged financially to the tune of millions of dollars'\"<ref>''Man who sparked patent uproar says...'', Liew Hanqing, The New Paper, 29 May 2008, quoted by [http://refutevuestarpatent.biz/?p=97 refutevuestarpatent.biz] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606235715/http://refutevuestarpatent.biz/?p=97 |date=6 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\nEileen Yu, on the [[ZDNet]] Asia blog, suggested that Vuestar's patent was the result of a flawed patent-approval system.<ref name=\"ZDNetBlog\">[http://www.zdnetasia.com/blogs/btw/0,3800011236,63003916,00.htm Is the law still not catching up?], Eileen Yo, ZDNet Asia BTW Blog</ref> However, she did also point out that Vuestar's claims might not be true or that they might have misinterpreted their patent.<ref name=\"ZDNetBlog\" /> Singapore law firm, Keystone Law, also advised people to carefully analyse Vuestar's wide claims on the intellectual property covered by their patent.<ref name=\"zdnet-may27\" /><ref name=\"Keystone\" />\n[[Image:VuestarSG.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Vuestar's Singapore Headquarters]]\n\n==Patents==\nThe patents owned by the parent company GoldSpirit Investment Pty Ltd and Vuestar Technology Pte Ltd were all registered under the name of inventor Ronald Langford, including {{Cite patent|US|7065520}}, {{Cite patent|AU|755035}} and [https://web.archive.org/web/20081222143422/http://www.epatents.gov.sg/pe/PRegister.asp?AppNo=2003018207&ImgID=I0000082679&SMode=Simple&SearchName=&SearchNumber=95940&CheckDigit=&SearchSubject=&SubM=Title&NumType=PNo&WhichQuery=1&RecordPerPage=5&DisplayOrder=DESC&NextPage=&Display=Format02&FD2=&AN2=&IPC2=&Inv2=&App2=&FAbs2=&Drw2= Singaporean patent 95940].\nThe Australian patent has ceased through failure to pay a renewal fee due in October 2007, according to [http://pericles.ipaustralia.gov.au/ols/searching/content/olsPatents.jsp the IPAustralian patent database]. {{Cite patent|EP|1327207|application}} was also filed but lapsed through failure to pay a renewal fee before the [[European Patent Office]] had conducted their own [[prior art search]].\n\nAll of these patents originated from {{Cite patent|WO|0229623|application}} which was searched and examined by [[IP Australia]] who were unable to identify any particularly relevant prior art. The patents in Australia and Singapore were therefore granted without significant limitations to the [[claim (patent)|claim]]s. The US patent was granted only after further examination by the [[US Patent and Trademark Office]] resulting in additional limitations being added to all of the independent claims as granted including that: \"the visual content comprises a plurality of mini-images in the form of a conveyor belt slide show\". Further US prosecution details are available via the [[USPTO Public PAIR system]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Odex's actions against file-sharing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vuestar.biz/ Vuestar Technologies]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080531165550/http://www.richardpalace.com/2008/05/28/vuestar/ Richard Palace]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080606002222/http://refutevuestarpatent.biz/ RefuteVueStarPatent.biz]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Internet in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Singaporean intellectual property law]]\n[[Category:Software patent law]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=January 2014}}\n'''Vuestar Technologies Pte Ltd''' is a [[Singapore]]-incorporated subsidiary owned by Australian parent Goldspirit Investments Pty Ltd. The owner of both companies, Ronald Neville Langford,<ref>[http://web20.telecomtv.com/pages/?newsid=43241&id=e9381817-0593-417a-8639-c4c53e2a2a10&view=news TelecomTV - TelecomTV One - News<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223012806/http://web20.telecomtv.com/pages/?newsid=43241&id=e9381817-0593-417a-8639-c4c53e2a2a10&view=news |date=23 December 2008 }}</ref> applied for a number of [[patent]]s around the world relating to search techniques using [[hyperlink]]ed images to other [[websites]] or web pages.<ref name=\"inquirer\">[http://www.theinquirer.net/gb/inquirer/news/2008/05/28/singapore-firm-owns-pictures All your Interwibble is belong to us], Silvie Barak, [[The Inquirer]], 28 May 2008</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, Vuestar sent invoices to owners of several Singaporean websites demanding licensing fees if the websites wished to continue using \"visual images\" to link to other web pages.<ref name=\"slashdot-may27\">[http://tech.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=08/05/27/1643258 Singapore Firm Claims Patent Breach By Virtually All Websites], [[Slashdot]], 27 May 2008</ref><ref name=\"zdnet-may27\">[http://www.zdnetasia.com/news/internet/0,39044908,62041802,00.htm S'pore firm claims patent to image search], Eileen Yu, [[ZDNet]] Asia, 27 May 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.vuestar.biz/faq.php#w-user VueStar.biz] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222102521/http://www.vuestar.biz/faq.php#w-user |date=22 December 2008 }} Frequently Asked Questions: Why do I need a User Licence?</ref> A Singapore law firm advised people to carefully analyse the wide claims being made by Vuestar as to the intellectual property covered by their patent.<ref name=\"zdnet-may27\" /><ref name=\"Keystone\">[http://www.keystonelawcorp.com/downloads/Singapore%20Keystone%20Law%202008%20Ed%204A.pdf Keystone Law Alert] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828171559/http://www.keystonelawcorp.com/downloads/Singapore%20Keystone%20Law%202008%20Ed%204A.pdf |date=28 August 2008 }}, Visual Images Search Patent</ref>\n\n==Company claims==\nVuestar's website states that it has obtained granted patents for \"a method of locating web-sites using visual images\" in Singapore, [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=\"legal-heritage\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Vuestar Technologies\n  | title = Legal heritage\n  | year = 2008\n  | url = http://vuestar.biz/legal.php\n  | accessdate = 2008-05-28\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080529211225/http://www.vuestar.biz/legal.php\n  | archive-date = 29 May 2008\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> It says that website owners who \"use visual [[image]]s which hyperlink to other web-pages or web-sites in accordance with the patent ... whether on the first page or subsequent pages of a web-site\" require a license from them to continue doing so legally.<ref name=\"services\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Vuestar Technologies\n  | title = Services\n  | year = 2008\n  | url = http://www.vuestar.biz/services.php\n  | accessdate = 2008-05-28\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527193126/http://www.vuestar.biz/services.php\n  | archive-date = 27 May 2008\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> User licenses are issued for one year and restricted to Singapore.<ref name=\"faq\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Vuestar Technologies\n  | title = Frequently asked questions\n  | year = 2008\n  | url = http://vuestar.biz/faq.php\n  | accessdate = 2008-05-28\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080526173907/http://www.vuestar.biz/faq.php\n  | archive-date = 26 May 2008\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> Annual licensing fees depend on [[web traffic]] as well as the extent of image hyperlinking<ref name=\"faq\" /> and range from nothing for governments, charities and non commercial enterprises to \"millions\".<ref name=\"patent-breach\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Chua\n  | first = Hian Hou\n  | title = Patent breach by 'virtually all websites'? Pay up, firm demands\n  | newspaper = The Straits Times\n  | pages = H5\n  | date = 2008-05-27 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, in a move which has sparked criticism among [[online community|online communities]], Vuestar sent invoices to owners of several Singaporean websites demanding licensing fees if the websites wished to continue using visual images to link to other web pages.<ref name=\"slashdot-may27\" /><ref name=\"zdnet-may27\" /> Vuestar has stated that it also intends to enforce its rights in [[Australia]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=\"slashdot-may27\" /><ref name=\"patent-breach\" />\n\n==Response==\nOwners of [[Arowana]] community site Arofanatics.com were sent an invoice for S$5,350, but they have said that they do not intend to pay.<ref name=\"patent-breach\" />\n\nThe actions of Vuestar have been called [[patent troll]]ing by some.<ref name=\"ars-technica-may28\">[https://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20080528-patent-troll-sending-out-invoices-for-image-hyperlinks.html Patent troll sending out invoices for image hyperlinks], Jacqui Cheng, [[Ars Technica]], 28 May 2008</ref><ref name=\"wash-techcr\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/05/29/AR2008052901211.html Today in Patent Trolling: VueStar], John Biggs, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' ([[TechCrunch]]), 29 May 2008</ref> Ronald Langford, the inventor and a major shareholder of Vuestar Technologies, has stated that \"there has been no law broken\" and that his company is seeking payment for the use of its technology \"because the company has been 'damaged financially to the tune of millions of dollars'\"<ref>''Man who sparked patent uproar says...'', Liew Hanqing, The New Paper, 29 May 2008, quoted by [http://refutevuestarpatent.biz/?p=97 refutevuestarpatent.biz] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606235715/http://refutevuestarpatent.biz/?p=97 |date=6 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\nEileen Yu, on the [[ZDNet]] Asia blog, suggested that Vuestar's patent was the result of a flawed patent-approval system.<ref name=\"ZDNetBlog\">[http://www.zdnetasia.com/blogs/btw/0,3800011236,63003916,00.htm Is the law still not catching up?], Eileen Yo, ZDNet Asia BTW Blog</ref> However, she did also point out that Vuestar's claims might not be true or that they might have misinterpreted their patent.<ref name=\"ZDNetBlog\" /> Singapore law firm, Keystone Law, also advised people to carefully analyse Vuestar's wide claims on the intellectual property covered by their patent.<ref name=\"zdnet-may27\" /><ref name=\"Keystone\" />\n[[Image:VuestarSG.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Vuestar's Singapore Headquarters]]\n==Patents==\nThe patents owned by the parent company GoldSpirit Investment Pty Ltd and Vuestar Technology Pte Ltd were all registered under the name of inventor Ronald Langford, including {{Cite patent|US|7065520}}, {{Cite patent|AU|755035}} and [https://web.archive.org/web/20081222143422/http://www.epatents.gov.sg/pe/PRegister.asp?AppNo=2003018207&ImgID=I0000082679&SMode=Simple&SearchName=&SearchNumber=95940&CheckDigit=&SearchSubject=&SubM=Title&NumType=PNo&WhichQuery=1&RecordPerPage=5&DisplayOrder=DESC&NextPage=&Display=Format02&FD2=&AN2=&IPC2=&Inv2=&App2=&FAbs2=&Drw2= Singaporean patent 95940].\nThe Australian patent has ceased through failure to pay a renewal fee due in October 2007, according to [http://pericles.ipaustralia.gov.au/ols/searching/content/olsPatents.jsp the IPAustralian patent database]. {{Cite patent|EP|1327207|application}} was also filed but lapsed through failure to pay a renewal fee before the [[European Patent Office]] had conducted their own [[prior art search]].\n\nAll of these patents originated from {{Cite patent|WO|0229623|application}} which was searched and examined by [[IP Australia]] who were unable to identify any particularly relevant prior art. The patents in Australia and Singapore were therefore granted without significant limitations to the [[claim (patent)|claim]]s. The US patent was granted only after further examination by the [[US Patent and Trademark Office]] resulting in additional limitations being added to all of the independent claims as granted including that: \"the visual content comprises a plurality of mini-images in the form of a conveyor belt slide show\". Further US prosecution details are available via the [[USPTO Public PAIR system]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Odex's actions against file-sharing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vuestar.biz/ Vuestar Technologies]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080531165550/http://www.richardpalace.com/2008/05/28/vuestar/ Richard Palace]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080606002222/http://refutevuestarpatent.biz/ RefuteVueStarPatent.biz]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[Category:Internet in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Singaporean intellectual property law]]\n[[Category:Software patent law]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vuestar_Technologies"}
{"title_page": "Puritan Bennett", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Puritan Bennett\n| logo = \n| type = \n| industry = Pharmaceuticals\n| fate = \n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1913}}\n| founder = Ray Bennett\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = Richard H. Anderson, President and CEO\n| products = \n| owner = [[Medtronic]]\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| website = {{URL|www.puritanbennett.com}}\n}}\n'''Puritan Bennett''' has been a provider of respiratory products since 1913 originally as a medical gas supplier. In addition to critical care ventilation, Puritan Bennett provided medical devices for patients outside of the acute care environment. Its products included portable ventilation, [[oxygen therapy]] systems, sleep diagnostic and sleep therapy equipment, [[spirometry]] and other respiratory care products.\n\n==History==\n1913: Puritan Bennett entered  the medical gas industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vineyardgazette.com/obituaries/2004/09/17/john-b-francis-87-was-executive-philanthropist|title=John B. Francis, 87, Was Executive, Philanthropist|last=|first=|date=September 16, 2004|website=The Vineyard Gazette - Martha's Vineyard News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/puritan-bennett-corporation-history/|title=History of Puritan-Bennett Corporation \u2013 FundingUniverse|last=|first=|date=|website=www.fundinguniverse.com|publisher=|others=International Directory of Company Histories, Vol. 13. St. James Press, 1996.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n1940: Founder Ray Bennett invented a [[mechanical ventilator]] as an alternative to the [[Negative pressure ventilator|iron lung]] machine.<ref>https://foocus.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/The-Fascinating-History-of-Respiratory-Therapy.pdf</ref>\n\n1995: [[Nellcor]] acquired Puritan Bennett. The newly expanded company was renamed Nellcor Puritan Bennett.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=7ee1a200-740b-11ea-8a6e-91eb04d115e6&url=L3Byb2ZpbGUvY29tcGFueS9ORUxMOlVT|title=Nellcor Puritan Bennett LLC|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n1997: Nellcor Puritan Bennett became a part of [[Mallinckrodt]], a medical products company with product lines in respiratory care, diagnostic imaging and analgesic pharmaceuticals.\n\n1998: Puritan-Bennett Aero Systems (PBASCO<ref name=\":0\" />) was sold to [[BE Aerospace]] Inc.<ref>http://www.beaerospace.com/home.nsf/c81051411e101f2285256a8c00535c44/364d099284adafd085256a94005891f7/$FILE/FORM%2010-K%20Feb%2024%202001.pdf {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061017034243/http://www.beaerospace.com/home.nsf/c81051411e101f2285256a8c00535c44/364d099284adafd085256a94005891f7/%24FILE/FORM%2010-K%20Feb%2024%202001.pdf |date=2006-10-17 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/stories/1998/04/13/daily7.html|title=B/E Aerospace completes purchase of Puritan-Bennett Aero Systems|last=|first=|date=Apr 14, 1998|website=www.bizjournals.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n2000: [[Tyco International]] acquired Mallinckrodt to become a [[Tyco Healthcare]] company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reuters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/29/business/tyco-buying-mallinckrodt-for-3.2-billion.html|title=Tyco Buying Mallinckrodt For $3.2 Billion|date=2000-06-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Journal|first=Laura Johannes and Thomas M. BurtonStaff Reporters of The Wall Street|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB962227324727281101|title=Tyco International to Acquire Mallinckrodt for $4.2 Billion|date=2000-06-29|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n2007: [[Covidien]] spun off from [[Tyco International]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.companieshistory.com/covidien/|title=Covidien|date=2013-08-26|website=Companies History - The biggest companies in the world|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and inherited Puritan Bennett along with other [[Tyco Healthcare]] Brands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-covidien-medtronic-inc-idUSKBN0ER03420140616|title=Medtronic to buy Covidien for $42.9 billion, rebase in Ireland|date=2014-06-16|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n2015: Medtronic acquires [[Covidien]] and inherit all brands including Puritan Bennett.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medtronic.com/covidien/en-us/index.html|title=Medtronic Minimally Invasive Therapies|website=www.medtronic.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Ventilators==\n\n===840 Ventilator System===\n:The 840 Ventilator System is the oldfashioned acute critical care ventilator sold by Puritan Bennett. Launched in some countries older than 2002. It is the flagship product in Puritan Bennett's line of critical care ventilators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medtronic.com/covidien/en-us/products/mechanical-ventilation/puritan-bennett-840-ventilator.html|title=Puritan Bennett\u2122 840 Ventilator {{!}} Medtronic|website=www.medtronic.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n*Software Options<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medtronic.com/covidien/en-us/index.html|title=Medtronic Minimally Invasive Therapies|website=www.medtronic.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n**PAV+ Software\n**BiLevel Software\n**Volume Ventilation Plus Software\n**Tube Compensation Software\n**NeoMode Software\n\n===700 Series===\n: The 700 Series (740 & 760) Ventilator System is a critical care ventilator model prior to the current 840 Series. The system was designed in Galway, Ireland.\n\n===7200 Series===\n:The 7200 Series is a critical care ventilator model prior to the 760 Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kindredhealthcare.com/resources/blog-kindred-continuum/2013/03/25/ventilators-of-the-past|title=Ventilators of the Past|last=Squire|first=Ryan|date=March 25, 2013|website=Kindred|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===560 Series===\n:The 560 Series is a portable ventilation unit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2020/03/30/medtronic-is-sharing-its-portable-ventilator-design-specifications-and-code-for-free-to-all/|title=Medtronic is sharing its portable ventilator design specifications and code for free to all|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Medical equipment]]\n\n\n{{company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Puritan Bennett\n| logo = \n| type = \n| industry = Pharmaceuticals\n| fate = \n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1913}}\n| founder = Ray Bennett\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = Richard H. Anderson, President and CEO\n| products = \n| owner = [[Medtronic]]\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| website = {{URL|www.puritanbennett.com}}\n}}\n'''Puritan Bennett''' has been a provider of respiratory products since 1913 originally as a medical gas supplier. In addition to critical care ventilation, Puritan Bennett provided medical devices for patients outside of the acute care environment. Its products included portable ventilation, [[oxygen therapy]] systems, sleep diagnostic and sleep therapy equipment, [[spirometry]] and other respiratory care products.\n\n==History==\n1913: Puritan Bennett entered  the medical gas industry.<ref>[http://www.puritanbennett.com/about/index.aspx#history Puritan Bennett | About Us]</ref>\n\n1940: Founder Ray Bennett invented a [[mechanical ventilator]] as an alternative to the [[Negative pressure ventilator|iron lung]] machine.\n\n1995: [[Nellcor]] acquired Puritan Bennett. The newly expanded company is renamed Nellcor Puritan Bennett.\n\n1997: Nellcor Puritan Bennett became a part of [[Mallinckrodt]], a medical products company with product lines in respiratory care, diagnostic imaging and analgesic pharmaceuticals.\n\n1998: Puritan-Bennett Aero Systems (PBASCO) was sold to [[BE Aerospace]] Inc.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1998_April_14/ai_n27521641]</ref><ref>http://www.beaerospace.com/home.nsf/c81051411e101f2285256a8c00535c44/364d099284adafd085256a94005891f7/$FILE/FORM%2010-K%20Feb%2024%202001.pdf {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061017034243/http://www.beaerospace.com/home.nsf/c81051411e101f2285256a8c00535c44/364d099284adafd085256a94005891f7/%24FILE/FORM%2010-K%20Feb%2024%202001.pdf |date=2006-10-17 }}</ref>\n\n2000: [[Tyco International]] acquired Mallinckrodt to become a [[Tyco Healthcare]] company.\n\n2007: [[Covidien]] spun off from [[Tyco International]] and inherited Puritan Bennett along with other [[Tyco Healthcare]] Brands.\n\n2015: Medtronic acquires [[Covidien]] and inherit all brands including Puritan Bennett.\n\n==Ventilators==\n\n===840 Ventilator System===\n:The 840 Ventilator System is the oldfashioned acute critical care ventilator sold by Puritan Bennett. Launched in some countries older than 2002. It is the flagship product in Puritan Bennett's line of critical care ventilators.<ref>[http://www.puritanbennett.com/prod/Product.aspx?S1=VEN&S2=VNT&id=199]</ref>\n\n*Software Options<ref>[http://www.puritanbennett.com/prod/Product.aspx?S1=VEN&S2=VNT&id=202]<