 is a part of the municipality of [[Molenwaard]], and lies about 13&nbsp;km north of [[Gorinchem]] on the southside of the [[Lek (river)|Lek]] River.\n\nThe statistical area \"Waal\", which also can include the surrounding countryside, has a population of around 110.<ref name=\"CBS2\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), [http://statline.cbs.nl/ ''Statline: Kerncijfers wijken en buurten 2003-2005'']. As of 1 January 2005.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n<references/>\n\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Dutch municipality Molenwaard}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in South Holland]]\n[[Category:Molenwaard]]\n\n\n{{SouthHolland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waal,_South_Holland"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of LGBT history, 20th century", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n\nThe following is a '''timeline of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender''' ('''[[LGBT]]''') '''history''', in the ''[[20th century]]''.\n<!--\nPlease also add applicable entries to the List of lesbian, gay, bisexual, or transgender firsts by year article\n-->==Timeline==\n\n==1900s==\n* '''1903'''&nbsp;\u2013 In New York City on 21 February 1903, New York police conducted the first United States recorded raid on a [[gay bathhouse]], the [[Ariston Bathhouse raid|Ariston Hotel Baths]]. 34 men were arrested and 12 brought to trial on sodomy charges; 7 men received sentences ranging from 4 to 20 years in prison.<ref name=Chauncey>(Chauncey, 1995)</ref>\n* '''1906'''&nbsp;\u2013 Potentially the first openly gay American novel with a happy ending, ''[[Imre: A Memorandum|Imre]]'', is published.<ref name=Fone>{{cite book |author=Fone, Byrne R. S. |title=Homophobia: a history |publisher=[[Metropolitan Books]] |location=New York |year=2000 |isbn=0-8050-4559-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/homophobiahistor00fone }}</ref>\n* '''1907'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Adolf Brand]], the activist leader of the Gemeinschaft der Eigenen, working to overturn Paragraph 175, publishes a piece \"outing\" the imperial chancellor of Germany, Prince [[Bernhard von B\u00fclow]]. The Prince sues Brand for libel and clears his name; Brand is sentenced to 18 months in prison.<ref>Marc Vargo. ''Scandal: infamous gay controversies of the twentieth century'' Routledge, 2003. pp 165\u20137.</ref>\n* '''1907\u20131909'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Harden\u2013Eulenburg affair]] in Germany<ref name=Steakley>Steakley, James D. (revised 1989). \"Iconography of a Scandal: Political Cartoons and the Eulenburg Affair in Wilhelmin Germany\", ''Hidden from History: Reclaiming the Gay & Lesbian Past'' (1990), Duberman, et al., eds. New York: Meridian, New American Library, Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-452-01067-5}}.</ref>\n\n==1910s==\n* '''1910'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Emma Goldman]] first begins speaking publicly in favor of homosexual rights. [[Magnus Hirschfeld]] later wrote \"she was the first and only woman, indeed the first and only American, to take up the defense of homosexual love before the general public.\"<ref name=hirschfeld>Goldman, Emma (1923). \"Offener Brief an den Herausgeber der Jahrb\u00fccher \u00fcber Louise Michel\" with a preface by Magnus Hirschfeld. ''Jahrbuch f\u00fcr sexuelle Zwischenstufen'' 23: 70.\u200a Translated from German by James Steakley. Goldman's original letter in English is not known to be extant.</ref> [[File:Lesbiche - 1928 - D- Die freundin 1928.jpg|thumb|upright|14 May 1928 issue of German lesbian periodical ''Die Freundin'' ([[Friedrich Radszuweit]])]]<ref>[http://www.wpunj.edu/newpol/issue45/Escoffier45.htm ''Left-wing Homosexuality Emancipation, Sexual Liberation, and Identity Politics''.]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430093850/http://www.wpunj.edu/newpol/issue45/Escoffier45.htm |date=30 April 2009 }} Jeffrey Escoffier,<br /> \"During the first decade of the twentieth-century, the great anarchist and feminist leader Emma Goldman argued for the acceptance of homosexuals in her speeches and writings.\"</ref>\n* '''1912'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first explicit reference to lesbianism in a Mormon magazine occurred when the \"Young Woman's Journal\" paid tribute to \"[[Sappho]] of Lesbos<ref name=\"affirmation.org\">[http://www.affirmation.org/history/lesbian_mormon_history.shtml Gay & Lesbian Mormons] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424190731/http://www.affirmation.org/history/lesbian_mormon_history.shtml |date=24 April 2012 }}. Affirmation. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> \"; the Scientific Humanitarian Committee of the Netherlands (NWHK), the first Dutch organization to campaign against anti-homosexual discrimination, is established by Dr. Jacob Schorer.\n* '''1913'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word faggot is first used in print in reference to gays in a vocabulary of criminal slang published in [[Portland, Oregon]]: \"All the faggots <small>''[sic]''</small> (sissies) will be dressed in drag at the ball tonight\".\n* '''1917'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[October Revolution]] in Russia repeals the previous criminal code in its entirety\u2014including Article 995.<ref>[http://community.middlebury.edu/~moss/RGC2.html middlebury.edu ''Russian Gay History'']<br />\"It was not until 1832 that the criminal code included Article 995, which made muzhelozhstvo (men lying with men, which the courts interpreted as anal intercourse) a criminal act punishable by exile to Siberia.... The October Revolution of 1917 did away with the entire Criminal Code .... The new Russian Criminal Codes of 1922 and 1926 eliminated the offence of muzhelozhstvo from the law.\"</ref><ref>Wayne R. Dynes, Stephen Donaldson. ''History of homosexuality in Europe and America''. Taylor & Francis, 1992, pp. 174+</ref> Bolshevik leaders reportedly say that \"homosexual relationships and heterosexual relationships are treated exactly the same by the law.\"\n* '''1919'''&nbsp;\u2013 In Berlin, Germany, Doctor [[Magnus Hirschfeld]] co-founds the [[Institut f\u00fcr Sexualwissenschaft]] (Institute for Sex Research), a pioneering private research institute and counseling office. Its library of thousands of books was destroyed by Nazis in May 1933.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hirschfeld.in-berlin.de/aus_inst_en.html|title=hirschfeld.in-berlin.de, ''The first Institute for Sexual Science''|author=Susanne J\u00e4ger|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.stonewallsociety.com/famouspeople/magnus.htm Famous GLBT & GLBTI People - Dr. Magnus Hirschfeld] stonewallsociety</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tex-BuFgji0C&pg=PA16|title=Atina Grossmann. ''Reforming Sex''. Oxford University Press, 1995.|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014|isbn=9780195363517|last1=Grossmann|first1=Atina|date=11 May 1995}}</ref>\n* '''1919''' - ''[[Different from the Others]]'', one of the first explicitly gay films, is released. [[Magnus Hirschfeld]] has a cameo in the film and partially funded its production.\n\n==1920s==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2010}}\n* '''1921'''&nbsp;\u2013 In England, an attempt to make lesbianism illegal for the first time in Britain's history fails.<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/law/article3856756.ece Weird Cases: Lesbian litigants] Times Online, 2 May 2008</ref>\n* '''1922'''&nbsp;\u2013 A new criminal code comes into force in the [[USSR]] officially decriminalizing homosexual acts.\n* '''1923'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word fag is first used in print in reference to gays in Nels Anderson's ''The Hobo'': \"Fairies or Fags are men or boys who exploit sex for profit.\"\n* '''1923'''&nbsp;\u2013  Lesbian [[Elsa Gidlow]], born in England, published the first volume of openly [[lesbian]] love poetry in the United States, titled \"On a Grey Thread.\"<ref>Holt, Patricia (22 June 1986). \"Search for the Independent Mind\". ''San Francisco Chronicle''.</ref>\n* '''1924'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first homosexual rights organization in America is founded by [[Henry Gerber]] in Chicago\u2014 the [[Society for Human Rights]].<ref>Hogan and Hudson, p. 244</ref> The group exists for a few months before disbanding under police pressure.<ref>Bullough, p. 28</ref> Paraguay and Peru legalize homosexuality.\n* '''1926'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''The New York Times'' is the first major publication to use the word homosexuality.<ref name=Fone/>\n* '''1927''' - [[Karol Szymanowski]], Poland's openly gay composer, is appointed chief of Poland's state-owned national music school, the [[Fryderyk Chopin Music Academy]].\n* '''1928'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Well of Loneliness]]'' by [[Radclyffe Hall]] is published in the UK and later in the United States. This sparks great legal controversy and brings the topic of homosexuality to public conversation.\n* '''1929'''&nbsp;\u2013 On 22 May, [[Katharine Lee Bates]], author of ''[[America the Beautiful]]'' dies. On 16 October, a [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]] Committee votes to repeal Paragraph 175; the [[Nazism|Nazis']] rise to power prevents the implementation of the vote.\n\n==1930s==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2010}}\n<!--[[File:Eldoradoinberlinafterforcedclosingbynazis.gif|thumb|250px|left|Once \"Eldorado\" homosexual night club in Berlin after being closed during 1933, with banners promoting \"Hitler List 1\"]].-->\n* '''1931''' - ''[[M\u00e4dchen in Uniform (1931 film)|M\u00e4dchen in Uniform]]'', one of the first explicitly lesbian films and the first pro-lesbian film, is released.\n* '''1931''' - In Berlin in 1931, [[Dorchen Richter|Dora Richter]] became the first known transgender woman to undergo [[vaginoplasty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transmediawatch.org/timeline.html|title=Trans Media Watch|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transmediawatch.org/timeline.html|title=Trans Media Watch|first=Donald|last=Munro|publisher=|accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref> \n* '''1932'''&nbsp;\u2013 Poland codifies the homosexual and heterosexual age of consent equally at 15. Polish law never had criminalized homosexuality, although occupying powers had outlawed it in 1835.<ref name=\"IES_Poland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sexarchive.info/IES/poland.html#6 |title=Homoerotic, Homosexual, and Ambisexual Behaviors |publisher=Continuum Publishing |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511015953/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/IES/poland.html |archivedate=11 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''1933'''&nbsp;\u2013 New [[Danish penalty law]] decriminalizes homosexuality.\n* '''1933'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[National Socialist German Workers Party]] bans homosexual groups. Homosexuals are sent to concentration camps. Nazis burn the library of Magnus Hirschfeld's [[Institut f\u00fcr Sexualwissenschaft|Institute for Sexual Research]], and destroy the Institute; [[Denmark]] and [[Philippines]] decriminalizes homosexuality. Homosexual acts are recriminalized in the USSR.\n* '''1934'''&nbsp;\u2013 Uruguay decriminalizes homosexuality. The USSR once again criminalizes ''muzhelozhstvo'' (specific Russian definition of \"male sexual intercourse with male\", literally \"man lying with man\"), punishable by up to 5 years in prison&nbsp;\u2013 more for the coercion or involvement of minors.<ref>{{cite book|last= West|first=Donald James|author2=Richard Green |title=Sociolegal control of homosexuality: a multi-nation comparison|year=1997|publisher=Springer|isbn=0-306-45532-3|page=224}}</ref>\n* '''1936'''&nbsp;\u2013 Mona's 440 Club, the first lesbian bar in America, opened in San Francisco in 1936.<ref name=\"duberman\">{{cite book|last=Duberman|first=Martin B.|editor-last1=Duberman|editor-first1=Martin B.|editor-last2=Vicinus|editor-first2=Martha|editor-link2=Martha Vicinus|editor-last3=Chauncey|editor-first3=George|title=Hidden from History: Reclaiming the Gay & Lesbian Past|publisher=New York: Meridian|year=1989|isbn=0-452-01067-5|url=https://archive.org/details/hiddenfromhisto000dube}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">James R. Smith [https://books.google.com/books?id=Wvsudy6RdGAC&pg=PA84 San Francisco's Lost Landmarks], Quill Driver Books, 2004 {{ISBN|1884995446}} p. 84</ref> Mona's waitresses and female performers wore tuxedos and patrons dressed their roles.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n* '''1936'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]], Spanish poet, is shot at the beginning of the Spanish civil war.\n* '''1937'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first use of the [[pink triangle]] for gay men in [[Nazi concentration camps]].\n* '''1938'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word ''[[gay]]'' is used for the first time on film in reference to homosexuality in the film ''[[Bringing Up Baby]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayifoundout.com/index.php/2011/01/the-first-time-gay-meaning-homosexual-was-used-as-such-in-a-film/ |title=The First Time \"Gay\", Meaning \"Homosexual\", Was Used as Such in a Film |publisher=todayifoundout.com |date=17 January 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n* '''1939'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Frances V. Rummell]], an educator and a teacher of French at Stephens College, published an autobiography under the title ''Diana: A Strange Autobiography''; it was the first explicitly lesbian autobiography in which two women end up happily together.<ref name=\"pbs.org\">[https://www.pbs.org/opb/historydetectives/investigations/806_diana.html History Detectives . Investigations \u2013 Diana]. PBS. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> This autobiography was published with a note stating \"The publishers wish it expressly understood that this is a true story, the first of its kind ever offered to the general reading public\".<ref name=\"pbs.org\"/>\n\n==1940s==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2010}}\n* '''1940'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Iceland]] decriminalizes homosexuality; the NWHK is disbanded in the Netherlands in May due to the [[Battle of the Netherlands|German invasion]], and most of its archive is voluntarily destroyed, while the rest is confiscated by Nazi soldiers.\n* '''1941'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Transsexuality]] was first used in reference to homosexuality and bisexuality.\n* '''1942'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Switzerland]] decriminalizes homosexuality, with the age of consent set at 20.\n* '''1944'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Sweden]] decriminalizes homosexuality, with the age of consent set at 18 and [[Suriname]] legalizes homosexuality.\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Schimitzek Erwin.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Pink triangle prisoner Erwin Schimitzek, interned in [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] in 1941, died in 1942.]] -->\n* '''1944'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first prominent American to reveal his homosexuality was the poet [[Robert Duncan (poet)|Robert Duncan]]. This occurred when in 1944, using his own name in the anarchist magazine ''Politics'', he wrote that homosexuals were an oppressed minority.<ref>[http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/15949 \"Robert Duncan and Romantic Synthesis: A Few Notes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906020604/http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/15949 |date=2010-09-06 }}. This article also republished as \"On Robert Duncan\" at Modern American Poetry website</ref>\n* '''1945'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[The Holocaust]] ends and it is estimated that between about 3,000 to about 9,000 homosexuals died in [[Nazi concentration camps|Nazi concentration]] and [[Nazi death camps|death camps]], while it is estimated that between about 2,000 to about 6,000 homosexual survivors in Nazi concentration and death camps were required to serve out the full term of their sentences under [[Paragraph 175]] in prison. The first gay bar in post-World War II Berlin opened in the summer of 1945, and the first drag ball took place in [[American Zone of Occupation|American sector]] of [[West Berlin]] in the fall of 1945.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JwB5AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA179#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Lesbian and Gay Histories and Cultures|first1=George|last1=Haggerty|first2=Bonnie|last2=Zimmerman|date=2 September 2003|publisher=Garland Science|via=Google Books|isbn=9781135578718}}</ref> Four honourably discharged gay veterans form the [[Veterans Benevolent Association]], the first LGBT veterans' group.<ref>Archer, p. 110</ref> Gay bar [[:ja:\u3084\u306a\u304e (\u30b2\u30a4\u30d0\u30fc)|Yanagi]] opened in Japan.<ref>\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u306e\u9054\u4eba (2008 [[Shinchosha]])</ref>\n* '''1946'''&nbsp;\u2013 \"[[COC Nederland|COC]]\" (Dutch acronym for \"Center for Culture and Recreation\"), one of the earliest [[homophile]] organizations, is founded in the Netherlands. It is the oldest surviving LGBT organization.\n* '''1946'''&nbsp;\u2013 Plastic surgeon [[Harold Gillies]] carries out sex reassignment surgery on [[Michael Dillon]] in Britain. \n* '''1947-1948'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Vice Versa (magazine)|Vice Versa]]'', the first American lesbian publication, is written and self-published by [[Lisa Ben]] (real name Edith Eyde) in Los Angeles.\n* '''1948'''&nbsp;\u2013 \"[[Danish National Association of Gays and Lesbians|Forbundet af 1948]]\" (\"League of 1948\"), a homosexual group, is formed in Denmark.\n* '''1948'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[History of Poland (1945\u20131989)|communist authorities of Poland]] make 15 the age of consent for all sexual acts, homosexual or heterosexual.\n\n==1950s==\n* '''1950'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Organization for Sexual Equality, now [[Swedish Federation for Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Rights]] (RFSL), is formed in Sweden; [[East Germany]] partially abrogates the Nazis' emendations to Paragraph 175; The [[Mattachine Society]], the first sustained American homosexual group, is founded in [[Los Angeles]] (11 November); 190 individuals in the United States are dismissed from government employment for their sexual orientation, commencing the [[Lavender scare]].\n* '''1951'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Greece]] decriminalizes homosexuality.\n* '''1951'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jordan]] In 1951, a revision of the Jordanian Criminal Code legalized private, adult, non-commercial, and consensual sodomy, with the age of consent set at 16.\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 \"Spring Fire,\" the first lesbian paperback novel, and the beginning of the lesbian pulp fiction genre, was published in 1952 and sold 1.5 million copies.<ref name=\"amazon.com\">[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1573441872 Spring Fire (Lesbian Pulp Fiction) (9781573441872): Vin Packer: Books]. Amazon.com. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.msvu.ca/en/home/library/aboutthelibrary/policiesprocedures/collectionpolicy/lesbianpulpfictioncollection.aspx Lesbian Pulp Fiction Collection]. Msvu.ca (20 November 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> It was written by lesbian [[Marijane Meaker]] under the false name Vin Packer.<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 In the spring of 1952, Dale Jennings was arrested in Los Angeles for allegedly soliciting a police officer in a bathroom in Westlake Park, now known as [[MacArthur Park]]. His trial drew national attention to the Mattachine Society, and membership increased drastically after Jennings contested the charges, resulting in a hung jury.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Vern L. Bullough, RN|title=Before Stonewall, Activists for Gay and Lesbian Rights in Historical Context|origyear=2002|publisher=Harrington Park Press|location=New York|isbn=1-56023-192-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/424 424]|year=2002|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/424}}</ref>\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Christine Jorgensen]] becomes the first widely publicized person to have undergone [[sex reassignment surgery]], in this case, [[transwoman|male to female]], creating a world-wide sensation.\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 In Japan the male homosexual magazine \"[[:ja:\u30a2\u30c9\u30cb\u30b9\u4f1a|Adonis]]\" is launched with the writer [[Yukio Mishima]] as a contributor.\n* '''1953'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Diana Foundation was founded on 19 March 1953 in Houston, TX by a small group of friends. The Diana Foundation is a nonprofit organization and recognized as the oldest continuously active gay organization in the United States and hosts two annual fundraising events including its Diana Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.TheDianaFoundation.org|title=Diana Foundation - Home Page|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418010940/http://www.thedianafoundation.org/|archivedate=18 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''1954'''&nbsp;\u2013 7 June\u2013Mathematical and computer [[genius]] [[Alan Turing]] commits [[suicide]] by [[cyanide]] poisoning, 18 months after being given a choice between two years in prison or libido-reducing hormone treatment for a year as a punishment for homosexuality.<ref name=\"ahodg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.turing.org.uk/bio/part8.html|title=A short on-line biography in eight parts: Part 8&nbsp;\u2014 Alan Turing's Crisis|last=Hodges|first=Andrew|date=1995|work=ALAN TURING founder of computer science|publisher=Andrew Hodges|accessdate=24 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091016020632/http%3A//www.turing.org.uk/bio/part8.html|archivedate=16 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A succession of well-known men, including [[Edward Douglas-Scott-Montagu, 3rd Baron Montagu of Beaulieu|Lord Montagu]], [[Michael Pitt-Rivers]] and [[Peter Wildeblood]], were convicted of [[homosexual]] offences as British police pursued a [[McCarthyism|McCarthy-like]] purge of [[High society (social class)|Society]] homosexuals.<ref>{{cite news|author=Adam Mars-Jones |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/jul/14/against-the-law-the-wildeblood-scandal-the-case-that-rocked-1950s-britain-and-changed-gay-rights |title=The Wildeblood scandal: the trial that rocked 1950s Britain \u2013 and changed gay rights &#124; Books |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref> Arcadie, the first homosexual group in France, is formed.\n* '''1955'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Daughters of Bilitis]] (DOB) was founded in San Francisco by four lesbian couples (including [[Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon]]) and was the first national lesbian political and social organization in the United States.<ref name=\"glbtq1\">[http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/daughters_bilitis.html Daughters of Bilitis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629110236/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/daughters_bilitis.html |date=29 June 2011 }}. glbtq (20 October 2005). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> The group's name came from \"Songs of Bilitis,\" a lesbian-themed song cycle by French poet Pierre Lou\u00ffs, which described the fictional Bilitis as a resident of the Isle of Lesbos alongside Sappho.<ref name=\"glbtq1\"/> DOB's activities included hosting public forums on homosexuality, offering support to isolated, married, and mothering lesbians, and participating in research activities.<ref name=\"glbtq1\"/> Mattachine Society [[New York City|New York]] chapter founded.\n* '''1956'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Ladder (magazine)|The Ladder]]'', the first nationally distributed lesbian publication in the United States, began publication.\n* '''1956'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Thailand]] decriminalizes homosexual acts.\n* '''1956'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Florida Legislative Investigation Committee]] (commonly known as the Johns Committee) established. Failing to find communist ties to civil rights organizations, it investigates homosexuals as a threat to national security.\n* '''1957'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word \"[[Transsexual]]\" is coined by U.S. physician [[Harry Benjamin]]; The [[Wolfenden report|Wolfenden Committee's]] report recommends decriminalizing consensual homosexual behaviour between adults in the United Kingdom; Psychologist [[Evelyn Hooker]] publishes a study showing that homosexual men are as well adjusted as non-homosexual men, which becomes a major factor in the [[American Psychiatric Association]] removing homosexuality from its handbook of disorders in 1973. Homoerotic artist [[Tom of Finland]] first published on the cover of ''[[Physique Pictorial]]'' magazine from Los Angeles.<ref>Hooven III, F. Valentine (2012). ''TOM OF FINLAND LIFE AND WORK OF A GAY HERO''. Berlin: Bruno Gm\u00fcnder Verlag GmbH. pp. 101-102. {{ISBN|978-3-86787-166-2}}.</ref>\n* '''1958'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Homosexual Law Reform Society]] is founded in the United Kingdom; [[Barbara Gittings]] founds the New York chapter of Daughters of Bilitis.\n* '''1958'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[One, Inc. v. Olesen]]'', 355 U.S. 371 (1958), was the first U.S. Supreme Court ruling to deal with homosexuality and the first to address free speech rights with respect to homosexuality. The Supreme Court reversed a lower court ruling that the gay magazine ''[[ONE magazine]]'' violated obscenity laws, thus upholding constitutional protection for pro-homosexual writing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/19/us/legal-history-lgbtq-rights-timeline.html|title=The Court Cases That Changed L.G.B.T.Q. Rights|last=Geidner|first=Chris|date=2019-06-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n* '''1958'''&nbsp;-  The first gay leather bar in the United States, the Gold Coast, opened in Chicago in 1958. It was founded by [[Dom Orejudos]] and [[Chuck Renslow]].\n* '''1959'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], at the time the UK's only national commercial broadcaster, broadcasts the UK\u2019s first TV gay drama, ''South'', starring [[Peter Wyngarde]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Brown, arts correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/mar/16/itv-play-gay-television |title=Newly unearthed ITV play could be first ever gay television drama |work=guardian.co.uk |accessdate=19 April 2013 |location=London |date=16 March 2013}}</ref> The first homosexual uprising in the USA occurs at Cooper's Doughnuts in Los Angeles, USA; rioters were arrested by [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]].<ref>Faderman, Lillian and Timmons, Stuart (2006). ''Gay L.A.: A History of Sexual Outlaws, Power Politics, and Lipstick Lesbians''. Basic Books. p. 1-2. {{ISBN|0-465-02288-X}}.</ref>\n\n==1960s==\n\n* '''1960'''&nbsp;\u2013 Cpls. Fannie Mae Clackum and Grace Garner, U.S. Air Force reservists in the late 1940s and early 1950s, became the first people to successfully challenge their discharges from the U.S. military for being gay, although the ruling turned on the fact that there wasn't enough evidence to show the women were lesbians.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.queerty.com/born-on-the-4th-of-july-12-american-lgbt-war-heroes-20130703/#ixzz2YfVXzqn5 |title=Born On The 4th Of July: 12 American LGBT War Heroes / Queerty |publisher=Queerty.com |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902002347/http://www.queerty.com/born-on-the-4th-of-july-12-american-lgbt-war-heroes-20130703/#ixzz2YfVXzqn5 |archivedate=2 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to scholars, since at least as early as 1960, [[Executive Order 10450]] was applied to ban transgender individuals from serving in the United States military.<ref>[https://www.outserve-sldn.org/about-us/ Our History]</ref>\n* '''1961'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Hungarian People's Republic|Hungary]] decriminalizes sodomy; ''[[Victim (1961 film)|Victim]]'' is the first English-language film to use the word \"homosexual\", and premieres in the UK on 31 August 1961; the [[Holy See|Vatican]] declares that anyone who is \"affected by the perverse inclination\" towards homosexuality should not be allowed to take religious vows or be ordained within the [[Roman Catholic Church]]; ''[[The Rejected]]'', the first [[documentary]] on homosexuality broadcast on American television, is first broadcast on [[KQED (TV)|KQED]] TV in [[San Francisco]] on 11 September 1961; [[Jos\u00e9 Sarria]] becomes the first openly gay candidate for public office in the United States when he runs for the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]].<ref>Miller, p. 347</ref>\n* '''1962'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Illinois]] becomes the first [[U.S. state]] to remove sodomy law from its criminal code through passage of the American Law Institute's [[Model Penal Code]]. While the adopted code did not penalize private sexual relations, it criminalized acts of \"Open Lewdness;\"<ref>1961 Ill. Laws 2044.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Schwartz | first = Louis B.  | title = Morals Offenses and the Model Penal Code | journal = Columbia Law Review | volume = 63 | issue = 4 | pages = 669\u2013686 | date = April 1963 | doi=10.2307/1120582 | jstor=1120582}}</ref> [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]] decriminalizes sodomy. The [[Tavern Guild]], the first gay business association in the United States, was created by gay bar owners in 1962 as a response to continued police harassment and closing of gay bars (including the [[Tay-Bush Inn raid]]), and continued until 1995.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bullough|first=Vern L.|title=Before Stonewall: d Activists for Gay and Lesbian Rights in Historical Context|publisher=Haworth Press|location=New York|date=2002|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/157 157]|isbn=978-1-56023-193-6|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/157}}</ref>\n* '''1963'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Eastern Regional Conference of Homophile Organizations|East Coast Homophile Organizations]] (ECHO) is established in Philadelphia; initial members include the regional chapters of [[Daughters of Bilitis]], [[Janus Society]], and [[Mattachine Society]].\n* '''1963'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Israel]] de facto decriminalizes sodomy and sexual acts between men by judicial decision against the enforcement of the relevant section in the old British-mandate law from 1936 (which in fact was never enforced).{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Canada]] sees its first gay-positive organization, ASK, and first gay magazines: ''ASK Newsletter'' (in [[Vancouver]]), and ''[[Gay (magazine)|Gay]]'' (by Gay Publishing Company of [[Toronto]]). ''Gay'' was the first periodical to use the term 'Gay' in the title and expanded quickly, including outstripping the distribution of American publications under the name ''Gay International''. These were quickly followed by ''Two'' (by Gayboy (later Kamp) Publishing Company of Toronto).<ref name=McLeodHistoryofGay>{{cite book |last=McLeod |first=Donald W. |title=A Brief History of Gay: Canada's First Gay Tabloid, 1964\u20131966}}</ref><ref name=GayArchivist>{{cite journal |title=Our Silver Anniversary: Canadians have been organizing for twenty five years! |journal=Newsletter of the Canadian Gay Archives |volume=7 |publisher=National Archives for Lesbians and Gay Men |date=June 1989}}</ref>\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Canada]]: In March 1964, Ted Northe founds the 'Imperial Court of Canada' a monarchist society compromised primarily of drag personalities and becomes a driving force in the effort to achieve equality in Canada.  The Courts of Canada now have over 14 chapters across the country and is the oldest, continuously running, LGBT Organization in Canada.\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first photograph of lesbians on the cover of lesbian magazine ''[[The Ladder (magazine)|The Ladder]]'' was done in September 1964, showing two women from the back, on a beach looking out to sea.\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013  The June 1964 Paul Welch ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' article entitled \"Homosexuality In America\" was the first time a national publication reported on gay issues.\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013  Created in 1964, the [[Council on Religion and the Homosexual]] was the first group in the U.S. to use the word \"homosexual\" in its name. \n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Council on Religion and the Homosexual]] held an event where local politicians could be questioned about issues concerning gay and lesbian people, including police intimidation. The event marks the first known instance of \"the gay vote\" being sought.\n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[George Klippert|Everett George Klippert]], the last person imprisoned in Canada for homosexuality, is arrested for private, consensual sex with men. After being assessed \"incurably homosexual\", he is sentenced to an indefinite \"preventive detention\" as a dangerous [[sexual offender]]. This was considered by many Canadians to be extremely homophobic, and prompted sympathetic articles in ''[[Maclean's]]'' and ''[[The Toronto Star]]'', eventually leading to increased calls for [[Criminal Law Amendment Act, 1968\u201369|legal reform]] in Canada which passed in 1969.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man imprisoned for being gay to get posthumous pardon from Trudeau|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/man-imprisoned-for-being-gay-to-get-posthumous-pardon-from-trudeau-1.3468287|accessdate=29 February 2016|newspaper=CBC News|date=28 February 2016}}</ref> \n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013 Conservatively dressed gays and lesbians demonstrate outside Independence Hall in Philadelphia on 4 July 1965. This was the first in a series of [[Annual Reminder]]s that took place through 1969.\n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013  Vanguard, an organization of LGBT youth in the low-income [[Tenderloin, San Francisco|Tenderloin]] district, was created in 1965. It is considered the first [[Gay Liberation]] organization in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.foundsf.org/index.php?title=1966_Vanguard_Sweep | title=1966 Vanguard Sweep - FoundSF}}</ref><ref>[http://www.glbthistory.org/Vanguard/images%20vanguard/vanguard-lowres.pdf ]{{dead link|date=May 2019}}</ref>\n* '''1966'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Mattachine Society stages a \"Sip-In\" at [[Julius (restaurant)|Julius Bar]] in New York City challenging a New York State Liquor Authority prohibiting serving alcohol to gays; the National Planning Conference of Homophile Organizations is established (to become NACHO\u2014[[North American Conference of Homophile Organizations]] later that year); the [[Compton's Cafeteria Riot]] occurred in August 1966 by transgender women and Vanguard members in the [[Tenderloin, San Francisco, California|Tenderloin]] district of San Francisco. This incident was one of the first recorded [[transgender]] riots in United States history, preceding the more famous 1969 [[Stonewall Riots]] in New York City by three years. Vanguard was founded to demonstrate for equal rights. The first lesbian to appear on the cover of the lesbian magazine ''The Ladder'' with her face showing was [[Lilli Vincenz]] in January 1966. A coalition of Homosexual organizations organized demonstrations for [[Armed Forces Day (United States)|Armed Forces Day]] to protest the exclusion of LGBT from the U.S. armed services. The Los Angeles group held a 15-car motorcade, which has been identified as the nation's first gay pride parade.<ref name=\"Faderman 2006\">Faderman, Lillian and Timmons, Stuart (2006). ''Gay L.A.: A History of Sexual Outlaws, Power Politics, and Lipstick Lesbians''. Basic Books. {{ISBN|0-465-02288-X}}.</ref> The National Transsexual Counseling Unit is created, becoming the first transgender organization ever and first American transgender organization ever.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_f9KDwAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA177#v=onepage&q&f=false Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender Americans at Risk: Problems and ... edited by Chuck Stewart]</ref> The [[Society for Individual Rights]] opened America\u2019s first gay and lesbian community center. \n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Black Cat Tavern in the Silver Lake neighborhood of Los Angeles is raided on New Year's Day by 12 plainclothes police officers who beat and arrested employees and patrons. The raid prompted a series of protests that began on 5 January 1967, organized by P.R.I.D.E. (Personal Rights in Defense and Education). It's the first use of the term \"Pride\" that came to be associated with LGBT rights.\n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' was first published in September as \"The Los Angeles Advocate,\" a local newsletter alerting gay men to police raids in Los Angeles gay bars.\n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Sexual Offences Act 1967]] decriminalised homosexual acts between two men over 21 years of age ''in private'' in [[England]] and [[Wales]].;<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/02/tories-out-in-force-gay-pride \"From Section 28 to a Home Office float - Tories come out in force at gay march\"], ''The Guardian'', London, 3 July 2010.</ref> The act did not apply to [[Scotland]], [[Northern Ireland]] nor the [[Channel Islands]]; The book ''Homosexual Behavior Among Males'' by Wainwright Churchill breaks ground as a scientific study approaching homosexuality as a fact of life and introduces the term \"homoerotophobia\", a possible precursor to \"homophobia\"; The [[Oscar Wilde Bookshop]], the world's first homosexual-oriented bookstore, opens in New York City; A raid on the [[Black Cat Tavern]] in [[Los Angeles, California]] promotes homosexual rights activity. The Student Homophile League at Columbia University is the first institutionally recognized gay student group in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013Grupo Nuestro Mundo (English: \"Our World Group\") is formed in [[Greater Buenos Aires]], the first gay rights organization in [[Argentina]] and [[Latin America]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Perlongher|first=N\u00e9stor|language=Spanish|publisher=Colihue|title=Prosa plebeya Ensayos 1980-1992|year= 1997|isbn=9505811918|page=262|location=Buenos Aires|series=Pu\u00f1aladas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cultura.gob.ar/orgullosos-de-la-diversidad-conoce-la-historia-de-la-marcha-del-orgullo-lgbtiq-en-argentina_6807/|language=Spanish|title=Historia de la Marcha del Orgullo en Argentina|date=November 15, 2018|accessdate=April 16, 2019|publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (Argentina)|Secretariat of Culture]]|location=Argentina}}</ref> ''[[The Homosexuals (CBS Reports)|The Homosexuals]]'', a 1967 episode of the documentary television series CBS Reports, was the first network documentary dealing with the topic of homosexuality. \n* '''1968'''&nbsp;\u2013 Paragraph 175 is eased in East Germany decriminalizing homosexual acts over the age of 18; [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] decriminalizes adult homosexual relations. In Los Angeles, following the arrest of two patrons in a raid, The Patch owner Lee Glaze organized the other patrons to move on the police station. After buying out a nearby flower shop, the demonstrators caravanned to the station, festooned it with the flowers and bailed out the arrested men.<ref name=\"Faderman 2006\"/> According to the online encyclopedia [[glbtq.com]], \"In the aftermath of the riot at [[Compton's Cafeteria Riot|Compton's]], a network of transgender social, psychological, and medical support services was established, which culminated in 1968 with the creation of the National Transsexual Counseling Unit [NTCU], the first such peer-run support and advocacy organization in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/san_francisco,2.html |title=Social sciences - San Francisco |publisher=glbtq |accessdate=2012-05-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705201921/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/san_francisco%2C2.html |archivedate=2015-07-05 }}</ref>\n* '''1969'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Stonewall riots]] occur in [[New York City]]; [[Paragraph 175]] is eased in [[West Germany]]; [[Bill C-150]] is passed, decriminalizing homosexuality in [[Canada]]. [[Pierre Trudeau]], the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], is quoted as having said: \"The state has no place in the bedrooms of the nation.\"; [[People's Republic of Poland|Poland]] decriminalizes homosexual [[prostitution]]; An [[Australia]]n arm of the [[Daughters of Bilitis]] forms in [[Melbourne]] and is considered Australia's first homosexual rights organisation.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The [[Gay Liberation Front]] is formed in America, and it is the first gay organization to use \"gay\" in its name. On 31 December 1969, the [[Cockettes]] perform for the first time at the Palace Theatre on Union and Columbus in the [[North Beach, San Francisco|North Beach]] neighborhood of San Francisco.\n\n==1970s==\n\n* '''1970'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first Gay Liberation Day March is held in New York City; The first LGBT Pride Parade is held in New York; The first \"Gay-in\" held in San Francisco; [[Carl Wittman]] writes ''A Gay Manifesto'';<ref name=\"cwittman\">{{cite web|url=http://library.gayhomeland.org/0006/EN/A_Gay_Manifesto.htm|title=A Gay Manifesto (1970)|last=Wittman|first=Carl|year=1970|publisher=Gay Homeland Foundation|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Blasius|first=Mark|author2=Shane Phelan |title=We are everywhere: a historical sourcebook in gay and lesbian politics|year=1997|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-90859-0|pages=380\u201390}}</ref> CAMP (Campaign Against Moral Persecution) is formed in [[Australia]];<ref name=\"dc.identifier.TSID 2964\">{{cite web|url=http://heuristscholar.org/cocoon/dos/browser/item/422/ |title=Lesbians |last=Jennings |first=Rebecca |date=21 October 2008 |publisher=Dictionary of Sydney |accessdate=28 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726150518/http://heuristscholar.org/cocoon/dos/browser/item/422/ |archivedate=26 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Willett|first=Graham |title=Living out loud: a history of gay and lesbian activism in Australia|year=2000|publisher=Allen & Unwin|page=33}}</ref> The Task Force on Gay Liberation formed within the [[American Library Association]]. Now known as the [[Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, and Transgender Round Table|GLBT Round Table]], this organization is the oldest LGBTQ professional organization in the United States.<ref name=\"keilty\">{{cite journal|last=Keilty|first=Patrick|title=Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Information Needs|journal=Encyclopedia of Library and Information Science, 3rd Edition|year=2009|pages=3275\u20133280|doi=10.1081/E-ELIS3-120044121|isbn=978-0-8493-9712-7}}</ref> In November, the first gay rights march occurs in the UK at Highbury Fields following the arrest of an activist from the Young Liberals for importuning.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mHAe63jpuOQC&pg=PA229&dq \"Sexual Politics: Sexuality, Family Planning, and the British Left from the 1880s to the Present Day\"], Stephen Brooke. OUP Oxford, 24 Nov 2011. p. 229. Retrieved 4 Feb 2017</ref>\n* '''1971'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Society Five]] (a homosexual rights organization) is formed in [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]], Australia; Homosexuality is decriminalized in [[Austria]], [[Costa Rica]] and [[Finland]]; [[Colorado]] and [[Oregon]] repeal sodomy laws; [[Idaho]] repeals the sodomy law&nbsp;\u2014 Then re-instates the repealed sodomy law because of outrage among [[Mormons]] and [[Catholics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/getequal/gettingrid.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929133832/http://www.aclu.org/getequal/gettingrid.html|archivedate=2007-09-29|title=Getting Rid of Sodomy Laws: History and Strategy that Led to the Lawrence Decision|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glapn.org/sodomylaws/usa/idaho/idaho.htm|title=Sodomy Laws, Idaho|accessdate=6 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109200305/http://www.glapn.org/sodomylaws/usa/idaho/idaho.htm|archivedate=9 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Netherlands changes the homosexual age of consent to 16, the same as the straight age of consent; The U.S. [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] calls for the repeal of all [[victimless crime]] laws, including the sodomy laws; Dr. [[Franklin E. Kameny|Frank Kameny]] becomes the first openly gay candidate for the [[United States Congress]]; The [[University of Michigan]] establishes the first collegiate LGBT programs office, then known as the \"Gay Advocate's Office.\" The UK [[Gay Liberation Front]] (GLF) was recognized as a political movement in the national press and was holding weekly meetings of 200 to 300 people.;<ref>{{cite news|title=An Alternative to Sexual Shame: Impact of the new militancy among homosexual groups|newspaper=The Times|author=Victoria Brittain|date=28 August 1971|page=12}}</ref> [[George Klippert]], the last man jailed for homosexuality in Canada, is released from prison. [[:ja:\u6771\u90f7\u5065|Ken Togo]] ran for national election, in [[Japan]]. During a UCLA conference called \"The Homosexual in America,\" [[Betty Berzon]] became the first psychotherapist in the country to come out as gay to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=561|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online - Pioneering activist Betty Berzon dies|work=Bay Area Reporter|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> ''[[Boys in the Sand]]'' was the first gay porn film to include credits, to achieve crossover success, to be reviewed by ''Variety'',<ref>Jeffrey Escoffier, \"Beefcake to Hardcore: Gay Pornography and the Sexual Revolution,\" in ''Sex Scene. Media and the Sexual Revolution'', ed. Eric Schaefer, Duke University Press, 2014, {{ISBN|9780822356424}}, pp. 319-347, at p. 319.</ref> and one of the earliest porn films, after 1969's ''[[Blue Movie]]''<ref name=\"NYT-19690722\">{{cite news |last=Canby |first=Vincent |authorlink=Vincent Canby |title=Movie Review - Blue Movie (1968) Screen: Andy Warhol's 'Blue Movie' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9507E5D91738E63ABC4A51DFB1668382679EDE |date=22 July 1969 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-19690810\">{{cite news |last=Canby |first=Vincent |authorlink=Vincent Canby |title=Warhol's Red Hot and 'Blue' Movie. D1. Print. (behind paywall) |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9807E4D91739EF3BBC4852DFBE668382679EDE |date=10 August 1969 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"WS-1969\">{{cite web |last=Comenas |first=Gary |title=July 21, 1969: Andy Warhol's Blue Movie Opens |url=http://www.warholstars.org/andy-warhol-1969.html |date=1969 |work=WarholStars.org |accessdate=20 January 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"JW-2015\">{{cite book |last=Haggerty |first=George E. |title=A Companion to Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Studies |url=https://books.google.com/?id=eUf3CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA339&lpg=PA339&dq=Variety+June+18,+1969+%22Blue+Movie%22#v=onepage&q=Variety%20June%2018%2C%201969%20%22Blue%20Movie%22&f=false |date=2015 |work=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |page=339 |accessdate=20 January 2016 |isbn=9781119000853 }}</ref> by [[Andy Warhol]], to gain mainstream credibility, preceding 1972's ''[[Deep Throat (film)|Deep Throat]]'' by nearly a year. It was promoted with an advertising campaign unprecedented for a pornographic feature, premiered in [[New York City]] in 1971 and was an immediate critical and commercial success.<ref name=Wakefield>[http://www.therialtoreport.com/2013/06/16/wakefield-poole-theater-dance-and-pornpodcast-14/ 'Wakefield Poole: Theater, Dance, and Porn'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131043139/http://www.therialtoreport.com/2013/06/16/wakefield-poole-theater-dance-and-pornpodcast-14/ |date=31 January 2014 }}, [http://www.therialtoreport.com The Rialto Report], audio interview with Wakefield Poole</ref>  The [[Alice B. Toklas Democratic Club]], founded in San Francisco in 1971, was the first gay Democratic club of the United States. \n* '''1972'''&nbsp;\u2013 Sweden becomes the first country in the world to allow transsexuals to legally change their sex, and provides free hormone therapy;<ref name=quistbergh2001>{{cite web |url=http://www.quistbergh.se/view/514 |language=Swedish |title=Jag k\u00e4nner mig lite homosexuell idag |trans-title=I feel a bit gay today |accessdate=12 December 2009 |year=2001 |first=Frederick Quist |last=Bergh}}</ref> Hawaii legalizes homosexuality; In [[South Australia]], a consenting adults in private-type legal defence was introduced; [[Norway]] decriminalizes homosexuality; [[East Lansing, Michigan]] and [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] and San Francisco, California become the first cities in United States to pass a homosexual rights ordinance. [[Jim Foster (activist)|Jim Foster]], San Francisco and [[Madeline Davis]], [[Buffalo, New York]], first openly gay and lesbian delegates to the Democratic Convention, Miami, McGovern; give the first speeches advocating a gay rights plank in the Democratic Party Platform. \"Stonewall Nation\", the first gay anthem is written and recorded by Madeline Davis and is produced on 45 rpm record by the Mattachine Society of the [[Niagara Frontier]]. Lesbianism 101, the first lesbianism course in the U.S., is taught at the University of Buffalo by Margaret Small and Madeline Davis. Queens, NY schoolteacher Jeanne Manford marched with her gay son, gay rights activist Morty Manford, in New York's Christopher Street Liberation Day march. This was the origin of the straight ally movement and of [[PFLAG]] - (originally Parents of Gays, then Parents, Families and Friends of Lesbians and Gays, now simply PFLAG.)<ref name=\"pflag1973\">{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=267 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=community.pflag.org |date=26 March 1973 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617013027/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=267 |archivedate=17 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Nancy Wechsler became the first openly gay or lesbian person in political office in America; she was elected to the Ann Arbor City Council in 1972 as a member of the Human Rights Party and came out as a lesbian during her first and only term there.<ref>[http://www.equalitygiving.org/Gay-Politicians Gay Politicians]. eQualityGiving. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Also in 1972, Camille Mitchell became the first open lesbian to be awarded custody of her children in a divorce case, although the judge restricted the arrangement by precluding Ms. Mitchell's lover from moving in with her and the children.<ref name=\"glinn.com\">[http://www.glinn.com/news/tline3.htm GLINN's Timeline of Gay and Lesbian Family Issues]. Glinn.com. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Freda Smith became the first openly lesbian minister in the Metropolitan Community Church (she was also their first female minister).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodhopemcc.org/about-us/general/denomination.html |title=Denomination - Good Hope MCC, Cape Town, South Africa |publisher=goodhopemcc.org |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/metro_comm_church.html |title=Metropolitan Community Church |publisher=glbtq.com |date=6 October 1968 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524234619/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/metro_comm_church.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Beth Chayim Chadashim]] was founded in 1972 as the first LGBT synagogue in the world, and the first LGBT synagogue recognized by the [[Union for Reform Judaism]].<ref name=\"laconservancy1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.laconservancy.org/locations/beth-chayim-chadashim |title=Beth Chayim Chadashim &#124; Los Angeles Conservancy |publisher=Laconservancy.org |date= |accessdate=2017-08-24}}</ref> A [[Quaker]] group, the Committee of Friends on Bisexuality, issued the \"Ithaca Statement on Bisexuality\" supporting bisexuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bimedia.org/1984/june-1972-the-ithaca-statement/ |title=BiMedia &#124; Bisexual News & Opinion from |publisher=BiMedia.org |date=2012-02-10 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> The Statement, which may have been \"the first public declaration of the bisexual movement\" and \"was certainly the first statement on bisexuality issued by an American religious assembly,\" appeared in the Quaker ''[[Friends Journal]]'' and ''The Advocate'' in 1972.<ref name=donaldson>{{Cite book | last = Donaldson | first = Stephen | year = 1995 | contribution = The Bisexual Movement's Beginnings in the 70s: A Personal Retrospective | pages = [https://archive.org/details/bisexualpolitics00tuck/page/31 31\u201345] | editor-last = Tucker | editor-first = Naomi | title = Bisexual Politics: Theories, Queries, & Visions | place = New York | publisher = Harrington Park Press | isbn = 1-56023-869-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/bisexualpolitics00tuck/page/31 }}</ref><ref name=highleyman>{{cite news\n  |url=http://www.camprehoboth.com/issue07_11_03/pastout.htm\n  |title=PAST Out: What is the history of the bisexual movement?\n  |accessdate=2008-03-18\n  |last=Highleyman\n  |first=Liz\n  |date=2003-07-11\n  |work=LETTERS From CAMP Rehoboth\n  |volume=13\n  |number=8\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080531051440/http://www.camprehoboth.com/issue07_11_03/pastout.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Martin|first=Robert|title=Quakers 'come out' at conference|journal=The Advocate|date=1972-08-02|issue=91|page=8}}</ref> Today Quakers have varying opinions on [[LGBT]] people and rights, with some Quaker groups more accepting than others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org/resources/entry/stances-of-faiths-on-lgbt-issues-religious-society-of-friends-quakers |title=Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: Religious Society of Friends (Quakers) &#124; Resources &#124; Human Rights Campaign |publisher=Hrc.org |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> The first gay bar in San Francisco to have clear windows was Twin Peaks Tavern, which removed its blacked-out windows in 1972.\n* '''1973'''&nbsp;\u2013 On 15 October the Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatry Federal Council declares homosexuality not an illness \u2013 the first such body in the world to do so; in December the American Psychiatric Association removes homosexuality from its [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] (DSM-II), based largely on the research and advocacy of Evelyn Hooker. The first formal meeting of [[PFLAG]] took place on 26 March 1973 at the Metropolitan-Duane Methodist Church in Greenwich Village (now the Church of the Village). Approximately 20 people attended, including founder Jeanne Manford, her husband Jules, son Morty, Dick and Amy Ashworth, [[Metropolitan Community Church]] founder Reverend Troy Perry, and more.<ref name=\"pflag1973\"/> [[Malta]] legalizes homosexuality; In West Germany, the age of consent is reduced for homosexuals to 18 (though it is 14 for heterosexuals).{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}; [[Sally Miller Gearhart]] became the first open lesbian to obtain a tenure-track faculty position when she was hired by San Francisco State University, where she helped establish one of the first women and gender study programs in the country.<ref>[http://giving.uoregon.edu/oregon-outlook/summer-2009/honoring-diversity-and-courage Honoring diversity and courage]. giving.uoregon.edu. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> [[Lavender Country]], an [[United States|American]] [[country music]] band, released a self-titled album which is the first known [[gay]]-themed album in country music history.<ref name=\"Dickinson\">{{cite journal |last= Dickinson |first= Chris |year= 2000 |title= Country Undetectable: Gay Artists in Country Music |journal= Journal of Country Music |volume= XXI |issue= 1 |pages= 28\u201339 |url= http://www.queermusicheritage.us/mar2005jcm.html |accessdate= 4 August 2009}}</ref>\n* '''1974'''&nbsp;\u2013 Chile allows a trans person to legally change her name and gender on the birth certificate  after undergoing sex reassignment surgery, becoming the second country in the world to do so.<ref>{{cite web |title=La revoluci\u00f3n de Marcia Alejandra |url=https://www.latercera.com/tendencias/noticia/la-revolucion-marcia-alejandra/132019/ |website=La Tercera |accessdate=25 November 2018 |language=es-ES |date=13 April 2018}}</ref> [[Kathy Kozachenko]] becomes the first openly gay American elected to public office when she wins a seat on the [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] city council; In New York City [[Fritz Klein (sex researcher)|Dr. Fritz Klein]] founds the Bisexual Forum, the first [[support group]] for the [[Bisexual Community]]; [[Elaine Noble]] becomes the second openly gay American elected to public office when she wins a seat in the [[Massachusetts State House]]; Inspired by Noble, [[Minnesota]] state legislator [[Allan Spear]] comes out in a newspaper interview; [[Ohio]] repeals sodomy laws. [[Robert Grant (Christian Leader)|Robert Grant]] founds American Christian Cause to oppose the \"[[gay agenda]]\", the beginning of modern Christian politics in America. In London, the first openly [[London Lesbian and Gay Switchboard|LGBT telephone help line]] opens, followed one year later by the Brighton Lesbian and Gay Switchboard;{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} the [[Brunswick Four]] are arrested on 5 January 1974, in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]. This incident of [[Lesbophobia]] galvanizes the Toronto Lesbian and Gay community;<ref>Warner, Tom. \u2018\u2019Never Going Back: A History of Queer Activism in Canada\u2019\u2019, 2002 University of Toronto Press, {{ISBN|0-8020-8460-5}} p41</ref> the [[National Socialist League (United States)|National Socialist League]] (The ''Gay Nazi Party'') is founded in [[Los Angeles, California]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} The first openly gay or lesbian person to be elected to any political office in America was [[Kathy Kozachenko]], who was elected to the Ann Arbor City Council in April 1974.<ref>[http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials.html >> social sciences >> Elected Officials] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022195646/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials.html |date=22 October 2009 }}. glbtq. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Also in 1974, the [[Lesbian Herstory Archives]] opened to the public in the New York apartment of lesbian couple [[Joan Nestle]] and Deborah Edel; it has the world's largest collection of materials by and about lesbians and their communities.<ref>[http://www.lesbianherstoryarchives.org/ The Lesbian Herstory Archives]. The Lesbian Herstory Archives. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Also in 1974, [[Angela Morley]] became the first openly transgender person to be nominated for an [[Academy Award]], when she was nominated for one in the category of Best Music, Original Song Score/Adaptation for ''The Little Prince'' (1974), a nomination shared with [[Alan Jay Lerner]], [[Frederick Loewe]], and [[Douglas Gamley]]. The world's first gay softball league was formed in San Francisco in 1974 as the Community Softball League, which eventually included both women's and men's teams. The teams, usually sponsored by gay bars,  competed against each other and against the San Francisco Police softball team.<ref>[http://thecastro.net/street/softball/softballpage.html Uncle Donald's Castro Street] Retrieved December 23, 2016\n</ref>\n* '''1975'''&nbsp;\u2013 Twelve women became the first group of women in Japan to publicly identify as lesbians, publishing one issue of a magazine called Subarashi Onna (Wonderful Women).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/pajx3m/lesbian-history-archive-artifacts |title=The First Lesbian Porn and 10 Other Revealing Artifacts from Lesbian History |publisher=VICE |date= |accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref> Homosexuality is legalized in [[California]] due to the [[Consenting Adult Sex Bill]], authored by and successfully lobbied for in the state legislature by State Assemblyman from San Francisco [[Willie Brown (politician)|Willie Brown]]; [[Leonard Matlovich]], a Technical Sergeant in the United States Air Force, becomes the first U.S. gay service member to purposely out himself to fight their ban; South Australia becomes the first state in Australia to make homosexuality legal between consenting adults in private. Panama is the third country in the world to allow transsexuals who have gone through gender reassignment surgery to get their personal documents reflecting their new sex; {{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}  UK journal [[Gay Left]] begins publication;<ref>[http://knittingcircle.org.uk/gayleftcollective.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070114112010/http://knittingcircle.org.uk/gayleftcollective.html|date=14 January 2007}}</ref> [[Minneapolis]] becomes the first city in the United States to pass trans-inclusive civil rights protection legislation;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/transgender_activism.html |title=Transgender Activism |publisher=glbtq.com |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525105458/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/transgender_activism.html |archivedate=25 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Clela Rorex, a clerk in Boulder County, Colorado, issues the first same-sex marriage licenses in the United States, issuing the very first of them to Dave McCord and Dave Zamora, on 26 March 1975.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.elephantjournal.com/2009/02/gregory-hinton-for-daily-camera-march-26-1975-the-first-same-sex-marriage-licenses-in-the-united-states-were-heroically-issued-in-boulder-by-county-clerk-clela-rorex/|title=March 26, 1975, the first same-sex marriage licenses in the United States were heroically issued in Boulder by County Clerk, Clela Rorex.|work=Elephant Journal|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> Six same-sex marriages were performed as a result of her giving out licenses, but all of the marriages were overturned later that year.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Maureen Colquhoun becomes the UK's first out lesbian MP after coming out in 1975. She is the UK's first openly gay MP.\n[[File:Gay Rights demonstration, NYC 1976.jpg|thumb|Gay rights protesters in New York City, protesting at the United States' [[1976 Democratic National Convention]]]]\n* '''1976'''&nbsp;\u2013 Robert Grant founds the [[Christian Voice (United States)|Christian Voice]] to take his anti-homosexual-rights crusade national in United States; the Homosexual Law Reform Coalition and the Gay Teachers Group are started in Australia; the [[Australian Capital Territory]] decriminalizes homosexuality between consenting adults in private and equalizes the age of consent; Out Minnesota state legislator [[Allan Spear]] is reelected; and Denmark equalizes the age of consent.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Association of homosexual liberation was founded in Japan.<ref name=\"boyfriend\">\u30aa\u30c8\u30b3\u30ce\u30b3\u306e\u305f\u3081\u306e\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30d5\u30ec\u30f3\u30c9 (1986)</ref> [[Tom Gallagher (diplomat)|Tom Gallagher]] became the first United States Foreign Service officer to come out as gay; he quit the Foreign Service after that, as  he would have been unable to obtain a security clearance.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\">{{cite news |last1=Genzlinger |first1=Neil |title=Tom Gallagher, Diplomat Who Became a Gay Activist, Dies At 77 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/12/obituaries/tom-gallagher-diplomat-who-became-a-gay-activist-dies-at-77.html |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=July 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"advocateobit\">{{cite news |last1=Ring |first1=Trudy |title=Tom Gallagher, First Foreign Service Officer to Come Out, Dies at 77 |url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/2018/7/13/tom-gallagher-first-foreign-service-officer-come-out-dies-77 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |work=The Advocate |date=July 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"washpostobit\">{{cite news |last1=Plokihii |first1=Olesia |title=Tom Gallagher, Foreign Service officer who quit to live as openly gay, dies at 77 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/tom-gallagher-foreign-service-officer-who-quit-to-live-as-openly-gay-dies-at-77/2018/07/20/e706be96-8b6f-11e8-a345-a1bf7847b375_story.html |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |work=The Washington Post |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Patricia Nell Warren]]'s  third novel, ''The Fancy Dancer'' (1976) was the first bestseller to portray a [[gay priest]] and to explore [[LGBT and rurality|gay life in a small town]].\n* '''1977'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Harvey Milk]] is elected city-county supervisor in San Francisco, becoming the first openly gay or lesbian candidate elected to political office in California, the seventh openly gay/lesbian elected official nationally, and the third man to be openly gay at time of his election. [[Dade County, Florida]] enacts a Human Rights Ordinance; it is repealed the same year after a militant anti-homosexual-rights campaign led by [[Anita Bryant]]. [[Quebec]] becomes the first jurisdiction larger than a city or county in the world to prohibit [[discrimination]] based on [[sexual orientation]] in the public and private sectors; [[Croatia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Slovenia]] and [[Vojvodina]] legalise homosexuality.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Welsh author [[Jeffrey Weeks (sociologist)|Jeffrey Weeks]] publishes ''Coming Out'';<ref>Coming Out: Homosexual Politics in Britain from the Nineteenth Century to the Present, Quartet Books 1977; 2nd revised edition, with new chapter and bibliography, 1990</ref> [[File:Gay flag 8.svg|thumb|Original eight-color version of the [[Rainbow flag (LGBT movement)|LGBT pride flag]]]] Publication of the first issue of [[Gaysweek]], NYC's first mainstream gay weekly. Police raided a house outside of Boston outraging the gay community. In response the Boston-Boise Committee was formed.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lib.neu.edu/archives/voices/gl_sexual2.htm | title = Gay Community Fights Back (1978) | accessdate = 26 August 2010 | work = We Raise Our Voices | publisher = Northeastern University | archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6611tUXn0?url=http://www.lib.neu.edu/archives/voices/gl_sexual2.htm | archive-date = 8 March 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Ann Holmes Redding|Anne Holmes]] became the first openly lesbian minister ordained by the United Church of Christ;<ref>Jack Rogers [https://books.google.com/books?id=MUAL7iZHVN4C&pg=PA139 Jesus, the Bible, and Homosexuality: Explode the Myths, Heal the Church], Westminster John Knox Press, 2009 {{ISBN|0-664-23397-X}} p. 139</ref> [[Ellen Barrett]] became the first openly lesbian priest ordained by the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church of the United States]] (serving the Diocese of New York).<ref>[http://www.integrityusa.org/FAQs/index.htm FAQs] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314234504/http://www.integrityusa.org/FAQs/index.htm |date=14 March 2012 }}. Integrityusa.org. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref><ref>David Hein, Gardiner H. Shattuck [https://books.google.com/books?id=_iK5VggudLkC&pg=PA143 The Episcopalians], Greenwood Publishing Group, 2004 {{ISBN|0313229589}} p. 143</ref> The first lesbian mystery novel in America was published; it was ''Angel Dance'', by Mary F. Beal.<ref>{{cite book|title=Angel Dance: A Classic Lesbian Thriller: Mary F. Beal: 9780895944177 |isbn = 0895944170}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Laughlin |first=Anne |url=http://www.afterellen.com/column/lifes-little-lesbian-mysteries-1 |title=Life's Little Lesbian Mysteries: The good ol' days |publisher=afterellen.com |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120722054207/http%3A%2F%2Fwww.afterellen.com%2Fcolumn%2Flifes-little-lesbian-mysteries-1 |archivedate=22 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The [[National Center for Lesbian Rights]] was founded. [[Shakuntala Devi]] published the first<ref>{{Cite journal | title=Globalizing queer? AIDS, homophobia and the politics of sexual identity in India | author=Subir K Kole | journal=Globalization and Health | doi=10.1186/1744-8603-3-8 | date=2007-07-11 | pmid=17623106 | volume=3 | page=8 | pmc=2018684 }}: \"The first academic book on Indian homosexuals appeared in 1977 (The World of Homosexuals) written by [[Shakuntala Devi]], the mathematics wunderkind who was internationally known as the human computer. This book treated homosexuality in a positive light and reviewed the socio-cultural and legal situation of homosexuality in India and contrasted that with the then gay liberation movement in USA.\"</ref> study of homosexuality in India.<ref name=\"worldoh\">{{Cite book | title=The World of Homosexuals | author=Shakuntala Devi | publisher=Vikas Publishing House | year=1977 | isbn=9780706904789 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=PBwbAAAAYAAJ }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | title=Homosexuality and Religion | author=Jeffrey S. Siker | publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group | year=2006 | isbn=9780313330889 | page=127 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=PUqn33H-uDYC&pg=PA127&dq=%22The+World+of+Homosexuals%22 }}: \"In her 1977 book, mathematician [[Shakuntala Devi]] interviewed...\"</ref> Platonica Club and Front Runners were founded in Japan.<ref name = \"boyfriend\" /> San Francisco hosted the world's first gay film festival in 1977.<ref>William Lipsky, Gay and Lesbian San Francisco, Arcadia Publishing, 2006</ref> [[Peter Adair]], Nancy Adair and other members of the Mariposa Film Group premiered the groundbreaking documentary on coming out, ''[[Word Is Out: Stories of Some of Our Lives]]'',  at the [[Castro Theater]] in 1977. The film was the first feature-length documentary on gay identity by gay and lesbian filmmakers.<ref name=\"summing\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/30/movies/homevideo/30kehr.html | title=New DVDs, 'Word is Out' and 'Meredith Monk'| newspaper=The New York Times| date=2010-05-28| last1=Kehr| first1=Dave}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Eg_4Eus1sE0C&pg=PA327 | title=Homosexuality Bibliography: 1976-1982. Second supplement| isbn=9780810817531| last1=Parker| first1=William| year=1985}}</ref> [[Beth Chayim Chadashim]] became the first LGBT synagogue to own its own building.<ref name=\"laconservancy1\"/> On March 26, 1977, [[Frank Kameny]] and a dozen other members of the gay and lesbian community, under the leadership of the then-[[National LGBTQ Task Force|National Gay Task Force]], briefed then-Public Liaison [[Midge Costanza]] on much-needed changes in federal laws and policies. This was the first time that gay rights were officially discussed at the White House.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.thetaskforce.org/press/releases/pr_kameny_101111|title = Task Force mourns the death of pioneering gay activist and founding board member Frank Kameny|publisher = National Gay and Lesbian Task Force|date = October 11, 2011|accessdate = July 9, 2014|quote = he and a dozen other members of our community briefed then-Public Liaison Midge Costanza|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141003172359/http://www.thetaskforce.org/press/releases/pr_kameny_101111|archivedate = October 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2010/03/24/lgbt-advocate-white-house-aide-costanza-dies|title = LGBT Advocate White House Aide Costanza Dies|publisher = Advocate.com|date = March 24, 2010|accessdate = July 9, 2014|quote = Costanza met with gay activists including Frank Kameny, Troy Perry, Elaine Noble, and Task Force co\u2013executive directors Bruce Voeller and Jean O'Leary.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140714214349/http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2010/03/24/lgbt-advocate-white-house-aide-costanza-dies|archive-date = July 14, 2014|url-status = live|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''1978'''&nbsp;\u2013 San Francisco Supervisor Harvey Milk and Mayor [[George Moscone]] are [[Moscone\u2013Milk assassinations|assassinated]] by former Supervisor [[Dan White]]; the first [[Sydney Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras]] is held, with 2000 people attending and 53 subsequently arrested and some seriously beaten by police. The [[rainbow flag (gay movement)|rainbow flag]] is first used as a symbol of gay pride; Sweden establishes a uniform age of consent. [[Samois]], the earliest known lesbian-feminist [[BDSM]] organization, is founded in San Francisco; well-known members of the group include [[Patrick Califia]] and [[Gayle Rubin]]; the group is among the very earliest advocates of what came to be known as [[sex-positive feminism]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}; The International Lesbian and Gay Association (ILGA) is established.<ref>[http://ilga.org/aboutilga.asp about ILGA] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422045221/http://ilga.org/aboutilga.asp |date=22 April 2009 }}</ref> Robin Tyler became the first out lesbian on U.S. national television, appearing on a Showtime comedy special hosted by [[Phyllis Diller]]. The same year she released her comedy album, ''Always a Bridesmaid, Never a Groom'', the first comedy album by an out lesbian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/tyler_r_ssh.html |title=Tyler, Robin |publisher=glbtq.com |date=8 April 1942 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010063902/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/tyler_r_ssh.html |archivedate=10 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> The [[San Francisco Lesbian/Gay Freedom Band]] was founded by Jon Reed Sims in 1978 as the San Francisco Gay Freedom Day Marching Band and Twirling Corp. Upon its founding in 1978, it became the first openly gay musical group in the world. San Francisco became the first city in America to have a recruitment drive for gay police officers, bringing in over 350 applications.<ref name=\"Evening Indy\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bgEMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=61gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6840,2315504|title=Homosexual Police Officers|last1=Cohen|first1=Susan|date=April 25, 1979|newspaper=The Evening Independent|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> Allen Bennett became the first openly gay rabbi in the United States.<ref name=\"Kaplan2005\">{{cite book|author=Dana Evan Kaplan|title=The Cambridge Companion to American Judaism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ntyKPd2-wUoC&pg=PA75|date=8 August 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-52951-8|pages=75\u2013}}</ref>\n* '''1979'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first national homosexual rights march on [[Washington, D.C.]] is held; The [[White Night riots]] occur, [[Harry Hay]] issues the first call for a [[Radical Faerie]] gathering in [[Arizona]], and The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence first appear in public on Easter Sunday in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesisters.org/sistory |title=Sistory |publisher=Thesisters.org |accessdate=2015-04-22}}</ref> [[Cuba]] and Spain decriminalize homosexuality.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} [[Esta Noche (gay bar)|Esta Noche]], a gay bar located at 3079 16th & Mission Street in San Francisco, was the first gay Latino bar in San Francisco, and first opened in 1979. A number of people in [[Sweden]] called in sick with a case of ''being homosexual,'' in protest of homosexuality being classified [[Homosexuality and psychology|as an illness]]. This was followed by an activist occupation of the main office of the ''[[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]]''. Within a few months, Sweden became the first country in the world to remove homosexuality as an illness.<ref name=quistbergh2001/> Japan Gay Center was established in Japan.<ref name = \"boyfriend\" /> Grady Quinn and Randy Rohl became the first known gay couple to attend a high school prom when they attended the Lincoln High School prom in Sioux Falls, South Dakota on May 23, 1979.<ref>https://www.apnews.com/0538ff70caff44b6b53d687866a85187</ref>\n\n==1980s==\n\n* '''1980'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[United States Democratic Party]] becomes the first major political party in the U.S. to endorse a homosexual rights platform plank; [[Scotland]] decriminalizes homosexuality; The [[Human Rights Campaign]] Fund is founded by [[Steve Endean]]; The Human Rights Campaign is America's largest civil rights organization working to achieve lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender equality.<ref name=HRC>{{cite web|title=HRC&nbsp;\u2013 About Us |publisher=Human Rights Campaign |year=2009 |url=http://www.hrc.org/about_us/ |accessdate=9 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521090000/http://www.hrc.org/about_us/ |archivedate=21 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}&nbsp;\u2013. A coalition of Homosexual organizations organized demonstrations for [[Armed Forces Day (United States)|Armed Forces Day]] to protest the exclusion of LGBT from the U.S. armed services. The Los Angeles group held a 15-car motorcade, which has been identified as the nation's first gay pride parade.</ref> [[Lionel Blue]] becomes the first British rabbi to come out as gay;<ref name=\"lionel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2016/12/20/news-opinion/world/rabbi-lionel-blue-the-first-openly-gay-british-rabbi-dies-at-86 |title=Rabbi Lionel Blue, the first openly gay British rabbi, dies at 86 &#124; Jewish Telegraphic Agency |publisher=Jta.org |date=2016-12-20 |accessdate=2017-06-22}}</ref> \"[[First Black Lesbian Conference|Becoming Visible: The First Black Lesbian Conference]]\" is held at the [[The Women's Building (San Francisco)|Women's Building]], from October 17 to 19, 1980. It has been credited as the first conference for [[African Americans|African-American]] [[lesbian]] women.<ref name=\":3\">Kyper, John. \"Black Lesbians Meet in October.\" ''Coming Up: A Calendar of Events'' 1 (Oct. 1980): 1. Web.</ref> The [[Socialist Party USA]] nominates an openly gay man, [[David McReynolds]], as its (and America's) first openly gay presidential candidate in 1980.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thevillager.com/2018/08/david-mcreynolds-pacifist-and-socialist-leader-is-dead-at-88/ |title=David McReynolds, pacifist and socialist leader, is dead at 88 |newspaper=The Villager |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n* '''1981'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[European Court of Human Rights]] in ''[[Dudgeon v United Kingdom]]'' strikes down Northern Ireland's criminalisation of homosexual acts between consenting adults, leading to Northern Ireland decriminalising homosexual sex the following year; [[Victoria (Australia)]] and [[Colombia]] decriminalize homosexuality with a uniform age of consent; The [[Moral Majority]] starts its anti-homosexual crusade; Norway becomes the first country in the world to enact a law to prevent discrimination against homosexuals; [[Hong Kong]]'s first sex-change operation is performed. The first official documentation of the condition to be known as [[AIDS]] was published by the US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)]] on 5 June 1981.<ref>CDC (5 June 1981) \u2018Pheumocystis Pneumonia&nbsp;\u2013 Los Angeles\u2019, MMWR, Vol. 30 No. 21.</ref> Tennis player [[Billie Jean King]] became the first prominent professional athlete to come out as a lesbian, when her relationship with her secretary Marilyn Barnett became public in a May 1981 \"[[palimony]]\" lawsuit filed by Barnett.<ref name = \"TimesOnline-20071209\">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/tennis/article3021888.ece The Big Interview: Billie Jean King], 9 December 2007.</ref> Due to this she lost all of her endorsements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/other_sports/tennis/articles/2006/12/03/no_royalty_like_king/?page=4 |title=No royalty like King |work=Boston Globe  |date=3 December 2006 |accessdate=4 July 2011 |first=Stan |last=Grossfeld}}</ref> [[Mary C. Morgan]] became the first openly gay or lesbian judge in America when she was appointed by California Governor Jerry Brown to the San Francisco Municipal Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaysouthafrica.org.za/test.php?link=12&sub=2 |title=Lesbian History |publisher=Gaysouthafrica.org.za |accessdate=2014-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321024539/http://www.gaysouthafrica.org.za/test.php?link=12&sub=2 |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Randy Shilts]] was hired as a national [[correspondent]] by the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', becoming \"the first openly gay reporter with a gay 'beat' in the American mainstream press.\"<ref name=\"QUEER\">[http://www.queertheory.com/histories/s/shilts_randy.htm Randy Shilts at Queer Theory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006162424/http://www.queertheory.com/histories/s/shilts_randy.htm |date=6 October 2012 }} Retrieved on 2007-01-03</ref> A Sergeant of the [[New York City Police Department]] ([[Charles H. Cochrane|Charles H. Cochrane Jr.]]) came out as gay during a city council hearing. This made him the first New York City Police Department member to publicly announce his homosexuality.<ref name=Qundlen>Anna Qundlen, [https://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/05/nyregion/about-new-york-a-tough-month-in-the-new-life-of-a-policeman.html \"A Tough Month in the New Life of a Policeman\"], ''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1981.</ref>  \n* '''1982'''&nbsp;\u2013 Laguna Beach, CA elects the first openly gay mayor in United States history; France equalizes the age of consent; The first [[Gay Games]] is held in San Francisco, attracting 1,600 participants; [[Northern Ireland]] decriminalizes homosexuality; [[Wisconsin]] becomes the first US state to ban discrimination against homosexuals; [[New South Wales]] becomes the first Australian state to outlaw discrimination on the basis of actual or perceived homosexuality. The condition to be known as [[AIDS]] had acquired a number of names&nbsp;\u2013 GRID5 (gay-related immune deficiency), \u2018gay cancer\u2019, \u2018community-acquired immune dysfunction\u2019 and \u2018gay compromise syndrome\u2019<ref>Oswald, G.A, et al. (1982) \u2018Attempted immune stimulation in the \"gay compromise syndrome\"\u2019. BMJ, 1982 October 16; 285(6348): 1082.</ref> The CDC used the term AIDS for the first time in September 1982, when it reported that an average of one to two cases of AIDS were being diagnosed in America every day.<ref>MMWR Weekly (1982) \u2018Current trends update on Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS)&nbsp;\u2013 United States\u2019. 24 September, 31(37); 507\u2013508, 513\u2013514.</ref> [[:ja:\u6771\u90f7\u5065|Ken Togo]] founded the Deracine Party in Japan. New York City police sergeant [[Charles H. Cochrane|Charles H. Cochrane Jr.]] and former Fairview, [[New Jersey]] sergeant Sam Ciccone formed the first group targeted at the needs of gay members of law enforcement, the Gay Officers Action League (GOAL).<ref name=\"Ciccone\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/18/nyregion/sam-ciccone-a-champion-of-gay-police-officers-dies-at-71.html|title=Sam Ciccone, a Champion of Gay Police Officers, Dies at 71|newspaper=New York Times|last1=Weber|first1=Bruce|date=May 17, 2015|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> Portugal decriminalizes homosexuality for the second time in its history.\n* '''1983'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Massachusetts]] Representative [[Gerry Studds]] reveals he is gay on the floor of the House, becoming the first openly gay member of Congress; [[Guernsey]] (Including [[Alderney]], [[Herm]] and [[Sark]]) decriminalizes homosexuality; AIDS is described as a \"gay plague\" by Reverend [[Jerry Falwell]];  BiPOL, the first and oldest bisexual political organization, is founded in San Francisco by bisexual activists Autumn Courtney, [[Lani Ka'ahumanu]], Arlene Krantz, David Lourea, Bill Mack, [[Alan Rockway]], and Maggi Rubenstein; Governor [[Jerry Brown]] appoints [[Herb Donaldson (lawyer)|Herb Donaldson]] as the first openly gay male municipal court judge in the State of California;<ref name=\"cain\">{{cite journal|last=Cain|first=Patricia A.|title=Litigating for Lesbian and Gay Rights: A Legal History|journal=Virginia Law Review|date=Oct 1993|volume=79|issue=7 Symposium on Sexual Orientation and the Law|pages=1551\u20131641|doi=10.2307/1073382|jstor=1073382|url=https://digitalcommons.law.scu.edu/facpubs/277}}</ref><ref name=\"sfchronobit\">{{cite news\n | last = Taylor\n | first = Michael\n | title = Judge Herbert Donaldson dies: 'A born jurist'\n | newspaper = San Francisco Chronicle\n | date = 2008-12-10\n | url = http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Judge-Herbert-Donaldson-dies-A-born-jurist-3181205.php\n | accessdate = 2014-10-01}}</ref> [[David Scondras]] becomes the first openly gay official elected to the [[Boston City Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bostonspiritmagazine.com/2013/10/boston-mayors-race-then-and-now/ |title=Boston Mayor's Race: Then and Now |first=Mark |last=Krone |website=bostonspiritmagazine.com |date=October 10, 2013 |accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''1984'''&nbsp;\u2013 The lesbian and gay association \"Ten Percent Club\" is formed in Hong Kong; Massachusetts voters reelect representative [[Gerry Studds]], despite his revealing himself as homosexual the year before; New South Wales and the [[Northern Territory]] in Australia make homosexual acts legal; [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]], newly elected to the UK parliament declares: \"My name is Chris Smith. I'm the Labour MP for Islington South and Finsbury, and I'm gay\", making him the first openly out homosexual male politician in the UK parliament (Maureen Colquhoun being the first openly out homosexual politician in the UK in 1975). The Argentine Homosexual Community (Comunidad Homosexual Argentina, CHA) is formed uniting several different and preexisting groups. [[Berkeley, California]] becomes the first city in the U.S. to adopt a program of domestic partnership health benefits for city employees; West Hollywood, CA is founded and becomes the first known city to elect a city council where a majority of the members are openly gay or lesbian. [[Reconstructionist Judaism]] became the first Jewish denomination to allow openly gay and lesbian rabbis and cantors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Jewish_World_Today/Denominations/Reconstructionist.shtml |title=Reconstructionist Judaism Today |publisher=myjewishlearning.com |date=18 January 2002 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524122700/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Jewish_World_Today/Denominations/Reconstructionist.shtml |archivedate=24 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ILGA Japan is founded in Japan. ''[[On Our Backs]]'', the first women-run erotica magazine and the first magazine to feature [[lesbian]] [[erotica]] for a lesbian audience in the United States, was first published in 1984 by Debi Sundahl and Myrna Elana, with the contributions of [[Susie Bright]], Nan Kinney, Honey Lee Cottrell, Dawn Lewis, Happy Hyder, [[Tee Corinne]], [[Jewelle Gomez]], Judith Stein, [[Joan Nestle]], and [[Patrick Califia]].<ref>[[Patrick Califia]], \"Raising Cane\", ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'', August 1999, Vol. 8, No. 2, p.32</ref> In 1984, BiPOL sponsored the first bisexual rights rally, outside the [[Democratic National Convention]] in San Francisco. The rally featured nine speakers from civil rights groups allied with the bisexual movement.\n* '''1985'''&nbsp;\u2013 France prohibits discrimination based on lifestyle (moeurs) in employment and services; the first memorial to [[History of gay people in Nazi Germany and the Holocaust|gay Holocaust victims]] is dedicated; [[Belgium]] equalizes the age of consent; the [[Restoration Church of Jesus Christ]] (informally called the ''Gay Mormon Church'') is founded by [[Antonio A. Feliz]].<ref>[[Sunstone (magazine)|Sunstone]] March 1986 Interview with Antonio A. Feliz Pages 43\u201344</ref> Actor [[Rock Hudson]] dies of [[AIDS]]. He is the first major public figure known to have died from an AIDS-related illness.<ref>Berger, J (1985) \u2018Rock Hudson, screen idol, dies at 59\u2019. The New York Times, 3 October.</ref> [[Terry Sweeney]] becomes [[Saturday Night Live]]'s first [[coming out|openly]] [[gay]] male cast member; Sweeney was \"out\" prior to being hired as a cast member.<ref name=\"shales\">{{citation |title=Live from New York: An Uncensored History of Saturday Night Live |first=Tom |last=Shales |first2=James Andrew |last2=Miller |year=2002 |publisher=Back Bay |isbn=0-316-73565-5 |page=316}}</ref> The [[Bisexual Resource Center]] (BRC) in Massachusetts has served the bisexual community since 1985. [[LGBT culture in Liverpool|Liverpool]]-based soap opera, ''[[Brookside]]'' featured the first openly gay character on a British TV series this year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/seventy-five-years-of-british-television-89276 |title=Seventy five years of British television: The Mirror looks back at the key moments |publisher=The Mirror |date=3 November 2011 |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>\n* '''1986'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Homosexual Law Reform Act]] passed in [[New Zealand]], legalizing sex between males over 16; [[Haiti]] decriminalizes homosexuality, June in ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]'' case, U.S. Supreme Court upholds Georgia law forbidding oral or anal sex, ruling that the constitutional right to privacy does not extend to homosexual relations, but it does not state whether the law can be enforced against heterosexuals. Becky Smith and Annie Afleck became the first openly lesbian couple in America granted legal, joint adoption of a child.<ref>Christopher L. Walton. [http://www.uuworld.org/ideas/articles/2026.shtml Gay rights timeline: Major social, political, and religious milestones on the road to equality.]. uuworld.org. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> From 1 till 3 May, the 1986, [[ILGA]] Asia Conference took place in [[Japan]]'s capital [[Tokyo]].<ref>\u300c\u30aa\u30c8\u30b3\u30ce\u30b3\u30ce\u305f\u3081\u306e\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30d5\u30ec\u30f3\u30c9\u300d\uff081986\u5e74\u767a\u884c\u5c11\u5e74\u793e\u30fb\u767a\u58f2\u96ea\u6deb\u793e\uff09P200</ref> The Dutch [[Remonstrants]] are the world's first [[Christian denomination]] to perform same-sex unions and marriages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1086030/2010/01/25/Remonstranten-en-Boomsma-krijgen-homo-emancipatieprijs.dhtml|title=Remonstrants and Boomsma receive homo emancipation prize|work=[[Trouw]]|language=nl|date=25 January 2010|accessdate=4 April 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105104850/http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1086030/2010/01/25/Remonstranten-en-Boomsma-krijgen-homo-emancipatieprijs.dhtml|archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref> Canadian province [[Ontario]] passes anti-discrimination legislation. ''[[Hill Street Blues]]'' featured the first lesbian recurring character on a major network; the character was a police officer called Kate McBride, played by [[Lindsay Crouse]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Maya Salam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/arts/television/lesbian-tv-shows.html |title=The Very (Very) Slow Rise of Lesbianism on TV - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n* '''1987'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power]](ACT-UP) founded in the US in response to the US government's slow response in dealing with the AIDS crisis.<ref>ACT UP. Flyer of the demonstration on 24 March 1987.</ref> [[AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power|ACT UP]] stages its first major demonstration, seventeen protesters are arrested; U.S. Congressman [[Barney Frank]] comes out. [[Boulder, Colorado]] citizens pass the first referendum to ban discrimination based on sexual orientation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/editorials/ci_22012676/civil-rights-marching-forward | title=Civil rights, marching forward | work=Boulder Daily Camera | date=18 November 2012 | accessdate=18 November 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news   | last = Phelps  | first = Timothy  | title = Gay issues split Colorado cities  | work = Eugene Register-Guard  | page = 8A  | publisher = Newsday  | date = 8 October 1995  | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wUlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G-sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6547,1764809  | accessdate = 14 January 2012}}</ref>  In New York City a group of Bisexual [[List of LGBT rights activists|LGBT rights activist]] including [[Brenda Howard]] found the [[New York Area Bisexual Network|New York Area Bisexual Network (NYABN)]]; [[Homomonument]], a memorial to persecuted homosexuals, opens in [[Amsterdam]]. [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] is the first openly gay person to be elected to public office in the [[Republic of Ireland]]. A group of 75 bisexuals marched in the 1987 March On Washington For Gay and Lesbian Rights, which was the first nationwide bisexual gathering. The article \"[http://www.lanikaahumanu.com/OUT%20OUTRAGED.pdf The Bisexual Movement: Are We Visible Yet?]\", by [[Lani Ka'ahumanu]], appeared in the official Civil Disobedience Handbook for the March. It was the first article about bisexuals and the emerging bisexual movement to be published in a national lesbian or gay publication.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.lanikaahumanu.com/OUT%20OUTRAGED.pdf |title=OUT & OUTRAGED Non-Violent Civil Disobedience at the U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref> Canadian province of [[Manitoba]] and territory [[Yukon]] ban sexual orientation discrimination.\n* '''1988'''&nbsp;\u2013 Sweden is the first country to pass laws protecting homosexual regarding social services, taxes, and inheritances. The anti-gay [[Section 28]] passes in England and Wales; Scotland enacts almost identical legislation; [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Canadian MP]] [[Svend Robinson]] comes out; Canada lowers the age of consent for sodomy to 18; [[Belize]] and Israel decriminalize ([[de jure]]) sodomy and sexual acts between men (the relevant section in the old British-mandate law from 1936 was never enforced in Israel). After losing an [[High Court (Ireland)|Irish High Court]] case (1980) and an [[Supreme Court of Ireland|Irish Supreme Court]] case (1983), [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] takes his case (''[[Norris v. Ireland]]'') to the European Court of Human Rights. The European Court strikes down the Irish law criminalising male-to-male sex on the grounds of privacy. [[Stacy Offner]] became the first openly lesbian rabbi hired by a mainstream Jewish congregation, Shir Tikvah Congregation of Minneapolis (a Reform Jewish congregation).<ref>Dana Evan Kaplan [https://books.google.com/books?id=qQoaBa7D-9oC&pg=PA255 Contemporary American Judaism: transformation and renewal] Columbia University Press, 2009 {{ISBN|0231137281}}, p. 255</ref><ref>[http://www.shirtikvah.net/Default.aspx?pageId=675181 Our Roots]. Shir Tikvah. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> [[Robert Dover (equestrian)|Robert Dover]] became the first openly gay Olympic athlete when he came out in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outsports.com/platform/amp/2020/2/19/21138643/gay-olympic-robert-dover-equestrian-horse-riding-five-rings-athlete |title=Robert Dover, the first out gay Olympic athlete |publisher=Outsports |date= |accessdate=2020-03-11}}</ref> \n* '''1989'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Western Australia]] decriminalizes male homosexuality (but the age of consent is set at 21); [[Liechtenstein]] legalizes homosexuality; Denmark is the first country in the world to enact [[registered partnership]] laws (like a [[civil union]]) for same-sex couples, with most of the same rights as marriage (excluding the right to adoption (until June 2010) and the right to marriage in a church).\n\n==1990s==\n\n* '''1990'''\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': Czechoslovakia (see [[LGBT rights in the Czech Republic|Czech Republic]], [[LGBT rights in Slovakia|Slovakia]])\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': UK Crown Dependency of [[Jersey]] and the Australian state of [[LGBT rights in Queensland|Queensland]]\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': [[BiNet USA]] (USA), [[OutRage!]] (UK),  [[Queer Nation]] (USA), [[Humsafar Trust|The Humsafar Trust]] (India)\n** '''Homosexuality no longer an illness''': The [[World Health Organization]]\n** '''Other''': [[Justin Fashanu]] is the first professional footballer to come out in the press.\n** [[Reform Judaism]] decided to allow openly lesbian and gay rabbis and cantors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/practices/Ritual/Prayer/Synagogue_and_Religious_Leaders/What_is_a_Rabbi/Demographic_Changes.shtml |title=The Changing Face of the Rabbinate |publisher=myjewishlearning.com |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302214918/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/practices/Ritual/Prayer/Synagogue_and_Religious_Leaders/What_is_a_Rabbi/Demographic_Changes.shtml |archivedate=2 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n** [[Dale McCormick]] became the first open lesbian elected to a state Senate (she was elected to the Maine Senate).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qrd.org/QRD/www/usa/maine/bdn-1.20.98.html |title=Dale McCormick finds job as Treasurer challenging, rewarding |publisher=qrd.org |date=20 January 1998 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** In 1990, the [[Union for Reform Judaism]] announced a national policy declaring lesbian and gay Jews to be full and equal members of the religious community. Its principal body, the [[Central Conference of American Rabbis]] (CCAR), officially endorsed a report of their committee on homosexuality and rabbis. They concluded that \"all rabbis, regardless of sexual orientation, be accorded the opportunity to fulfill the sacred vocation that they have chosen\" and that \"all Jews are religiously equal regardless of their sexual orientation.\"\n** The oldest national bisexuality organization in the United States, [[BiNet USA]], was founded in 1990. It was originally called the North American Multicultural Bisexual Network (NAMBN), and had its first meeting at the first National Bisexual Conference in America.<ref name=\"binetusa_a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.binetusa.org/Pages/aboutus.html |title=All About BiNet USA including the Fine Print |publisher=BiNet USA |date= |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref><ref name=\"binetusa_a\" /><ref name=\"glbtq\">{{cite web|last=Summers |first=Claude J. |title=BiNet USA |encyclopedia=glbtq: An Encyclopedia of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Culture |publisher=glbtq, Inc. |date=2009-10-20 |url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/binet_usa.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220100127/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/binet_usa.html |archivedate=2014-02-20 }}</ref> This first conference was held in San Francisco in 1990, and sponsored by BiPOL. Over 450 people attended from 20 states and 5 countries, and the mayor of San Francisco sent a proclamation \"commending the bisexual rights community for its leadership in the cause of social justice,\" and declaring June 23, 1990 [[Celebrate Bisexuality Day|Bisexual Pride Day]].\n** The first Eagle Creek Saloon, that opened on the 1800 block of Market Street in San Francisco in 1990 and closed in 1993, was the first black-owned gay bar in the city.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whiting |first=Sam |url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/art-exhibits/art-piece-remembers-dream-of-sfs-first-black-owned-gay-bar |title=Art piece remembers dream of SF's first black-owned gay bar &#124; Datebook |publisher=Datebook.sfchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n* '''1991'''\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in the Bahamas|Bahamas]], [[LGBT rights in Hong Kong|Hong Kong]]  and [[LGBT rights in Ukraine|Ukraine]]\n** '''AIDS Related''': The [[red ribbon]] is first used as a symbol of the campaign against [[HIV/AIDS]].\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation:''' Canadian province [[Nova Scotia]] (sexual orientation)\n** Sherry Harris was elected to the City Council in Seattle, Washington, making her the first openly lesbian African-American elected official.<ref>Bonnie Zimmerman. [https://books.google.com/books?id=0EUoCrFolGcC&pg=PA258&lpg=PA258&dq=%22sherry++harris%22+%22first+african-+american+lesbian%22&source=bl&ots=NEIskdTf_5&sig=jsrQizMWcCxr7yUZNmY9JdWPYxo&hl=en&ei=cSd1TYnHDIT58Ab6m9jEDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22sherry%20%20harris%22%20%22first%20african-%20american%20lesbian%22&f=false Lesbian Histories and Cultures: An Encyclopedia, Volume 1.]</ref>\n** The first lesbian kiss on television occurred; it was on ''L.A. Law'' between the fictional characters of C.J. Lamb (played by Amanda Donohoe) and Abby (Michele Greene).<ref>[http://www.observer.com/1999/fox-plans-sapphic-smooch-party-five-steve-odonnell-lateline-lets-it-all-out Fox Plans Sapphic Smooch for Party of Five ... Steve O'Donnell of Lateline Lets It All Out | The New York Observer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616082925/http://www.observer.com/1999/fox-plans-sapphic-smooch-party-five-steve-odonnell-lateline-lets-it-all-out |date=16 June 2011 }}. Observer.com (31 January 1999). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref>\n** The [[Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame]] was created in June 1991.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rJEU4xYiWEEC&lpg=PA200&dq=%22chicago%20gay%20and%20lesbian%20hall%20of%20fame%22&pg=PA200#v=onepage&q=%22chicago%20gay%20and%20lesbian%20hall%20of%20fame%22&f=false|title=Out and Proud in Chicago: An Overview of the City's Gay Community|last=Harper|first=Jorjet|publisher=Agate Publishing|year=2009|isbn=9781572846432|editor-last=Baim|editor-first=Tracy|location=|pages=200|language=en}}</ref> The hall of fame is the first \"municipal institution of its kind in the United States, and possibly in the world.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n* '''1992'''\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Iceland|Iceland]], [[LGBT rights in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]] and [[LGBT rights in Switzerland|Switzerland]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Estonia|Estonia]] and [[LGBT rights in Latvia|Latvia]]\n** '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': UK Crown Dependency of [[LGBT rights in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] (homosexuality still illegal until 1994)\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Australia|Australia]], [[LGBT rights in Canada|Canada]]\n** '''Recriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Nicaragua|Nicaragua]] (until Mar 2008)\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation:''' Canadian provinces [[New Brunswick]] and [[British Columbia]] (sexual orientation)\n** '''[[Althea Garrison]]''' was elected as the first transgender state legislator in America, and served one term in the Massachusetts House of Representatives; however, it was not publicly known she was transgender when she was elected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials,2.html |title=Social sciences - Elected Officials |publisher=glbtq |date=13 November 2006 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714173926/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials%2C2.html |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n** The [[Lesbian Avengers]] was founded in [[New York City]] by [[Ana Mar\u00eda Simo]], [[Sarah Schulman]], Maxine Wolfe, [[Anne-Christine d'Adesky]], Marie Honan, and [[Anne Maguire]]\n** [[Tokyo International Lesbian & Gay Film Festival]] was held in Japan.\n* '''1993'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Norway|Norway]] (without adoption until 2009, replaced with same-sex marriage in 2008/09)\n** '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': Australian Territory of [[Norfolk Island]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Belarus|Belarus]], UK Crown Dependency of [[LGBT rights in Gibraltar|Gibraltar]], [[LGBT rights in the Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], [[LGBT rights in Lithuania|Lithuania]], [[LGBT rights in Russia|Russia]] (with the exception of the [[Chechen Republic]]);\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': \n*** US state of [[Minnesota]] (gender identity) \n*** New Zealand parliament passes the Human Rights Amendment Act which outlaws discrimination on the grounds of sexual orientation or HIV\n*** Canadian province [[Saskatchewan]] (sexual orientation)\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in New Zealand|New Zealand]]\n** '''Significant LGBT Murders''': [[Brandon Teena]]\n** [[Melissa Etheridge]] came out as a lesbian.\n** The Triangle Ball was held; it was the first inaugural ball in America to ever be held in honor of gays and lesbians.\n** The first [[Dyke March]] (a march for lesbians and their straight female allies, planned by the [[Lesbian Avengers]]) was held, with 20,000 women marching.<ref>[http://www.thegully.com/essays/gaymundo/020719_lesbian_future.html Dyke March: The Next Wave]. The Gully. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baywindows.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=glbt&sc2=news&sc3=&id=61643 |title=Boisterous women chant, laugh and clap their way through Dyke March 2000 (Bay Windows) |accessdate=2012-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110612131852/http://www.baywindows.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=glbt&sc2=news&sc3=&id=61643 |archivedate=12 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n** [[Roberta Achtenberg]] became the first openly gay or lesbian person to be nominated by the president and confirmed by the U.S. Senate when she was appointed to the position of Assistant Secretary for Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity by President Bill Clinton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.browsebiography.com/bio-roberta_achtenberg.html |title=Roberta Achtenberg biography |publisher=browsebiography.com |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** [[Lea DeLaria]] was \"the first [[closeted|openly]] gay comic to break the late-night talk-show barrier\" with her 1993 appearance on ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]''.<ref name=\"EW 1993-12-10\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,308870,00.html\n|title = Trend: Gay stand-up comedians\n|last = Cagle\n|first = Jess\n|work = [[Entertainment Weekly]]\n|publisher = [[Time Warner]]\n|date = 10 December 1993\n|accessdate = 2011-06-28}}</ref>\n** In December 1993 [[Lea DeLaria]] hosted [[Comedy Central]]'s ''Out There'', the first all-gay stand-up comedy special.<ref name=\"EW 1993-12-10\" />\n** Before the \"[[Don't Ask Don't Tell]]\" policy was enacted in 1993, lesbians and bisexual women and gay men and bisexual men were banned from serving in the military.<ref name=\"prezi2003\">{{cite web|url=https://prezi.com/ytivn4zvwnrv/military-service-should-be-based-on-conduct-not-sexual-orie/|title=Military Service Should Be Based On Conduct, Not Sexual Orientation|publisher=prezi.com |author=Elizabeth Hoffman|date=2003-03-28 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> In 1993 the \"Don't Ask Don't Tell\" policy was enacted, which mandated that the military could not ask servicemembers about their sexual orientation.<ref name=\"Craig A. Rimmerman p. 249\">Craig A. Rimmerman [https://books.google.com/books?id=Go9XsJ47GswC&pg=PA249 Gay rights, military wrongs: political perspectives on lesbians and gays in the military], Garland Pub., 1996 {{ISBN|0815325800}} p. 249</ref><ref name=\"'Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Turns 15\">Thompson, Mark. (2008-01-28) [http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1707545,00.html 'Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Turns 15]. TIME. Retrieved on 2010-11-30.</ref> However, until the policy was ended in 2011 service members were still expelled from the military if they engaged in sexual conduct with a member of the same sex, stated that they were lesbian, gay, or bisexual, and/or married or attempted to marry someone of the same sex.<ref name=\"The Military Commander & the Law\">Richard A. Gittins [https://books.google.com/books?id=ENpnS9KApu8C&pg=PA215 The Military Commander & the Law], DIANE Publishing, 1996 {{ISBN|0788172603}} p. 215</ref>\n* '''1994'''\n** '''Unregistered Cohabitation recognition''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|Israel]] (without adoption, without step-adoption until 2005)\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (sexual orientation, interim constitution)\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Bermuda|Bermuda]], UK Crown Dependency of [[LGBT rights in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] and [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbia]], Commonwealth of Australia\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''':\n*** '''Partial''': [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|UK]] reduces the age of consent for homosexual men to 18;\n** '''Homosexuality no longer an illness''': [[American Medical Association]]\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': [[National Coalition for Gay and Lesbian Equality]] (South Africa)\n** '''Other''' : [[LGBT rights in Canada|Canada]] grants refugee status to homosexuals fearing for their well-being in their native country; ''[[Toonen v. Australia]]'' decided by UN Human Rights Committee; fear of persecution due to sexual orientation becomes grounds for asylum in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gesaman |first=Krista |url=http://www.newsweek.com/2009/11/29/desperately-seeking-freedom.html |title=Are More Gays, Lesbians Seeking Asylum in U.S.? |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=29 November 2009 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** [[Deborah Batts]] became the first openly gay or lesbian federal judge; she was appointed to the U.S. District Court in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/batts_da.html |title=Batts, Deborah A |publisher=glbtq.com |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002143835/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/batts_da.html |archivedate=2 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>[http://www.queertheory.com/histories/b/batts_deborah.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011003321/http://www.queertheory.com/histories/b/batts_deborah.htm|date=11 October 2011}}</ref>\n** The Gay Asian Pacific Alliance and Asian Pacific Sister joined the Chinese New Year Parade in San Francisco, which was the first time that queer Asian American communities had attended in a publicly ethnic activity.<ref>Lavilla, S. (1998, Jul 09). A growing show of pride: Record Asian american presence at parade reflects a growing acceptance. ''Asianweek'' Retrieved from http://search.proquest.com/docview/367563813</ref>\n** Gay Parade was held in Japan. (8.1994)\n** '''[[Wilson Cruz]]''' became the first gay actor to play an openly gay character in a leading role in a television series (''[[My So-Called Life]]'').\n** '''[[Steve Gunderson]]''' was outed as gay on the House floor by representative [[Bob Dornan]] (R-[[California|CA]]) during a debate over federal funding for gay-friendly curricula,<ref>Chris Bull (May 3, 1994), [https://books.google.com/books?id=9GMEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA29&dq=Steve%20Gunderson%20Dornan&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false The Out House: Congressional Debate over an Education Bill Gets Personal and Nasty], ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', p. 29.</ref> making him one of the first openly gay members of the U.S. Congress and the first openly gay U.S. Republican representative.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Closeted+in+the+capital%3a+they%27re+powerful%2c+Republican%2c+and+gay.+Will...-a0116288151 |title=Closeted in the capital: they're powerful, Republican, and gay. Will the marriage battle finally get them to come out to their bosses? |publisher=The Advocate |author=Bergling, Tim |date=May 11, 2004 |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> \n** [[LGBT culture in Liverpool|Liverpool]]-based soap opera, '''''[[Brookside]]''''', broadcast the UK's first pre-watershed lesbian kiss.<ref>{{cite news|author=Monique Roffey |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/when-anna-and-beth-kissed-margaret-anna-friel-plays-brooksides-lesbian-pinup-monique-roffey-met-her-1440368.html |title=When Anna and Beth kissed Margaret: Anna Friel plays Brookside's lesbian pin-up. Monique Roffey met her |newspaper=The Independent |date=2 November 1994 |accessdate=2012-06-07 |location=London}}</ref>\n** The broadcast of '''[[Pedro Zamora]] and [[Sean Sasser]]'s [[commitment ceremony]]''' in 1994, in which they exchanged vows, was the first such same-sex ceremony in television history, and is considered a landmark in the history of the medium.<ref name=CNN>Duke, Alan; Carter, Chelsea, J. (August 8, 2013). [http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/08/showbiz/sean-sasser-death/index.html \"Sean Sasser, whose ceremony with partner on 'Real World' was TV first, dies\"]. [[CNN]].</ref><ref name=USAToday>Oldenburg, Ann (August 8, 2013). [https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2013/08/08/real-world-star-sean-sasser-dies-at-44/2632631/ \"'Real World' star Sean Sasser dies at 44\"]. ''[[USA Today]]''.</ref>\n* '''1995'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Sweden|Sweden]] (with adoption, replaced with same-sex marriage in April 2009)\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': Canadian province [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] (sexual orientation)\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Albania|Albania]] and [[LGBT rights in Moldova|Moldova]]\n** '''AIDS Related''': Triple combination therapy of drugs such as [[Lamivudine|3TC]], [[Zidovudine|AZT]] and [[Zalcitabine|ddC]] shown to be effective in treating [[HIV]], the virus responsible for [[AIDS]]<ref>The New York Times (21 November 1995) \u2018New drug to fight AIDS is approved by FDA\u2019.</ref>\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': Gay Advice Darlington/Durham was founded by local gay and bisexual men, and has developed into a Charity that works with and for the Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender (LGBT) Community of County Durham and Darlington.\n** '''Other''' : The [[Human Rights Campaign]] drops the word \"Fund\" from their title and broadens their mission to promote \"an America where gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender people are ensured equality and embraced as full members of the American family at home, at work and in every community;\"\n** [[Rachel Maddow]] became the first openly gay or lesbian American to win an international [[Rhodes Scholarship]].\n** Kings Cross Steelers, the world's first gay rugby club, was founded.<ref>{{cite news|last=McKenzie |first=Sheena |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/23/sport/world-first-gay-rugby-club-team-london/index.html?eref=rss_latest |title=World's first gay rugby club 20 years on |publisher=CNN.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref>\n** Rabbi [[Margaret Wenig]]'s essay \"Truly Welcoming Lesbian and Gay Jews\" was published in ''The Jewish Condition: Essays on Contemporary Judaism Honoring Rabbi [[Alexander M. Schindler]]''; it was the first published argument to the Jewish community on behalf of civil marriage for gay couples.<ref name=\"wenig\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:fFLO9cY0WUUJ:huc.edu/news/docs/prlinks3/Wenig%2520PR.pdf+%22miriam+frank%22+%22margaret+wenig%22+%22mentally+ill%22+first&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESi23nbt0sf9HxA42m72kp-VshCZh5JKMb3Hij-nLKXhlNPM6VasnnCORZOT3VL0e3mlKGD8ZONJvC6gk8GgLZy_ZEsA74UoazDW6WKzPULQp5hJfW7Bea6V6AqAubipRho2owD1&sig=AHIEtbR6VRH-CJYWipd-wwBi6ItCM-6UmA |title=Powered by Google Docs |date= |accessdate=2012-04-12}}</ref>\n** [[Ed Flanagan (politician)|Ed Flanagan]] served as Vermont's [[Vermont Auditor of Accounts|State Auditor]] from 1993 through 2001, becoming the first openly gay, statewide-elected official in the United States when he came out in 1995, before his 1996 reelection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outhistory.org/exhibits/show/out-and-elected/1992/edward-flanagan|title=Edward Flanagan, Vermont, 1992 \u00b7 Out and Elected in the USA: 1974-2004 \u00b7 outhistory.org|website=outhistory.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref> \n* '''1996'''\n**'''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Iceland|Iceland]] (with step-adoption, without joint adoption until 2006, replaced with same-sex marriage in 2010)\n** '''Unregistered Cohabitation recognition''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Hungary]] (replaced with registered partnerships in 2009)\n** '''Restriction of LGBT partnership rights''': [[LGBT rights in the United States|USA]], (federal, see [[DOMA]])\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Burkina Faso|Burkina Faso]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Romania|Romania]],  [[LGBT rights in North Macedonia|North Macedonia]], [[LGBT rights in Macau|Macau]]\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation:''' [[Lgbt rights in Canada|Canada]] (federal, sexual orientation)\n** The first lesbian wedding on television occurred, held for fictional characters Carol (played by Jane Sibbett) and Susan (played by Jessica Hecht) on the TV show \"Friends\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2008/8/lesbianweddings |title=Getting Hitched: Lesbian Weddings in Film and TV |publisher=AfterEllen.com |date=18 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716134253/http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2008/8/lesbianweddings |archivedate=16 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n** The first openly gay speaker at a [[Republican National Convention]] was [[Log Cabin Republicans]] member Steve Fong of California in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last=Keen |first=Lisa |url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=71747 |title=The Bay Area Reporter Online &#124; Tension between gays and GOP shrouds convention |publisher=Ebar.com |date=2016-07-21 |accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref>\n** [[Muffin Spencer-Devlin]] became the first [[LPGA]] player to come out as gay.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garrity |first1=John |last2=Nutt |first2=Amy |title=No More Disguises - Muffin Spencer-Devlin stands tall in her chosen role: the first LPGA player to declare she's gay |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1996/03/18/211002/no-more-disguises-muffin-spencer-devlin-stands-tall-in-her-chosen-role-the-first-lpga-player-to-declare-shes-gay |accessdate=February 11, 2015 |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=March 18, 1996}}</ref>\n* '''1997'''\n**'''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Fiji|Fiji]] (sexual orientation, constitution) and [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (sexual orientation, constitution)\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Russia|Russia]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Ecuador|Ecuador]], [[LGBT rights in Venezuela|Venezuela]] and the Australian state of [[LGBT rights in Tasmania|Tasmania]]\n** '''Other''' : Israeli President Ezer Weizman compares homosexuality to alcoholism in front of high school students.<ref>[[Ezer Weizman]]</ref> The UK extends immigration rights to same-sex couples akin to marriage; [[Ellen DeGeneres]] came out as a lesbian, one of the first celebrities to do so.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/9704/06/ellen/|work=CNN|title=Ellen DeGeneres tells Time she's a lesbian}}</ref> Furthermore, later that year her character Ellen Morgan came out as a lesbian on the TV show ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'', making Ellen DeGeneres the first openly lesbian actress to play an openly lesbian character on television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/People/ellen.html |title=Ellen DeGeneres: Reluctant Lesbian Icon |publisher=AfterEllen.com |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120720113652/http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/People/ellen.html |archivedate=20 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> '''[[Patria Jim\u00e9nez]]''' became the first openly gay person to win a position in the Mexican Congress, doing so for the [[Party of the Democratic Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= Mexican gays poised to make demands for change |date= 27 July 1997 |publisher= CNN interactive |url= http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9707/27/mexico.gays/ |accessdate= 17 December 2007}}</ref> The [[Gay and Lesbian Medical Association]] launched the ''Journal of the Gay and Lesbian Medical Association'', the world's first peer-reviewed, multi-disciplinary journal dedicated to LGBT health. The first open-mouth kiss between two women on prime time television occurred, on ABC's ''[[Relativity (TV series)|Relativity]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frost |first=Karen |url=https://www.afterellen.com/tv/474467-long-road-lesbian-sex-sensuality-network-tv#UjXTCyxhuYzGUkMG.99 |title=The Long Road to Lesbian Sex & Sensuality on Network TV |publisher=AfterEllen |date=2017-08-19 |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n* '''1998'''\n**'''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Ecuador|Ecuador]] (sexual orientation, constitution), [[LGBT rights in the Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] (sexual orientation) and the Canadian provinces of [[Prince Edward Island]] (sexual orientation) and [[LGBT rights in Alberta|Alberta]] ([[Vriend v Alberta|court ruling only]]; legislation amended in 2009)\n** '''Significant LGBT Murders''': [[Rita Hester]], [[Matthew Shepard]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[LGBT rights in Kazakhstan|Kazakhstan]], [[LGBT rights in Kyrgyzstan|Kyrgyzstan]], [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (retroactive to 1994), [[LGBT rights in Cyprus|Republic of Cyprus]] and [[LGBT rights in Tajikistan|Tajikistan]]\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Croatia|Croatia]] and [[LGBT rights in Latvia|Latvia]]\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Romania|Romania]], [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]]\n** [[Gender identity]] was added to the mission of '''[[Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays]]''' after a vote at their annual meeting in San Francisco.<ref name=\"bare_url_a\">{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=Community.pflag.org |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620050818/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |archivedate=20 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays]] is the first national LGBT organization to officially adopt a transgender-inclusion policy for its work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/page.aspx?pid=380 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=Community.pflag.org |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514141130/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=380 |archivedate=14 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n** [[Tammy Baldwin]] became the first openly gay or lesbian non-incumbent ever elected to Congress, and the first open lesbian ever elected to Congress, winning Wisconsin's 2nd congressional district seat over Josephine Musser.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/11/03/election/house/wisconsin.cd2/|work=CNN|title=Baldwin breaks barrier, becomes first openly lesbian House member}}</ref><ref>[http://www.now.org/nnt/winter-99/lesactn.html NOW Calls Lesbian Rights Supporters to Unite in Strategy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215112429/http://www.now.org/nnt/winter-99/lesactn.html |date=15 February 2010 }}. Now.org (4 February 1999). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref>\n** [[Dana International]] became the first transsexual to win the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], representing [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest|Israel]] with the song \"[[Diva (Dana International song)|Diva]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1998 {{!}} Year page {{!}} Eurovision Song Contest - Copenhagen 2014|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=313#Participants|publisher=Eurovision.tv|accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref> \n** [[Robert Halford]] comes out as being the first openly gay heavy metal musician.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429870/19980205/halford_rob.jhtml | date=5 February 1998 | title=Rob Halford Discusses Sexuality Publicly For The First Time | publisher=[[MTV News]] | accessdate=24 May 2010 }}</ref>\n** The first [[bisexual pride flag]] was unveiled on 5 December 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wright.edu/counseling/SafezoneSymbols.html |title=Counseling and Wellness Services - Safezone Symbols |publisher=Wright.edu |date=1998-12-05 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n** Julie Hesmondhalgh first began to play Hayley Anne Patterson, British TV's first transgender character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/01/21/coronation-street-says-goodbye-to-its-first-transgender-character/|title=Coronation Street says goodbye to its first transgender character|work=PinkNews|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** [[BiNet USA]] hosted the '''First National Institute on Bisexuality and HIV/AIDS.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.binetusa.org/binethistory.html |title=BiNet USA |publisher=BiNet USA |date= |accessdate=2015-10-30}}</ref>\n* '''1999'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US State of [[Domestic partnership in California|California]] (without adoption, without step adoption until 2001, same-sex marriage in June 2008-November 2008)\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Pacte civil de solidarit\u00e9|France]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Chile|Chile]]\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Finland|Finland]] (without adoption)\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': \"[[Queer Youth Alliance]]\" (UK)\n** '''Other''': [[LGBT rights in Israel|Israel]]'s supreme court recognizes a lesbian partner as another legal mother of her partner's biological son; [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] grants spousal immigration benefits to same-sex partners.\n**  '''[[Steven Greenberg (rabbi)|Steven Greenberg]]''' publicly came out as gay in an article in the [[Israel]]i newspaper ''[[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]]''. As he has a [[semichah|rabbinic ordination]] from the [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] rabbinical seminary of Yeshiva University ([[RIETS]]), he is generally described as the first [[openly gay]] Orthodox Jewish rabbi.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/11/national/11bishop.html?scp=4&sq=Rabbi%20Steven%20Greenberg&st=cse| title=Bishop Says Conflict on Gays Distracts From Vital Issues| work=[[The New York Times]] | date=11 September 2004| accessdate=18 November 2011 | author=Goodstein, Laurie}}<br />{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,1425657,00.html | title=Judaism and the gay dilemma | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=26 February 2005 | accessdate=16 November 2011 | author=Rocker, Simon | location=London}}\n{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/07/an-interview-with-rabbi-s_n_638679.html| title= An Interview With Rabbi Steven Greenberg: Orthodox And Gay | work=[[Huffington Post]]| date=7 July 2010| accessdate=16 November 2011 | author=Neroulias, Nicole}}<br />{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/07/an-interview-with-rabbi-s_n_638679.html\n| title= Gay And Orthodox, According To Jon Marans | work=[[The Jewish Week]]| date=19 July 2011 | accessdate=16 November 2011 | author=Merwin, Ted}}</ref> However, some Orthodox Jews, including many rabbis, dispute his being an Orthodox rabbi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algemeiner.com/2011/12/05/100-orthodox-rabbis-issue-same-sex-marriage-declaration/ |title=100 Orthodox Rabbis Issue Same Sex Marriage Declaration |publisher=algemeiner.com |date=5 December 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** The '''[[Transgender Day of Remembrance]]''' was founded in 1999 by [[Gwendolyn Ann Smith]], a [[trans woman]] who is a graphic designer, columnist, and activist,<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=G. |title=Biography |url=http://www.gwensmith.com/background/biography.html |publisher=Gwensmith.com |accessdate=2013-11-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424004720/http://www.gwensmith.com/background/biography.html |archivedate=24 April 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> to memorialize the murder of [[Rita Hester]] in [[Allston, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Ethan|title=Remembering Rita Hester|url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=entertainment&sc=music&sc2=features&sc3&id=83392|newspaper=EDGE Boston|date=2008-11-15}}</ref> Since its inception, TDoR has been held annually on 20 November,<ref>{{cite web|title=Transgender Day of Remembrance|url=http://www.hrc.org/campaigns/transgender-day-remembrance|publisher=Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=2013-11-20}}</ref> and it has slowly evolved from the [[World Wide Web|web]]-based project started by Smith into an international day of action. \n** In 1999, the first '''[[Celebrate Bisexuality Day]]''' was organized by Michael Page, [[Gigi Raven Wilbur]], and [[Wendy Curry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.binetusa.org/bihistory2.html |title=BiNet USA |publisher=BiNet USA |date=1990-06-23 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n\n* <!--2000 is the last year of the 20th century-->'''2000'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US State of [[Same-sex marriage in Vermont|Vermont]]\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (discrimination, hate speech, harassment; see [[Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discrimination Act, 2000|PEPUDA]])\n** '''Revoking of discrimination legislation''': UK subdivision of [[LGBT rights in Scotland|Scotland]] ([[Section 28]])\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]]. See also: [[Sexual orientation and military service]] and [[Stonewall (UK)|Stonewall]]\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Belarus|Belarus]], [[LGBT rights in Israel|Israel]] and [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] (passed eff. 2001)\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Azerbaijan|Azerbaijan]] and [[LGBT rights in Georgia (country)|Georgia]]\n** '''Other''': In [[LGBT rights in Germany|Germany]] the [[Bundestag]] officially apologizes to gays and lesbians persecuted under the Nazi regime, and for \"harm done to homosexual citizens up to 1969\"; Israel recognizes same-sex relations for immigration purposes for a foreign partner of an Israeli resident.\n** The '''[[Transgender Pride flag]]''' was first shown, at a pride parade in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].\n** '''[[Hillary Clinton]]''' became the first First Lady to march in an [[LGBT pride parade]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Nate White |url=https://medium.com/@natewhite11/why-hillary-s-experience-argument-actually-does-check-out-64cc9a439442#.swdfuutqn |title=Why Hillary's experience argument actually does check out \u2014 Medium |publisher=Medium.com |accessdate=2016-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821202223/https://medium.com/%40natewhite11/why-hillary-s-experience-argument-actually-does-check-out-64cc9a439442#.swdfuutqn |archivedate=21 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history]]\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history, 19th century]]\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history, 21st century]]\n* [[List of years in LGBT rights]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{LGBT history}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline Of Lgbt History}}\n[[Category:LGBT timelines| ]]\n[[Category:20th century timelines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n\nThe following is a '''timeline of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender''' ('''[[LGBT]]''') '''history''', in the ''[[20th century]]''.\n<!--\nPlease also add applicable entries to the List of lesbian, gay, bisexual, or transgender firsts by year article\n-->==Timeline==\n\n==1900s==\n* '''1903'''&nbsp;\u2013 In New York City on 21 February 1903, New York police conducted the first United States recorded raid on a [[gay bathhouse]], the Ariston Hotel Baths. 34 men were arrested and 12 brought to trial on sodomy charges; 7 men received sentences ranging from 4 to 20 years in prison.<ref name=Chauncey>(Chauncey, 1995)</ref>\n* '''1906'''&nbsp;\u2013 Potentially the first openly gay American novel with a happy ending, ''[[Imre: A Memorandum|Imre]]'', is published.<ref name=Fone>{{cite book |author=Fone, Byrne R. S. |title=Homophobia: a history |publisher=[[Metropolitan Books]] |location=New York |year=2000 |isbn=0-8050-4559-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/homophobiahistor00fone }}</ref>\n* '''1907'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Adolf Brand]], the activist leader of the Gemeinschaft der Eigenen, working to overturn Paragraph 175, publishes a piece \"outing\" the imperial chancellor of Germany, Prince [[Bernhard von B\u00fclow]]. The Prince sues Brand for libel and clears his name; Brand is sentenced to 18 months in prison.<ref>Marc Vargo. ''Scandal: infamous gay controversies of the twentieth century'' Routledge, 2003. pp 165\u20137.</ref>\n* '''1907\u20131909'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Harden\u2013Eulenburg affair]] in Germany<ref name=Steakley>Steakley, James D. (revised 1989). \"Iconography of a Scandal: Political Cartoons and the Eulenburg Affair in Wilhelmin Germany\", ''Hidden from History: Reclaiming the Gay & Lesbian Past'' (1990), Duberman, et al., eds. New York: Meridian, New American Library, Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-452-01067-5}}.</ref>\n\n==1910s==\n* '''1910'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Emma Goldman]] first begins speaking publicly in favor of homosexual rights. [[Magnus Hirschfeld]] later wrote \"she was the first and only woman, indeed the first and only American, to take up the defense of homosexual love before the general public.\"<ref name=hirschfeld>Goldman, Emma (1923). \"Offener Brief an den Herausgeber der Jahrb\u00fccher \u00fcber Louise Michel\" with a preface by Magnus Hirschfeld. ''Jahrbuch f\u00fcr sexuelle Zwischenstufen'' 23: 70.\u200a Translated from German by James Steakley. Goldman's original letter in English is not known to be extant.</ref> [[File:Lesbiche - 1928 - D- Die freundin 1928.jpg|thumb|upright|14 May 1928 issue of German lesbian periodical ''Die Freundin'' ([[Friedrich Radszuweit]])]]<ref>[http://www.wpunj.edu/newpol/issue45/Escoffier45.htm ''Left-wing Homosexuality Emancipation, Sexual Liberation, and Identity Politics''.]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430093850/http://www.wpunj.edu/newpol/issue45/Escoffier45.htm |date=30 April 2009 }} Jeffrey Escoffier,<br /> \"During the first decade of the twentieth-century, the great anarchist and feminist leader Emma Goldman argued for the acceptance of homosexuals in her speeches and writings.\"</ref>\n* '''1912'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first explicit reference to lesbianism in a Mormon magazine occurred when the \"Young Woman's Journal\" paid tribute to \"[[Sappho]] of Lesbos<ref name=\"affirmation.org\">[http://www.affirmation.org/history/lesbian_mormon_history.shtml Gay & Lesbian Mormons] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424190731/http://www.affirmation.org/history/lesbian_mormon_history.shtml |date=24 April 2012 }}. Affirmation. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> \"; the Scientific Humanitarian Committee of the Netherlands (NWHK), the first Dutch organization to campaign against anti-homosexual discrimination, is established by Dr. Jacob Schorer.\n* '''1913'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word faggot is first used in print in reference to gays in a vocabulary of criminal slang published in [[Portland, Oregon]]: \"All the faggots <small>''[sic]''</small> (sissies) will be dressed in drag at the ball tonight\".\n* '''1917'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[October Revolution]] in Russia repeals the previous criminal code in its entirety\u2014including Article 995.<ref>[http://community.middlebury.edu/~moss/RGC2.html middlebury.edu ''Russian Gay History'']<br />\"It was not until 1832 that the criminal code included Article 995, which made muzhelozhstvo (men lying with men, which the courts interpreted as anal intercourse) a criminal act punishable by exile to Siberia.... The October Revolution of 1917 did away with the entire Criminal Code .... The new Russian Criminal Codes of 1922 and 1926 eliminated the offence of muzhelozhstvo from the law.\"</ref><ref>Wayne R. Dynes, Stephen Donaldson. ''History of homosexuality in Europe and America''. Taylor & Francis, 1992, pp. 174+</ref> Bolshevik leaders reportedly say that \"homosexual relationships and heterosexual relationships are treated exactly the same by the law.\"\n* '''1919'''&nbsp;\u2013 In Berlin, Germany, Doctor [[Magnus Hirschfeld]] co-founds the [[Institut f\u00fcr Sexualwissenschaft]] (Institute for Sex Research), a pioneering private research institute and counseling office. Its library of thousands of books was destroyed by Nazis in May 1933.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hirschfeld.in-berlin.de/aus_inst_en.html|title=hirschfeld.in-berlin.de, ''The first Institute for Sexual Science''|author=Susanne J\u00e4ger|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.stonewallsociety.com/famouspeople/magnus.htm Famous GLBT & GLBTI People - Dr. Magnus Hirschfeld] stonewallsociety</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tex-BuFgji0C&pg=PA16|title=Atina Grossmann. ''Reforming Sex''. Oxford University Press, 1995.|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014|isbn=9780195363517|last1=Grossmann|first1=Atina|date=11 May 1995}}</ref>\n* '''1919''' - ''[[Different from the Others]]'', one of the first explicitly gay films, is released. [[Magnus Hirschfeld]] has a cameo in the film and partially funded its production.\n\n==1920s==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2010}}\n* '''1921'''&nbsp;\u2013 In England, an attempt to make lesbianism illegal for the first time in Britain's history fails.<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/law/article3856756.ece Weird Cases: Lesbian litigants] Times Online, 2 May 2008</ref>\n* '''1922'''&nbsp;\u2013 A new criminal code comes into force in the [[USSR]] officially decriminalizing homosexual acts.\n* '''1923'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word fag is first used in print in reference to gays in Nels Anderson's ''The Hobo'': \"Fairies or Fags are men or boys who exploit sex for profit.\"\n* '''1923'''&nbsp;\u2013  Lesbian [[Elsa Gidlow]], born in England, published the first volume of openly [[lesbian]] love poetry in the United States, titled \"On a Grey Thread.\"<ref>Holt, Patricia (22 June 1986). \"Search for the Independent Mind\". ''San Francisco Chronicle''.</ref>\n* '''1924'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first homosexual rights organization in America is founded by [[Henry Gerber]] in Chicago\u2014 the [[Society for Human Rights]].<ref>Hogan and Hudson, p. 244</ref> The group exists for a few months before disbanding under police pressure.<ref>Bullough, p. 28</ref> Paraguay and Peru legalize homosexuality.\n* '''1926'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''The New York Times'' is the first major publication to use the word homosexuality.<ref name=Fone/>\n* '''1927''' - [[Karol Szymanowski]], Poland's openly gay composer, is appointed chief of Poland's state-owned national music school, the [[Fryderyk Chopin Music Academy]].\n* '''1928'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Well of Loneliness]]'' by [[Radclyffe Hall]] is published in the UK and later in the United States. This sparks great legal controversy and brings the topic of homosexuality to public conversation.\n* '''1929'''&nbsp;\u2013 On 22 May, [[Katharine Lee Bates]], author of ''[[America the Beautiful]]'' dies. On 16 October, a [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]] Committee votes to repeal Paragraph 175; the [[Nazism|Nazis']] rise to power prevents the implementation of the vote.\n\n==1930s==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2010}}\n<!--[[File:Eldoradoinberlinafterforcedclosingbynazis.gif|thumb|250px|left|Once \"Eldorado\" homosexual night club in Berlin after being closed during 1933, with banners promoting \"Hitler List 1\"]].-->\n* '''1931''' - ''[[M\u00e4dchen in Uniform (1931 film)|M\u00e4dchen in Uniform]]'', one of the first explicitly lesbian films and the first pro-lesbian film, is released.\n* '''1931''' - In Berlin in 1931, [[Dorchen Richter|Dora Richter]] became the first known transgender woman to undergo [[vaginoplasty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transmediawatch.org/timeline.html|title=Trans Media Watch|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transmediawatch.org/timeline.html|title=Trans Media Watch|first=Donald|last=Munro|publisher=|accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref> \n* '''1932'''&nbsp;\u2013 Poland codifies the homosexual and heterosexual age of consent equally at 15. Polish law never had criminalized homosexuality, although occupying powers had outlawed it in 1835.<ref name=\"IES_Poland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sexarchive.info/IES/poland.html#6 |title=Homoerotic, Homosexual, and Ambisexual Behaviors |publisher=Continuum Publishing |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511015953/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/IES/poland.html |archivedate=11 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''1933'''&nbsp;\u2013 New [[Danish penalty law]] decriminalizes homosexuality.\n* '''1933'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[National Socialist German Workers Party]] bans homosexual groups. Homosexuals are sent to concentration camps. Nazis burn the library of Magnus Hirschfeld's [[Institut f\u00fcr Sexualwissenschaft|Institute for Sexual Research]], and destroy the Institute; [[Denmark]] and [[Philippines]] decriminalizes homosexuality. Homosexual acts are recriminalized in the USSR.\n* '''1934'''&nbsp;\u2013 Uruguay decriminalizes homosexuality. The USSR once again criminalizes ''muzhelozhstvo'' (specific Russian definition of \"male sexual intercourse with male\", literally \"man lying with man\"), punishable by up to 5 years in prison&nbsp;\u2013 more for the coercion or involvement of minors.<ref>{{cite book|last= West|first=Donald James|author2=Richard Green |title=Sociolegal control of homosexuality: a multi-nation comparison|year=1997|publisher=Springer|isbn=0-306-45532-3|page=224}}</ref>\n* '''1936'''&nbsp;\u2013 Mona's 440 Club, the first lesbian bar in America, opened in San Francisco in 1936.<ref name=\"duberman\">{{cite book|last=Duberman|first=Martin B.|editor-last1=Duberman|editor-first1=Martin B.|editor-last2=Vicinus|editor-first2=Martha|editor-link2=Martha Vicinus|editor-last3=Chauncey|editor-first3=George|title=Hidden from History: Reclaiming the Gay & Lesbian Past|publisher=New York: Meridian|year=1989|isbn=0-452-01067-5|url=https://archive.org/details/hiddenfromhisto000dube}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">James R. Smith [https://books.google.com/books?id=Wvsudy6RdGAC&pg=PA84 San Francisco's Lost Landmarks], Quill Driver Books, 2004 {{ISBN|1884995446}} p. 84</ref> Mona's waitresses and female performers wore tuxedos and patrons dressed their roles.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n* '''1936'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]], Spanish poet, is shot at the beginning of the Spanish civil war.\n* '''1937'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first use of the [[pink triangle]] for gay men in [[Nazi concentration camps]].\n* '''1938'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word ''[[gay]]'' is used for the first time on film in reference to homosexuality in the film ''[[Bringing Up Baby]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayifoundout.com/index.php/2011/01/the-first-time-gay-meaning-homosexual-was-used-as-such-in-a-film/ |title=The First Time \"Gay\", Meaning \"Homosexual\", Was Used as Such in a Film |publisher=todayifoundout.com |date=17 January 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n* '''1939'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Frances V. Rummell]], an educator and a teacher of French at Stephens College, published an autobiography under the title ''Diana: A Strange Autobiography''; it was the first explicitly lesbian autobiography in which two women end up happily together.<ref name=\"pbs.org\">[https://www.pbs.org/opb/historydetectives/investigations/806_diana.html History Detectives . Investigations \u2013 Diana]. PBS. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> This autobiography was published with a note stating \"The publishers wish it expressly understood that this is a true story, the first of its kind ever offered to the general reading public\".<ref name=\"pbs.org\"/>\n\n==1940s==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2010}}\n* '''1940'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Iceland]] decriminalizes homosexuality; the NWHK is disbanded in the Netherlands in May due to the [[Battle of the Netherlands|German invasion]], and most of its archive is voluntarily destroyed, while the rest is confiscated by Nazi soldiers.\n* '''1941'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Transsexuality]] was first used in reference to homosexuality and bisexuality.\n* '''1942'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Switzerland]] decriminalizes homosexuality, with the age of consent set at 20.\n* '''1944'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Sweden]] decriminalizes homosexuality, with the age of consent set at 18 and [[Suriname]] legalizes homosexuality.\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Schimitzek Erwin.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Pink triangle prisoner Erwin Schimitzek, interned in [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] in 1941, died in 1942.]] -->\n* '''1944'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first prominent American to reveal his homosexuality was the poet [[Robert Duncan (poet)|Robert Duncan]]. This occurred when in 1944, using his own name in the anarchist magazine ''Politics'', he wrote that homosexuals were an oppressed minority.<ref>[http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/15949 \"Robert Duncan and Romantic Synthesis: A Few Notes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906020604/http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/15949 |date=2010-09-06 }}. This article also republished as \"On Robert Duncan\" at Modern American Poetry website</ref>\n* '''1945'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[The Holocaust]] ends and it is estimated that between about 3,000 to about 9,000 homosexuals died in [[Nazi concentration camps|Nazi concentration]] and [[Nazi death camps|death camps]], while it is estimated that between about 2,000 to about 6,000 homosexual survivors in Nazi concentration and death camps were required to serve out the full term of their sentences under [[Paragraph 175]] in prison. The first gay bar in post-World War II Berlin opened in the summer of 1945, and the first drag ball took place in [[American Zone of Occupation|American sector]] of [[West Berlin]] in the fall of 1945.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JwB5AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA179#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Lesbian and Gay Histories and Cultures|first1=George|last1=Haggerty|first2=Bonnie|last2=Zimmerman|date=2 September 2003|publisher=Garland Science|via=Google Books|isbn=9781135578718}}</ref> Four honourably discharged gay veterans form the [[Veterans Benevolent Association]], the first LGBT veterans' group.<ref>Archer, p. 110</ref> Gay bar [[:ja:\u3084\u306a\u304e (\u30b2\u30a4\u30d0\u30fc)|Yanagi]] opened in Japan.<ref>\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u306e\u9054\u4eba (2008 [[Shinchosha]])</ref>\n* '''1946'''&nbsp;\u2013 \"[[COC Nederland|COC]]\" (Dutch acronym for \"Center for Culture and Recreation\"), one of the earliest [[homophile]] organizations, is founded in the Netherlands. It is the oldest surviving LGBT organization.\n* '''1946'''&nbsp;\u2013 Plastic surgeon [[Harold Gillies]] carries out sex reassignment surgery on [[Michael Dillon]] in Britain. \n* '''1947-1948'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Vice Versa (magazine)|Vice Versa]]'', the first American lesbian publication, is written and self-published by [[Lisa Ben]] (real name Edith Eyde) in Los Angeles.\n* '''1948'''&nbsp;\u2013 \"[[Danish National Association of Gays and Lesbians|Forbundet af 1948]]\" (\"League of 1948\"), a homosexual group, is formed in Denmark.\n* '''1948'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[History of Poland (1945\u20131989)|communist authorities of Poland]] make 15 the age of consent for all sexual acts, homosexual or heterosexual.\n\n==1950s==\n* '''1950'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Organization for Sexual Equality, now [[Swedish Federation for Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Rights]] (RFSL), is formed in Sweden; [[East Germany]] partially abrogates the Nazis' emendations to Paragraph 175; The [[Mattachine Society]], the first sustained American homosexual group, is founded in [[Los Angeles]] (11 November); 190 individuals in the United States are dismissed from government employment for their sexual orientation, commencing the [[Lavender scare]].\n* '''1951'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Greece]] decriminalizes homosexuality.\n* '''1951'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jordan]] In 1951, a revision of the Jordanian Criminal Code legalized private, adult, non-commercial, and consensual sodomy, with the age of consent set at 16.\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 \"Spring Fire,\" the first lesbian paperback novel, and the beginning of the lesbian pulp fiction genre, was published in 1952 and sold 1.5 million copies.<ref name=\"amazon.com\">[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1573441872 Spring Fire (Lesbian Pulp Fiction) (9781573441872): Vin Packer: Books]. Amazon.com. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.msvu.ca/en/home/library/aboutthelibrary/policiesprocedures/collectionpolicy/lesbianpulpfictioncollection.aspx Lesbian Pulp Fiction Collection]. Msvu.ca (20 November 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> It was written by lesbian [[Marijane Meaker]] under the false name Vin Packer.<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 In the spring of 1952, Dale Jennings was arrested in Los Angeles for allegedly soliciting a police officer in a bathroom in Westlake Park, now known as [[MacArthur Park]]. His trial drew national attention to the Mattachine Society, and membership increased drastically after Jennings contested the charges, resulting in a hung jury.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Vern L. Bullough, RN|title=Before Stonewall, Activists for Gay and Lesbian Rights in Historical Context|origyear=2002|publisher=Harrington Park Press|location=New York|isbn=1-56023-192-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/424 424]|year=2002|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/424}}</ref>\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Christine Jorgensen]] becomes the first widely publicized person to have undergone [[sex reassignment surgery]], in this case, [[transwoman|male to female]], creating a world-wide sensation.\n* '''1952'''&nbsp;\u2013 In Japan the male homosexual magazine \"[[:ja:\u30a2\u30c9\u30cb\u30b9\u4f1a|Adonis]]\" is launched with the writer [[Yukio Mishima]] as a contributor.\n* '''1953'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Diana Foundation was founded on 19 March 1953 in Houston, TX by a small group of friends. The Diana Foundation is a nonprofit organization and recognized as the oldest continuously active gay organization in the United States and hosts two annual fundraising events including its Diana Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.TheDianaFoundation.org|title=Diana Foundation - Home Page|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418010940/http://www.thedianafoundation.org/|archivedate=18 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''1954'''&nbsp;\u2013 7 June\u2013Mathematical and computer [[genius]] [[Alan Turing]] commits [[suicide]] by [[cyanide]] poisoning, 18 months after being given a choice between two years in prison or libido-reducing hormone treatment for a year as a punishment for homosexuality.<ref name=\"ahodg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.turing.org.uk/bio/part8.html|title=A short on-line biography in eight parts: Part 8&nbsp;\u2014 Alan Turing's Crisis|last=Hodges|first=Andrew|date=1995|work=ALAN TURING founder of computer science|publisher=Andrew Hodges|accessdate=24 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091016020632/http%3A//www.turing.org.uk/bio/part8.html|archivedate=16 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A succession of well-known men, including [[Edward Douglas-Scott-Montagu, 3rd Baron Montagu of Beaulieu|Lord Montagu]], [[Michael Pitt-Rivers]] and [[Peter Wildeblood]], were convicted of [[homosexual]] offences as British police pursued a [[McCarthyism|McCarthy-like]] purge of [[High society (social class)|Society]] homosexuals.<ref>{{cite news|author=Adam Mars-Jones |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/jul/14/against-the-law-the-wildeblood-scandal-the-case-that-rocked-1950s-britain-and-changed-gay-rights |title=The Wildeblood scandal: the trial that rocked 1950s Britain \u2013 and changed gay rights &#124; Books |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref> Arcadie, the first homosexual group in France, is formed.\n* '''1955'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Daughters of Bilitis]] (DOB) was founded in San Francisco by four lesbian couples (including [[Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon]]) and was the first national lesbian political and social organization in the United States.<ref name=\"glbtq1\">[http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/daughters_bilitis.html Daughters of Bilitis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629110236/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/daughters_bilitis.html |date=29 June 2011 }}. glbtq (20 October 2005). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> The group's name came from \"Songs of Bilitis,\" a lesbian-themed song cycle by French poet Pierre Lou\u00ffs, which described the fictional Bilitis as a resident of the Isle of Lesbos alongside Sappho.<ref name=\"glbtq1\"/> DOB's activities included hosting public forums on homosexuality, offering support to isolated, married, and mothering lesbians, and participating in research activities.<ref name=\"glbtq1\"/> Mattachine Society [[New York City|New York]] chapter founded.\n* '''1956'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Ladder (magazine)|The Ladder]]'', the first nationally distributed lesbian publication in the United States, began publication.\n* '''1956'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Thailand]] decriminalizes homosexual acts.\n* '''1956'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Florida Legislative Investigation Committee]] (commonly known as the Johns Committee) established. Failing to find communist ties to civil rights organizations, it investigates homosexuals as a threat to national security.\n* '''1957'''&nbsp;\u2013 The word \"[[Transsexual]]\" is coined by U.S. physician [[Harry Benjamin]]; The [[Wolfenden report|Wolfenden Committee's]] report recommends decriminalizing consensual homosexual behaviour between adults in the United Kingdom; Psychologist [[Evelyn Hooker]] publishes a study showing that homosexual men are as well adjusted as non-homosexual men, which becomes a major factor in the [[American Psychiatric Association]] removing homosexuality from its handbook of disorders in 1973. Homoerotic artist [[Tom of Finland]] first published on the cover of ''[[Physique Pictorial]]'' magazine from Los Angeles.<ref>Hooven III, F. Valentine (2012). ''TOM OF FINLAND LIFE AND WORK OF A GAY HERO''. Berlin: Bruno Gm\u00fcnder Verlag GmbH. pp. 101-102. {{ISBN|978-3-86787-166-2}}.</ref>\n* '''1958'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Homosexual Law Reform Society]] is founded in the United Kingdom; [[Barbara Gittings]] founds the New York chapter of Daughters of Bilitis.\n* '''1958'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[One, Inc. v. Olesen]]'', 355 U.S. 371 (1958), was the first U.S. Supreme Court ruling to deal with homosexuality and the first to address free speech rights with respect to homosexuality. The Supreme Court reversed a lower court ruling that the gay magazine ''[[ONE magazine]]'' violated obscenity laws, thus upholding constitutional protection for pro-homosexual writing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/19/us/legal-history-lgbtq-rights-timeline.html|title=The Court Cases That Changed L.G.B.T.Q. Rights|last=Geidner|first=Chris|date=2019-06-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n* '''1958'''&nbsp;-  The first gay leather bar in the United States, the Gold Coast, opened in Chicago in 1958. It was founded by [[Dom Orejudos]] and [[Chuck Renslow]].\n* '''1959'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], at the time the UK's only national commercial broadcaster, broadcasts the UK\u2019s first TV gay drama, ''South'', starring [[Peter Wyngarde]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Brown, arts correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/mar/16/itv-play-gay-television |title=Newly unearthed ITV play could be first ever gay television drama |work=guardian.co.uk |accessdate=19 April 2013 |location=London |date=16 March 2013}}</ref> The first homosexual uprising in the USA occurs at Cooper's Doughnuts in Los Angeles, USA; rioters were arrested by [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]].<ref>Faderman, Lillian and Timmons, Stuart (2006). ''Gay L.A.: A History of Sexual Outlaws, Power Politics, and Lipstick Lesbians''. Basic Books. p. 1-2. {{ISBN|0-465-02288-X}}.</ref>\n\n==1960s==\n\n* '''1960'''&nbsp;\u2013 Cpls. Fannie Mae Clackum and Grace Garner, U.S. Air Force reservists in the late 1940s and early 1950s, became the first people to successfully challenge their discharges from the U.S. military for being gay, although the ruling turned on the fact that there wasn't enough evidence to show the women were lesbians.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.queerty.com/born-on-the-4th-of-july-12-american-lgbt-war-heroes-20130703/#ixzz2YfVXzqn5 |title=Born On The 4th Of July: 12 American LGBT War Heroes / Queerty |publisher=Queerty.com |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902002347/http://www.queerty.com/born-on-the-4th-of-july-12-american-lgbt-war-heroes-20130703/#ixzz2YfVXzqn5 |archivedate=2 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to scholars, since at least as early as 1960, [[Executive Order 10450]] was applied to ban transgender individuals from serving in the United States military.<ref>[https://www.outserve-sldn.org/about-us/ Our History]</ref>\n* '''1961'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Hungarian People's Republic|Hungary]] decriminalizes sodomy; ''[[Victim (1961 film)|Victim]]'' is the first English-language film to use the word \"homosexual\", and premieres in the UK on 31 August 1961; the [[Holy See|Vatican]] declares that anyone who is \"affected by the perverse inclination\" towards homosexuality should not be allowed to take religious vows or be ordained within the [[Roman Catholic Church]]; ''[[The Rejected]]'', the first [[documentary]] on homosexuality broadcast on American television, is first broadcast on [[KQED (TV)|KQED]] TV in [[San Francisco]] on 11 September 1961; [[Jos\u00e9 Sarria]] becomes the first openly gay candidate for public office in the United States when he runs for the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]].<ref>Miller, p. 347</ref>\n* '''1962'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Illinois]] becomes the first [[U.S. state]] to remove sodomy law from its criminal code through passage of the American Law Institute's [[Model Penal Code]]. While the adopted code did not penalize private sexual relations, it criminalized acts of \"Open Lewdness;\"<ref>1961 Ill. Laws 2044.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Schwartz | first = Louis B.  | title = Morals Offenses and the Model Penal Code | journal = Columbia Law Review | volume = 63 | issue = 4 | pages = 669\u2013686 | date = April 1963 | doi=10.2307/1120582 | jstor=1120582}}</ref> [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]] decriminalizes sodomy. The [[Tavern Guild]], the first gay business association in the United States, was created by gay bar owners in 1962 as a response to continued police harassment and closing of gay bars (including the [[Tay-Bush Inn raid]]), and continued until 1995.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bullough|first=Vern L.|title=Before Stonewall: d Activists for Gay and Lesbian Rights in Historical Context|publisher=Haworth Press|location=New York|date=2002|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/157 157]|isbn=978-1-56023-193-6|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560231936/page/157}}</ref>\n* '''1963'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Eastern Regional Conference of Homophile Organizations|East Coast Homophile Organizations]] (ECHO) is established in Philadelphia; initial members include the regional chapters of [[Daughters of Bilitis]], [[Janus Society]], and [[Mattachine Society]].\n* '''1963'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Israel]] de facto decriminalizes sodomy and sexual acts between men by judicial decision against the enforcement of the relevant section in the old British-mandate law from 1936 (which in fact was never enforced).{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Canada]] sees its first gay-positive organization, ASK, and first gay magazines: ''ASK Newsletter'' (in [[Vancouver]]), and ''[[Gay (magazine)|Gay]]'' (by Gay Publishing Company of [[Toronto]]). ''Gay'' was the first periodical to use the term 'Gay' in the title and expanded quickly, including outstripping the distribution of American publications under the name ''Gay International''. These were quickly followed by ''Two'' (by Gayboy (later Kamp) Publishing Company of Toronto).<ref name=McLeodHistoryofGay>{{cite book |last=McLeod |first=Donald W. |title=A Brief History of Gay: Canada's First Gay Tabloid, 1964\u20131966}}</ref><ref name=GayArchivist>{{cite journal |title=Our Silver Anniversary: Canadians have been organizing for twenty five years! |journal=Newsletter of the Canadian Gay Archives |volume=7 |publisher=National Archives for Lesbians and Gay Men |date=June 1989}}</ref>\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Canada]]: In March 1964, Ted Northe founds the 'Imperial Court of Canada' a monarchist society compromised primarily of drag personalities and becomes a driving force in the effort to achieve equality in Canada.  The Courts of Canada now have over 14 chapters across the country and is the oldest, continuously running, LGBT Organization in Canada.\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first photograph of lesbians on the cover of lesbian magazine ''[[The Ladder (magazine)|The Ladder]]'' was done in September 1964, showing two women from the back, on a beach looking out to sea.\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013  The June 1964 Paul Welch ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' article entitled \"Homosexuality In America\" was the first time a national publication reported on gay issues.\n* '''1964'''&nbsp;\u2013  Created in 1964, the [[Council on Religion and the Homosexual]] was the first group in the U.S. to use the word \"homosexual\" in its name. \n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Council on Religion and the Homosexual]] held an event where local politicians could be questioned about issues concerning gay and lesbian people, including police intimidation. The event marks the first known instance of \"the gay vote\" being sought.\n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[George Klippert|Everett George Klippert]], the last person imprisoned in Canada for homosexuality, is arrested for private, consensual sex with men. After being assessed \"incurably homosexual\", he is sentenced to an indefinite \"preventive detention\" as a dangerous [[sexual offender]]. This was considered by many Canadians to be extremely homophobic, and prompted sympathetic articles in ''[[Maclean's]]'' and ''[[The Toronto Star]]'', eventually leading to increased calls for [[Criminal Law Amendment Act, 1968\u201369|legal reform]] in Canada which passed in 1969.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man imprisoned for being gay to get posthumous pardon from Trudeau|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/man-imprisoned-for-being-gay-to-get-posthumous-pardon-from-trudeau-1.3468287|accessdate=29 February 2016|newspaper=CBC News|date=28 February 2016}}</ref> \n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013 Conservatively dressed gays and lesbians demonstrate outside Independence Hall in Philadelphia on 4 July 1965. This was the first in a series of [[Annual Reminder]]s that took place through 1969.\n* '''1965'''&nbsp;\u2013  Vanguard, an organization of LGBT youth in the low-income [[Tenderloin, San Francisco|Tenderloin]] district, was created in 1965. It is considered the first [[Gay Liberation]] organization in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.foundsf.org/index.php?title=1966_Vanguard_Sweep | title=1966 Vanguard Sweep - FoundSF}}</ref><ref>[http://www.glbthistory.org/Vanguard/images%20vanguard/vanguard-lowres.pdf ]{{dead link|date=May 2019}}</ref>\n* '''1966'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Mattachine Society stages a \"Sip-In\" at [[Julius (restaurant)|Julius Bar]] in New York City challenging a New York State Liquor Authority prohibiting serving alcohol to gays; the National Planning Conference of Homophile Organizations is established (to become NACHO\u2014[[North American Conference of Homophile Organizations]] later that year); the [[Compton's Cafeteria Riot]] occurred in August 1966 by transgender women and Vanguard members in the [[Tenderloin, San Francisco, California|Tenderloin]] district of San Francisco. This incident was one of the first recorded [[transgender]] riots in United States history, preceding the more famous 1969 [[Stonewall Riots]] in New York City by three years. Vanguard was founded to demonstrate for equal rights. The first lesbian to appear on the cover of the lesbian magazine ''The Ladder'' with her face showing was [[Lilli Vincenz]] in January 1966. A coalition of Homosexual organizations organized demonstrations for [[Armed Forces Day (United States)|Armed Forces Day]] to protest the exclusion of LGBT from the U.S. armed services. The Los Angeles group held a 15-car motorcade, which has been identified as the nation's first gay pride parade.<ref name=\"Faderman 2006\">Faderman, Lillian and Timmons, Stuart (2006). ''Gay L.A.: A History of Sexual Outlaws, Power Politics, and Lipstick Lesbians''. Basic Books. {{ISBN|0-465-02288-X}}.</ref> The National Transsexual Counseling Unit is created, becoming the first transgender organization ever and first American transgender organization ever.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_f9KDwAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA177#v=onepage&q&f=false Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender Americans at Risk: Problems and ... edited by Chuck Stewart]</ref> The [[Society for Individual Rights]] opened America\u2019s first gay and lesbian community center. \n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Black Cat Tavern in the Silver Lake neighborhood of Los Angeles is raided on New Year's Day by 12 plainclothes police officers who beat and arrested employees and patrons. The raid prompted a series of protests that began on 5 January 1967, organized by P.R.I.D.E. (Personal Rights in Defense and Education). It's the first use of the term \"Pride\" that came to be associated with LGBT rights.\n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' was first published in September as \"The Los Angeles Advocate,\" a local newsletter alerting gay men to police raids in Los Angeles gay bars.\n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Sexual Offences Act 1967]] decriminalised homosexual acts between two men over 21 years of age ''in private'' in [[England]] and [[Wales]].;<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/02/tories-out-in-force-gay-pride \"From Section 28 to a Home Office float - Tories come out in force at gay march\"], ''The Guardian'', London, 3 July 2010.</ref> The act did not apply to [[Scotland]], [[Northern Ireland]] nor the [[Channel Islands]]; The book ''Homosexual Behavior Among Males'' by Wainwright Churchill breaks ground as a scientific study approaching homosexuality as a fact of life and introduces the term \"homoerotophobia\", a possible precursor to \"homophobia\"; The [[Oscar Wilde Bookshop]], the world's first homosexual-oriented bookstore, opens in New York City; A raid on the [[Black Cat Tavern]] in [[Los Angeles, California]] promotes homosexual rights activity. The Student Homophile League at Columbia University is the first institutionally recognized gay student group in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''1967'''&nbsp;\u2013Grupo Nuestro Mundo (English: \"Our World Group\") is formed in [[Greater Buenos Aires]], the first gay rights organization in [[Argentina]] and [[Latin America]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Perlongher|first=N\u00e9stor|language=Spanish|publisher=Colihue|title=Prosa plebeya Ensayos 1980-1992|year= 1997|isbn=9505811918|page=262|location=Buenos Aires|series=Pu\u00f1aladas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cultura.gob.ar/orgullosos-de-la-diversidad-conoce-la-historia-de-la-marcha-del-orgullo-lgbtiq-en-argentina_6807/|language=Spanish|title=Historia de la Marcha del Orgullo en Argentina|date=November 15, 2018|accessdate=April 16, 2019|publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (Argentina)|Secretariat of Culture]]|location=Argentina}}</ref> ''[[The Homosexuals (CBS Reports)|The Homosexuals]]'', a 1967 episode of the documentary television series CBS Reports, was the first network documentary dealing with the topic of homosexuality. \n* '''1968'''&nbsp;\u2013 Paragraph 175 is eased in East Germany decriminalizing homosexual acts over the age of 18; [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] decriminalizes adult homosexual relations. In Los Angeles, following the arrest of two patrons in a raid, The Patch owner Lee Glaze organized the other patrons to move on the police station. After buying out a nearby flower shop, the demonstrators caravanned to the station, festooned it with the flowers and bailed out the arrested men.<ref name=\"Faderman 2006\"/> According to the online encyclopedia [[glbtq.com]], \"In the aftermath of the riot at [[Compton's Cafeteria Riot|Compton's]], a network of transgender social, psychological, and medical support services was established, which culminated in 1968 with the creation of the National Transsexual Counseling Unit [NTCU], the first such peer-run support and advocacy organization in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/san_francisco,2.html |title=Social sciences - San Francisco |publisher=glbtq |accessdate=2012-05-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705201921/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/san_francisco%2C2.html |archivedate=2015-07-05 }}</ref>\n* '''1969'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Stonewall riots]] occur in [[New York City]]; [[Paragraph 175]] is eased in [[West Germany]]; [[Bill C-150]] is passed, decriminalizing homosexuality in [[Canada]]. [[Pierre Trudeau]], the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], is quoted as having said: \"The state has no place in the bedrooms of the nation.\"; [[People's Republic of Poland|Poland]] decriminalizes homosexual [[prostitution]]; An [[Australia]]n arm of the [[Daughters of Bilitis]] forms in [[Melbourne]] and is considered Australia's first homosexual rights organisation.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The [[Gay Liberation Front]] is formed in America, and it is the first gay organization to use \"gay\" in its name. On 31 December 1969, the [[Cockettes]] perform for the first time at the Palace Theatre on Union and Columbus in the [[North Beach, San Francisco|North Beach]] neighborhood of San Francisco.\n\n==1970s==\n\n* '''1970'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first Gay Liberation Day March is held in New York City; The first LGBT Pride Parade is held in New York; The first \"Gay-in\" held in San Francisco; [[Carl Wittman]] writes ''A Gay Manifesto'';<ref name=\"cwittman\">{{cite web|url=http://library.gayhomeland.org/0006/EN/A_Gay_Manifesto.htm|title=A Gay Manifesto (1970)|last=Wittman|first=Carl|year=1970|publisher=Gay Homeland Foundation|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Blasius|first=Mark|author2=Shane Phelan |title=We are everywhere: a historical sourcebook in gay and lesbian politics|year=1997|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-90859-0|pages=380\u201390}}</ref> CAMP (Campaign Against Moral Persecution) is formed in [[Australia]];<ref name=\"dc.identifier.TSID 2964\">{{cite web|url=http://heuristscholar.org/cocoon/dos/browser/item/422/ |title=Lesbians |last=Jennings |first=Rebecca |date=21 October 2008 |publisher=Dictionary of Sydney |accessdate=28 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726150518/http://heuristscholar.org/cocoon/dos/browser/item/422/ |archivedate=26 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Willett|first=Graham |title=Living out loud: a history of gay and lesbian activism in Australia|year=2000|publisher=Allen & Unwin|page=33}}</ref> The Task Force on Gay Liberation formed within the [[American Library Association]]. Now known as the [[Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, and Transgender Round Table|GLBT Round Table]], this organization is the oldest LGBTQ professional organization in the United States.<ref name=\"keilty\">{{cite journal|last=Keilty|first=Patrick|title=Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Information Needs|journal=Encyclopedia of Library and Information Science, 3rd Edition|year=2009|pages=3275\u20133280|doi=10.1081/E-ELIS3-120044121|isbn=978-0-8493-9712-7}}</ref> In November, the first gay rights march occurs in the UK at Highbury Fields following the arrest of an activist from the Young Liberals for importuning.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mHAe63jpuOQC&pg=PA229&dq \"Sexual Politics: Sexuality, Family Planning, and the British Left from the 1880s to the Present Day\"], Stephen Brooke. OUP Oxford, 24 Nov 2011. p. 229. Retrieved 4 Feb 2017</ref>\n* '''1971'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Society Five]] (a homosexual rights organization) is formed in [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]], Australia; Homosexuality is decriminalized in [[Austria]], [[Costa Rica]] and [[Finland]]; [[Colorado]] and [[Oregon]] repeal sodomy laws; [[Idaho]] repeals the sodomy law&nbsp;\u2014 Then re-instates the repealed sodomy law because of outrage among [[Mormons]] and [[Catholics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/getequal/gettingrid.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929133832/http://www.aclu.org/getequal/gettingrid.html|archivedate=2007-09-29|title=Getting Rid of Sodomy Laws: History and Strategy that Led to the Lawrence Decision|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glapn.org/sodomylaws/usa/idaho/idaho.htm|title=Sodomy Laws, Idaho|accessdate=6 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109200305/http://www.glapn.org/sodomylaws/usa/idaho/idaho.htm|archivedate=9 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Netherlands changes the homosexual age of consent to 16, the same as the straight age of consent; The U.S. [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] calls for the repeal of all [[victimless crime]] laws, including the sodomy laws; Dr. [[Franklin E. Kameny|Frank Kameny]] becomes the first openly gay candidate for the [[United States Congress]]; The [[University of Michigan]] establishes the first collegiate LGBT programs office, then known as the \"Gay Advocate's Office.\" The UK [[Gay Liberation Front]] (GLF) was recognized as a political movement in the national press and was holding weekly meetings of 200 to 300 people.;<ref>{{cite news|title=An Alternative to Sexual Shame: Impact of the new militancy among homosexual groups|newspaper=The Times|author=Victoria Brittain|date=28 August 1971|page=12}}</ref> [[George Klippert]], the last man jailed for homosexuality in Canada, is released from prison. [[:ja:\u6771\u90f7\u5065|Ken Togo]] ran for national election, in [[Japan]]. During a UCLA conference called \"The Homosexual in America,\" [[Betty Berzon]] became the first psychotherapist in the country to come out as gay to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=561|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online - Pioneering activist Betty Berzon dies|work=Bay Area Reporter|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> ''[[Boys in the Sand]]'' was the first gay porn film to include credits, to achieve crossover success, to be reviewed by ''Variety'',<ref>Jeffrey Escoffier, \"Beefcake to Hardcore: Gay Pornography and the Sexual Revolution,\" in ''Sex Scene. Media and the Sexual Revolution'', ed. Eric Schaefer, Duke University Press, 2014, {{ISBN|9780822356424}}, pp. 319-347, at p. 319.</ref> and one of the earliest porn films, after 1969's ''[[Blue Movie]]''<ref name=\"NYT-19690722\">{{cite news |last=Canby |first=Vincent |authorlink=Vincent Canby |title=Movie Review - Blue Movie (1968) Screen: Andy Warhol's 'Blue Movie' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9507E5D91738E63ABC4A51DFB1668382679EDE |date=22 July 1969 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-19690810\">{{cite news |last=Canby |first=Vincent |authorlink=Vincent Canby |title=Warhol's Red Hot and 'Blue' Movie. D1. Print. (behind paywall) |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9807E4D91739EF3BBC4852DFBE668382679EDE |date=10 August 1969 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"WS-1969\">{{cite web |last=Comenas |first=Gary |title=July 21, 1969: Andy Warhol's Blue Movie Opens |url=http://www.warholstars.org/andy-warhol-1969.html |date=1969 |work=WarholStars.org |accessdate=20 January 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"JW-2015\">{{cite book |last=Haggerty |first=George E. |title=A Companion to Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Studies |url=https://books.google.com/?id=eUf3CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA339&lpg=PA339&dq=Variety+June+18,+1969+%22Blue+Movie%22#v=onepage&q=Variety%20June%2018%2C%201969%20%22Blue%20Movie%22&f=false |date=2015 |work=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |page=339 |accessdate=20 January 2016 |isbn=9781119000853 }}</ref> by [[Andy Warhol]], to gain mainstream credibility, preceding 1972's ''[[Deep Throat (film)|Deep Throat]]'' by nearly a year. It was promoted with an advertising campaign unprecedented for a pornographic feature, premiered in [[New York City]] in 1971 and was an immediate critical and commercial success.<ref name=Wakefield>[http://www.therialtoreport.com/2013/06/16/wakefield-poole-theater-dance-and-pornpodcast-14/ 'Wakefield Poole: Theater, Dance, and Porn'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131043139/http://www.therialtoreport.com/2013/06/16/wakefield-poole-theater-dance-and-pornpodcast-14/ |date=31 January 2014 }}, [http://www.therialtoreport.com The Rialto Report], audio interview with Wakefield Poole</ref>  The [[Alice B. Toklas Democratic Club]], founded in San Francisco in 1971, was the first gay Democratic club of the United States. \n* '''1972'''&nbsp;\u2013 Sweden becomes the first country in the world to allow transsexuals to legally change their sex, and provides free hormone therapy;<ref name=quistbergh2001>{{cite web |url=http://www.quistbergh.se/view/514 |language=Swedish |title=Jag k\u00e4nner mig lite homosexuell idag |trans-title=I feel a bit gay today |accessdate=12 December 2009 |year=2001 |first=Frederick Quist |last=Bergh}}</ref> Hawaii legalizes homosexuality; In [[South Australia]], a consenting adults in private-type legal defence was introduced; [[Norway]] decriminalizes homosexuality; [[East Lansing, Michigan]] and [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] and San Francisco, California become the first cities in United States to pass a homosexual rights ordinance. [[Jim Foster (activist)|Jim Foster]], San Francisco and [[Madeline Davis]], [[Buffalo, New York]], first openly gay and lesbian delegates to the Democratic Convention, Miami, McGovern; give the first speeches advocating a gay rights plank in the Democratic Party Platform. \"Stonewall Nation\", the first gay anthem is written and recorded by Madeline Davis and is produced on 45 rpm record by the Mattachine Society of the [[Niagara Frontier]]. Lesbianism 101, the first lesbianism course in the U.S., is taught at the University of Buffalo by Margaret Small and Madeline Davis. Queens, NY schoolteacher Jeanne Manford marched with her gay son, gay rights activist Morty Manford, in New York's Christopher Street Liberation Day march. This was the origin of the straight ally movement and of [[PFLAG]] - (originally Parents of Gays, then Parents, Families and Friends of Lesbians and Gays, now simply PFLAG.)<ref name=\"pflag1973\">{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=267 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=community.pflag.org |date=26 March 1973 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617013027/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=267 |archivedate=17 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Nancy Wechsler became the first openly gay or lesbian person in political office in America; she was elected to the Ann Arbor City Council in 1972 as a member of the Human Rights Party and came out as a lesbian during her first and only term there.<ref>[http://www.equalitygiving.org/Gay-Politicians Gay Politicians]. eQualityGiving. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Also in 1972, Camille Mitchell became the first open lesbian to be awarded custody of her children in a divorce case, although the judge restricted the arrangement by precluding Ms. Mitchell's lover from moving in with her and the children.<ref name=\"glinn.com\">[http://www.glinn.com/news/tline3.htm GLINN's Timeline of Gay and Lesbian Family Issues]. Glinn.com. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Freda Smith became the first openly lesbian minister in the Metropolitan Community Church (she was also their first female minister).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodhopemcc.org/about-us/general/denomination.html |title=Denomination - Good Hope MCC, Cape Town, South Africa |publisher=goodhopemcc.org |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/metro_comm_church.html |title=Metropolitan Community Church |publisher=glbtq.com |date=6 October 1968 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524234619/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/metro_comm_church.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Beth Chayim Chadashim]] was founded in 1972 as the first LGBT synagogue in the world, and the first LGBT synagogue recognized by the [[Union for Reform Judaism]].<ref name=\"laconservancy1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.laconservancy.org/locations/beth-chayim-chadashim |title=Beth Chayim Chadashim &#124; Los Angeles Conservancy |publisher=Laconservancy.org |date= |accessdate=2017-08-24}}</ref> A [[Quaker]] group, the Committee of Friends on Bisexuality, issued the \"Ithaca Statement on Bisexuality\" supporting bisexuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bimedia.org/1984/june-1972-the-ithaca-statement/ |title=BiMedia &#124; Bisexual News & Opinion from |publisher=BiMedia.org |date=2012-02-10 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> The Statement, which may have been \"the first public declaration of the bisexual movement\" and \"was certainly the first statement on bisexuality issued by an American religious assembly,\" appeared in the Quaker ''[[Friends Journal]]'' and ''The Advocate'' in 1972.<ref name=donaldson>{{Cite book | last = Donaldson | first = Stephen | year = 1995 | contribution = The Bisexual Movement's Beginnings in the 70s: A Personal Retrospective | pages = [https://archive.org/details/bisexualpolitics00tuck/page/31 31\u201345] | editor-last = Tucker | editor-first = Naomi | title = Bisexual Politics: Theories, Queries, & Visions | place = New York | publisher = Harrington Park Press | isbn = 1-56023-869-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/bisexualpolitics00tuck/page/31 }}</ref><ref name=highleyman>{{cite news\n  |url=http://www.camprehoboth.com/issue07_11_03/pastout.htm\n  |title=PAST Out: What is the history of the bisexual movement?\n  |accessdate=2008-03-18\n  |last=Highleyman\n  |first=Liz\n  |date=2003-07-11\n  |work=LETTERS From CAMP Rehoboth\n  |volume=13\n  |number=8\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080531051440/http://www.camprehoboth.com/issue07_11_03/pastout.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Martin|first=Robert|title=Quakers 'come out' at conference|journal=The Advocate|date=1972-08-02|issue=91|page=8}}</ref> Today Quakers have varying opinions on [[LGBT]] people and rights, with some Quaker groups more accepting than others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org/resources/entry/stances-of-faiths-on-lgbt-issues-religious-society-of-friends-quakers |title=Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: Religious Society of Friends (Quakers) &#124; Resources &#124; Human Rights Campaign |publisher=Hrc.org |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> The first gay bar in San Francisco to have clear windows was Twin Peaks Tavern, which removed its blacked-out windows in 1972.\n* '''1973'''&nbsp;\u2013 On 15 October the Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatry Federal Council declares homosexuality not an illness \u2013 the first such body in the world to do so; in December the American Psychiatric Association removes homosexuality from its [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] (DSM-II), based largely on the research and advocacy of Evelyn Hooker. The first formal meeting of [[PFLAG]] took place on 26 March 1973 at the Metropolitan-Duane Methodist Church in Greenwich Village (now the Church of the Village). Approximately 20 people attended, including founder Jeanne Manford, her husband Jules, son Morty, Dick and Amy Ashworth, [[Metropolitan Community Church]] founder Reverend Troy Perry, and more.<ref name=\"pflag1973\"/> [[Malta]] legalizes homosexuality; In West Germany, the age of consent is reduced for homosexuals to 18 (though it is 14 for heterosexuals).{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}; [[Sally Miller Gearhart]] became the first open lesbian to obtain a tenure-track faculty position when she was hired by San Francisco State University, where she helped establish one of the first women and gender study programs in the country.<ref>[http://giving.uoregon.edu/oregon-outlook/summer-2009/honoring-diversity-and-courage Honoring diversity and courage]. giving.uoregon.edu. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> [[Lavender Country]], an [[United States|American]] [[country music]] band, released a self-titled album which is the first known [[gay]]-themed album in country music history.<ref name=\"Dickinson\">{{cite journal |last= Dickinson |first= Chris |year= 2000 |title= Country Undetectable: Gay Artists in Country Music |journal= Journal of Country Music |volume= XXI |issue= 1 |pages= 28\u201339 |url= http://www.queermusicheritage.us/mar2005jcm.html |accessdate= 4 August 2009}}</ref>\n* '''1974'''&nbsp;\u2013 Chile allows a trans person to legally change her name and gender on the birth certificate  after undergoing sex reassignment surgery, becoming the second country in the world to do so.<ref>{{cite web |title=La revoluci\u00f3n de Marcia Alejandra |url=https://www.latercera.com/tendencias/noticia/la-revolucion-marcia-alejandra/132019/ |website=La Tercera |accessdate=25 November 2018 |language=es-ES |date=13 April 2018}}</ref> [[Kathy Kozachenko]] becomes the first openly gay American elected to public office when she wins a seat on the [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] city council; In New York City [[Fritz Klein (sex researcher)|Dr. Fritz Klein]] founds the Bisexual Forum, the first [[support group]] for the [[Bisexual Community]]; [[Elaine Noble]] becomes the second openly gay American elected to public office when she wins a seat in the [[Massachusetts State House]]; Inspired by Noble, [[Minnesota]] state legislator [[Allan Spear]] comes out in a newspaper interview; [[Ohio]] repeals sodomy laws. [[Robert Grant (Christian Leader)|Robert Grant]] founds American Christian Cause to oppose the \"[[gay agenda]]\", the beginning of modern Christian politics in America. In London, the first openly [[London Lesbian and Gay Switchboard|LGBT telephone help line]] opens, followed one year later by the Brighton Lesbian and Gay Switchboard;{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} the [[Brunswick Four]] are arrested on 5 January 1974, in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]. This incident of [[Lesbophobia]] galvanizes the Toronto Lesbian and Gay community;<ref>Warner, Tom. \u2018\u2019Never Going Back: A History of Queer Activism in Canada\u2019\u2019, 2002 University of Toronto Press, {{ISBN|0-8020-8460-5}} p41</ref> the [[National Socialist League (United States)|National Socialist League]] (The ''Gay Nazi Party'') is founded in [[Los Angeles, California]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} The first openly gay or lesbian person to be elected to any political office in America was [[Kathy Kozachenko]], who was elected to the Ann Arbor City Council in April 1974.<ref>[http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials.html >> social sciences >> Elected Officials] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022195646/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials.html |date=22 October 2009 }}. glbtq. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Also in 1974, the [[Lesbian Herstory Archives]] opened to the public in the New York apartment of lesbian couple [[Joan Nestle]] and Deborah Edel; it has the world's largest collection of materials by and about lesbians and their communities.<ref>[http://www.lesbianherstoryarchives.org/ The Lesbian Herstory Archives]. The Lesbian Herstory Archives. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> Also in 1974, [[Angela Morley]] became the first openly transgender person to be nominated for an [[Academy Award]], when she was nominated for one in the category of Best Music, Original Song Score/Adaptation for ''The Little Prince'' (1974), a nomination shared with [[Alan Jay Lerner]], [[Frederick Loewe]], and [[Douglas Gamley]]. The world's first gay softball league was formed in San Francisco in 1974 as the Community Softball League, which eventually included both women's and men's teams. The teams, usually sponsored by gay bars,  competed against each other and against the San Francisco Police softball team.<ref>[http://thecastro.net/street/softball/softballpage.html Uncle Donald's Castro Street] Retrieved December 23, 2016\n</ref>\n* '''1975'''&nbsp;\u2013 Twelve women became the first group of women in Japan to publicly identify as lesbians, publishing one issue of a magazine called Subarashi Onna (Wonderful Women).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/pajx3m/lesbian-history-archive-artifacts |title=The First Lesbian Porn and 10 Other Revealing Artifacts from Lesbian History |publisher=VICE |date= |accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref> Homosexuality is legalized in [[California]] due to the [[Consenting Adult Sex Bill]], authored by and successfully lobbied for in the state legislature by State Assemblyman from San Francisco [[Willie Brown (politician)|Willie Brown]]; [[Leonard Matlovich]], a Technical Sergeant in the United States Air Force, becomes the first U.S. gay service member to purposely out himself to fight their ban; South Australia becomes the first state in Australia to make homosexuality legal between consenting adults in private. Panama is the third country in the world to allow transsexuals who have gone through gender reassignment surgery to get their personal documents reflecting their new sex; {{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}  UK journal [[Gay Left]] begins publication;<ref>[http://knittingcircle.org.uk/gayleftcollective.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070114112010/http://knittingcircle.org.uk/gayleftcollective.html|date=14 January 2007}}</ref> [[Minneapolis]] becomes the first city in the United States to pass trans-inclusive civil rights protection legislation;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/transgender_activism.html |title=Transgender Activism |publisher=glbtq.com |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525105458/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/transgender_activism.html |archivedate=25 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Clela Rorex, a clerk in Boulder County, Colorado, issues the first same-sex marriage licenses in the United States, issuing the very first of them to Dave McCord and Dave Zamora, on 26 March 1975.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.elephantjournal.com/2009/02/gregory-hinton-for-daily-camera-march-26-1975-the-first-same-sex-marriage-licenses-in-the-united-states-were-heroically-issued-in-boulder-by-county-clerk-clela-rorex/|title=March 26, 1975, the first same-sex marriage licenses in the United States were heroically issued in Boulder by County Clerk, Clela Rorex.|work=Elephant Journal|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> Six same-sex marriages were performed as a result of her giving out licenses, but all of the marriages were overturned later that year.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Maureen Colquhoun becomes the UK's first out lesbian MP after coming out in 1975. She is the UK's first openly gay MP.\n[[File:Gay Rights demonstration, NYC 1976.jpg|thumb|Gay rights protesters in New York City, protesting at the United States' [[1976 Democratic National Convention]]]]\n* '''1976'''&nbsp;\u2013 Robert Grant founds the [[Christian Voice (United States)|Christian Voice]] to take his anti-homosexual-rights crusade national in United States; the Homosexual Law Reform Coalition and the Gay Teachers Group are started in Australia; the [[Australian Capital Territory]] decriminalizes homosexuality between consenting adults in private and equalizes the age of consent; Out Minnesota state legislator [[Allan Spear]] is reelected; and Denmark equalizes the age of consent.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Association of homosexual liberation was founded in Japan.<ref name=\"boyfriend\">\u30aa\u30c8\u30b3\u30ce\u30b3\u306e\u305f\u3081\u306e\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30d5\u30ec\u30f3\u30c9 (1986)</ref> [[Tom Gallagher (diplomat)|Tom Gallagher]] became the first United States Foreign Service officer to come out as gay; he quit the Foreign Service after that, as  he would have been unable to obtain a security clearance.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\">{{cite news |last1=Genzlinger |first1=Neil |title=Tom Gallagher, Diplomat Who Became a Gay Activist, Dies At 77 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/12/obituaries/tom-gallagher-diplomat-who-became-a-gay-activist-dies-at-77.html |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=July 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"advocateobit\">{{cite news |last1=Ring |first1=Trudy |title=Tom Gallagher, First Foreign Service Officer to Come Out, Dies at 77 |url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/2018/7/13/tom-gallagher-first-foreign-service-officer-come-out-dies-77 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |work=The Advocate |date=July 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"washpostobit\">{{cite news |last1=Plokihii |first1=Olesia |title=Tom Gallagher, Foreign Service officer who quit to live as openly gay, dies at 77 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/tom-gallagher-foreign-service-officer-who-quit-to-live-as-openly-gay-dies-at-77/2018/07/20/e706be96-8b6f-11e8-a345-a1bf7847b375_story.html |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |work=The Washington Post |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Patricia Nell Warren]]'s  third novel, ''The Fancy Dancer'' (1976) was the first bestseller to portray a [[gay priest]] and to explore [[LGBT and rurality|gay life in a small town]].\n* '''1977'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Harvey Milk]] is elected city-county supervisor in San Francisco, becoming the first openly gay or lesbian candidate elected to political office in California, the seventh openly gay/lesbian elected official nationally, and the third man to be openly gay at time of his election. [[Dade County, Florida]] enacts a Human Rights Ordinance; it is repealed the same year after a militant anti-homosexual-rights campaign led by [[Anita Bryant]]. [[Quebec]] becomes the first jurisdiction larger than a city or county in the world to prohibit [[discrimination]] based on [[sexual orientation]] in the public and private sectors; [[Croatia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Slovenia]] and [[Vojvodina]] legalise homosexuality.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Welsh author [[Jeffrey Weeks (sociologist)|Jeffrey Weeks]] publishes ''Coming Out'';<ref>Coming Out: Homosexual Politics in Britain from the Nineteenth Century to the Present, Quartet Books 1977; 2nd revised edition, with new chapter and bibliography, 1990</ref> [[File:Gay flag 8.svg|thumb|Original eight-color version of the [[Rainbow flag (LGBT movement)|LGBT pride flag]]]] Publication of the first issue of [[Gaysweek]], NYC's first mainstream gay weekly. Police raided a house outside of Boston outraging the gay community. In response the Boston-Boise Committee was formed.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lib.neu.edu/archives/voices/gl_sexual2.htm | title = Gay Community Fights Back (1978) | accessdate = 26 August 2010 | work = We Raise Our Voices | publisher = Northeastern University | archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6611tUXn0?url=http://www.lib.neu.edu/archives/voices/gl_sexual2.htm | archive-date = 8 March 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Ann Holmes Redding|Anne Holmes]] became the first openly lesbian minister ordained by the United Church of Christ;<ref>Jack Rogers [https://books.google.com/books?id=MUAL7iZHVN4C&pg=PA139 Jesus, the Bible, and Homosexuality: Explode the Myths, Heal the Church], Westminster John Knox Press, 2009 {{ISBN|0-664-23397-X}} p. 139</ref> [[Ellen Barrett]] became the first openly lesbian priest ordained by the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church of the United States]] (serving the Diocese of New York).<ref>[http://www.integrityusa.org/FAQs/index.htm FAQs] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314234504/http://www.integrityusa.org/FAQs/index.htm |date=14 March 2012 }}. Integrityusa.org. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref><ref>David Hein, Gardiner H. Shattuck [https://books.google.com/books?id=_iK5VggudLkC&pg=PA143 The Episcopalians], Greenwood Publishing Group, 2004 {{ISBN|0313229589}} p. 143</ref> The first lesbian mystery novel in America was published; it was ''Angel Dance'', by Mary F. Beal.<ref>{{cite book|title=Angel Dance: A Classic Lesbian Thriller: Mary F. Beal: 9780895944177 |isbn = 0895944170}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Laughlin |first=Anne |url=http://www.afterellen.com/column/lifes-little-lesbian-mysteries-1 |title=Life's Little Lesbian Mysteries: The good ol' days |publisher=afterellen.com |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120722054207/http%3A%2F%2Fwww.afterellen.com%2Fcolumn%2Flifes-little-lesbian-mysteries-1 |archivedate=22 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The [[National Center for Lesbian Rights]] was founded. [[Shakuntala Devi]] published the first<ref>{{Cite journal | title=Globalizing queer? AIDS, homophobia and the politics of sexual identity in India | author=Subir K Kole | journal=Globalization and Health | doi=10.1186/1744-8603-3-8 | date=2007-07-11 | pmid=17623106 | volume=3 | page=8 | pmc=2018684 }}: \"The first academic book on Indian homosexuals appeared in 1977 (The World of Homosexuals) written by [[Shakuntala Devi]], the mathematics wunderkind who was internationally known as the human computer. This book treated homosexuality in a positive light and reviewed the socio-cultural and legal situation of homosexuality in India and contrasted that with the then gay liberation movement in USA.\"</ref> study of homosexuality in India.<ref name=\"worldoh\">{{Cite book | title=The World of Homosexuals | author=Shakuntala Devi | publisher=Vikas Publishing House | year=1977 | isbn=9780706904789 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=PBwbAAAAYAAJ }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | title=Homosexuality and Religion | author=Jeffrey S. Siker | publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group | year=2006 | isbn=9780313330889 | page=127 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=PUqn33H-uDYC&pg=PA127&dq=%22The+World+of+Homosexuals%22 }}: \"In her 1977 book, mathematician [[Shakuntala Devi]] interviewed...\"</ref> Platonica Club and Front Runners were founded in Japan.<ref name = \"boyfriend\" /> San Francisco hosted the world's first gay film festival in 1977.<ref>William Lipsky, Gay and Lesbian San Francisco, Arcadia Publishing, 2006</ref> [[Peter Adair]], Nancy Adair and other members of the Mariposa Film Group premiered the groundbreaking documentary on coming out, ''[[Word Is Out: Stories of Some of Our Lives]]'',  at the [[Castro Theater]] in 1977. The film was the first feature-length documentary on gay identity by gay and lesbian filmmakers.<ref name=\"summing\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/30/movies/homevideo/30kehr.html | title=New DVDs, 'Word is Out' and 'Meredith Monk'| newspaper=The New York Times| date=2010-05-28| last1=Kehr| first1=Dave}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Eg_4Eus1sE0C&pg=PA327 | title=Homosexuality Bibliography: 1976-1982. Second supplement| isbn=9780810817531| last1=Parker| first1=William| year=1985}}</ref> [[Beth Chayim Chadashim]] became the first LGBT synagogue to own its own building.<ref name=\"laconservancy1\"/> On March 26, 1977, [[Frank Kameny]] and a dozen other members of the gay and lesbian community, under the leadership of the then-[[National LGBTQ Task Force|National Gay Task Force]], briefed then-Public Liaison [[Midge Costanza]] on much-needed changes in federal laws and policies. This was the first time that gay rights were officially discussed at the White House.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.thetaskforce.org/press/releases/pr_kameny_101111|title = Task Force mourns the death of pioneering gay activist and founding board member Frank Kameny|publisher = National Gay and Lesbian Task Force|date = October 11, 2011|accessdate = July 9, 2014|quote = he and a dozen other members of our community briefed then-Public Liaison Midge Costanza|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141003172359/http://www.thetaskforce.org/press/releases/pr_kameny_101111|archivedate = October 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2010/03/24/lgbt-advocate-white-house-aide-costanza-dies|title = LGBT Advocate White House Aide Costanza Dies|publisher = Advocate.com|date = March 24, 2010|accessdate = July 9, 2014|quote = Costanza met with gay activists including Frank Kameny, Troy Perry, Elaine Noble, and Task Force co\u2013executive directors Bruce Voeller and Jean O'Leary.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140714214349/http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2010/03/24/lgbt-advocate-white-house-aide-costanza-dies|archive-date = July 14, 2014|url-status = live|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''1978'''&nbsp;\u2013 San Francisco Supervisor Harvey Milk and Mayor [[George Moscone]] are [[Moscone\u2013Milk assassinations|assassinated]] by former Supervisor [[Dan White]]; the first [[Sydney Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras]] is held, with 2000 people attending and 53 subsequently arrested and some seriously beaten by police. The [[rainbow flag (gay movement)|rainbow flag]] is first used as a symbol of gay pride; Sweden establishes a uniform age of consent. [[Samois]], the earliest known lesbian-feminist [[BDSM]] organization, is founded in San Francisco; well-known members of the group include [[Patrick Califia]] and [[Gayle Rubin]]; the group is among the very earliest advocates of what came to be known as [[sex-positive feminism]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}; The International Lesbian and Gay Association (ILGA) is established.<ref>[http://ilga.org/aboutilga.asp about ILGA] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422045221/http://ilga.org/aboutilga.asp |date=22 April 2009 }}</ref> Robin Tyler became the first out lesbian on U.S. national television, appearing on a Showtime comedy special hosted by [[Phyllis Diller]]. The same year she released her comedy album, ''Always a Bridesmaid, Never a Groom'', the first comedy album by an out lesbian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/tyler_r_ssh.html |title=Tyler, Robin |publisher=glbtq.com |date=8 April 1942 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010063902/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/tyler_r_ssh.html |archivedate=10 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> The [[San Francisco Lesbian/Gay Freedom Band]] was founded by Jon Reed Sims in 1978 as the San Francisco Gay Freedom Day Marching Band and Twirling Corp. Upon its founding in 1978, it became the first openly gay musical group in the world. San Francisco became the first city in America to have a recruitment drive for gay police officers, bringing in over 350 applications.<ref name=\"Evening Indy\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bgEMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=61gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6840,2315504|title=Homosexual Police Officers|last1=Cohen|first1=Susan|date=April 25, 1979|newspaper=The Evening Independent|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> Allen Bennett became the first openly gay rabbi in the United States.<ref name=\"Kaplan2005\">{{cite book|author=Dana Evan Kaplan|title=The Cambridge Companion to American Judaism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ntyKPd2-wUoC&pg=PA75|date=8 August 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-52951-8|pages=75\u2013}}</ref>\n* '''1979'''&nbsp;\u2013 The first national homosexual rights march on [[Washington, D.C.]] is held; The [[White Night riots]] occur, [[Harry Hay]] issues the first call for a [[Radical Faerie]] gathering in [[Arizona]], and The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence first appear in public on Easter Sunday in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesisters.org/sistory |title=Sistory |publisher=Thesisters.org |accessdate=2015-04-22}}</ref> [[Cuba]] and Spain decriminalize homosexuality.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} [[Esta Noche (gay bar)|Esta Noche]], a gay bar located at 3079 16th & Mission Street in San Francisco, was the first gay Latino bar in San Francisco, and first opened in 1979. A number of people in [[Sweden]] called in sick with a case of ''being homosexual,'' in protest of homosexuality being classified [[Homosexuality and psychology|as an illness]]. This was followed by an activist occupation of the main office of the ''[[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]]''. Within a few months, Sweden became the first country in the world to remove homosexuality as an illness.<ref name=quistbergh2001/> Japan Gay Center was established in Japan.<ref name = \"boyfriend\" /> Grady Quinn and Randy Rohl became the first known gay couple to attend a high school prom when they attended the Lincoln High School prom in Sioux Falls, South Dakota on May 23, 1979.<ref>https://www.apnews.com/0538ff70caff44b6b53d687866a85187</ref>\n\n==1980s==\n\n* '''1980'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[United States Democratic Party]] becomes the first major political party in the U.S. to endorse a homosexual rights platform plank; [[Scotland]] decriminalizes homosexuality; The [[Human Rights Campaign]] Fund is founded by [[Steve Endean]]; The Human Rights Campaign is America's largest civil rights organization working to achieve lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender equality.<ref name=HRC>{{cite web|title=HRC&nbsp;\u2013 About Us |publisher=Human Rights Campaign |year=2009 |url=http://www.hrc.org/about_us/ |accessdate=9 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521090000/http://www.hrc.org/about_us/ |archivedate=21 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}&nbsp;\u2013. A coalition of Homosexual organizations organized demonstrations for [[Armed Forces Day (United States)|Armed Forces Day]] to protest the exclusion of LGBT from the U.S. armed services. The Los Angeles group held a 15-car motorcade, which has been identified as the nation's first gay pride parade.</ref> [[Lionel Blue]] becomes the first British rabbi to come out as gay;<ref name=\"lionel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2016/12/20/news-opinion/world/rabbi-lionel-blue-the-first-openly-gay-british-rabbi-dies-at-86 |title=Rabbi Lionel Blue, the first openly gay British rabbi, dies at 86 &#124; Jewish Telegraphic Agency |publisher=Jta.org |date=2016-12-20 |accessdate=2017-06-22}}</ref> \"[[First Black Lesbian Conference|Becoming Visible: The First Black Lesbian Conference]]\" is held at the [[The Women's Building (San Francisco)|Women's Building]], from October 17 to 19, 1980. It has been credited as the first conference for [[African Americans|African-American]] [[lesbian]] women.<ref name=\":3\">Kyper, John. \"Black Lesbians Meet in October.\" ''Coming Up: A Calendar of Events'' 1 (Oct. 1980): 1. Web.</ref> The [[Socialist Party USA]] nominates an openly gay man, [[David McReynolds]], as its (and America's) first openly gay presidential candidate in 1980.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thevillager.com/2018/08/david-mcreynolds-pacifist-and-socialist-leader-is-dead-at-88/ |title=David McReynolds, pacifist and socialist leader, is dead at 88 |newspaper=The Villager |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n* '''1981'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[European Court of Human Rights]] in ''[[Dudgeon v United Kingdom]]'' strikes down Northern Ireland's criminalisation of homosexual acts between consenting adults, leading to Northern Ireland decriminalising homosexual sex the following year; [[Victoria (Australia)]] and [[Colombia]] decriminalize homosexuality with a uniform age of consent; The [[Moral Majority]] starts its anti-homosexual crusade; Norway becomes the first country in the world to enact a law to prevent discrimination against homosexuals; [[Hong Kong]]'s first sex-change operation is performed. The first official documentation of the condition to be known as [[AIDS]] was published by the US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)]] on 5 June 1981.<ref>CDC (5 June 1981) \u2018Pheumocystis Pneumonia&nbsp;\u2013 Los Angeles\u2019, MMWR, Vol. 30 No. 21.</ref> Tennis player [[Billie Jean King]] became the first prominent professional athlete to come out as a lesbian, when her relationship with her secretary Marilyn Barnett became public in a May 1981 \"[[palimony]]\" lawsuit filed by Barnett.<ref name = \"TimesOnline-20071209\">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/tennis/article3021888.ece The Big Interview: Billie Jean King], 9 December 2007.</ref> Due to this she lost all of her endorsements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/other_sports/tennis/articles/2006/12/03/no_royalty_like_king/?page=4 |title=No royalty like King |work=Boston Globe  |date=3 December 2006 |accessdate=4 July 2011 |first=Stan |last=Grossfeld}}</ref> [[Mary C. Morgan]] became the first openly gay or lesbian judge in America when she was appointed by California Governor Jerry Brown to the San Francisco Municipal Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaysouthafrica.org.za/test.php?link=12&sub=2 |title=Lesbian History |publisher=Gaysouthafrica.org.za |accessdate=2014-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321024539/http://www.gaysouthafrica.org.za/test.php?link=12&sub=2 |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Randy Shilts]] was hired as a national [[correspondent]] by the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', becoming \"the first openly gay reporter with a gay 'beat' in the American mainstream press.\"<ref name=\"QUEER\">[http://www.queertheory.com/histories/s/shilts_randy.htm Randy Shilts at Queer Theory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006162424/http://www.queertheory.com/histories/s/shilts_randy.htm |date=6 October 2012 }} Retrieved on 2007-01-03</ref> A Sergeant of the [[New York City Police Department]] ([[Charles H. Cochrane|Charles H. Cochrane Jr.]]) came out as gay during a city council hearing. This made him the first New York City Police Department member to publicly announce his homosexuality.<ref name=Qundlen>Anna Qundlen, [https://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/05/nyregion/about-new-york-a-tough-month-in-the-new-life-of-a-policeman.html \"A Tough Month in the New Life of a Policeman\"], ''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1981.</ref>  \n* '''1982'''&nbsp;\u2013 Laguna Beach, CA elects the first openly gay mayor in United States history; France equalizes the age of consent; The first [[Gay Games]] is held in San Francisco, attracting 1,600 participants; [[Northern Ireland]] decriminalizes homosexuality; [[Wisconsin]] becomes the first US state to ban discrimination against homosexuals; [[New South Wales]] becomes the first Australian state to outlaw discrimination on the basis of actual or perceived homosexuality. The condition to be known as [[AIDS]] had acquired a number of names&nbsp;\u2013 GRID5 (gay-related immune deficiency), \u2018gay cancer\u2019, \u2018community-acquired immune dysfunction\u2019 and \u2018gay compromise syndrome\u2019<ref>Oswald, G.A, et al. (1982) \u2018Attempted immune stimulation in the \"gay compromise syndrome\"\u2019. BMJ, 1982 October 16; 285(6348): 1082.</ref> The CDC used the term AIDS for the first time in September 1982, when it reported that an average of one to two cases of AIDS were being diagnosed in America every day.<ref>MMWR Weekly (1982) \u2018Current trends update on Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS)&nbsp;\u2013 United States\u2019. 24 September, 31(37); 507\u2013508, 513\u2013514.</ref> [[:ja:\u6771\u90f7\u5065|Ken Togo]] founded the Deracine Party in Japan. New York City police sergeant [[Charles H. Cochrane|Charles H. Cochrane Jr.]] and former Fairview, [[New Jersey]] sergeant Sam Ciccone formed the first group targeted at the needs of gay members of law enforcement, the Gay Officers Action League (GOAL).<ref name=\"Ciccone\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/18/nyregion/sam-ciccone-a-champion-of-gay-police-officers-dies-at-71.html|title=Sam Ciccone, a Champion of Gay Police Officers, Dies at 71|newspaper=New York Times|last1=Weber|first1=Bruce|date=May 17, 2015|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> Portugal decriminalizes homosexuality for the second time in its history.\n* '''1983'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Massachusetts]] Representative [[Gerry Studds]] reveals he is gay on the floor of the House, becoming the first openly gay member of Congress; [[Guernsey]] (Including [[Alderney]], [[Herm]] and [[Sark]]) decriminalizes homosexuality; AIDS is described as a \"gay plague\" by Reverend [[Jerry Falwell]];  BiPOL, the first and oldest bisexual political organization, is founded in San Francisco by bisexual activists Autumn Courtney, [[Lani Ka'ahumanu]], Arlene Krantz, David Lourea, Bill Mack, [[Alan Rockway]], and Maggi Rubenstein; Governor [[Jerry Brown]] appoints [[Herb Donaldson (lawyer)|Herb Donaldson]] as the first openly gay male municipal court judge in the State of California;<ref name=\"cain\">{{cite journal|last=Cain|first=Patricia A.|title=Litigating for Lesbian and Gay Rights: A Legal History|journal=Virginia Law Review|date=Oct 1993|volume=79|issue=7 Symposium on Sexual Orientation and the Law|pages=1551\u20131641|doi=10.2307/1073382|jstor=1073382|url=https://digitalcommons.law.scu.edu/facpubs/277}}</ref><ref name=\"sfchronobit\">{{cite news\n | last = Taylor\n | first = Michael\n | title = Judge Herbert Donaldson dies: 'A born jurist'\n | newspaper = San Francisco Chronicle\n | date = 2008-12-10\n | url = http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Judge-Herbert-Donaldson-dies-A-born-jurist-3181205.php\n | accessdate = 2014-10-01}}</ref> [[David Scondras]] becomes the first openly gay official elected to the [[Boston City Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bostonspiritmagazine.com/2013/10/boston-mayors-race-then-and-now/ |title=Boston Mayor's Race: Then and Now |first=Mark |last=Krone |website=bostonspiritmagazine.com |date=October 10, 2013 |accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''1984'''&nbsp;\u2013 The lesbian and gay association \"Ten Percent Club\" is formed in Hong Kong; Massachusetts voters reelect representative [[Gerry Studds]], despite his revealing himself as homosexual the year before; New South Wales and the [[Northern Territory]] in Australia make homosexual acts legal; [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]], newly elected to the UK parliament declares: \"My name is Chris Smith. I'm the Labour MP for Islington South and Finsbury, and I'm gay\", making him the first openly out homosexual male politician in the UK parliament (Maureen Colquhoun being the first openly out homosexual politician in the UK in 1975). The Argentine Homosexual Community (Comunidad Homosexual Argentina, CHA) is formed uniting several different and preexisting groups. [[Berkeley, California]] becomes the first city in the U.S. to adopt a program of domestic partnership health benefits for city employees; West Hollywood, CA is founded and becomes the first known city to elect a city council where a majority of the members are openly gay or lesbian. [[Reconstructionist Judaism]] became the first Jewish denomination to allow openly gay and lesbian rabbis and cantors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Jewish_World_Today/Denominations/Reconstructionist.shtml |title=Reconstructionist Judaism Today |publisher=myjewishlearning.com |date=18 January 2002 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524122700/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Jewish_World_Today/Denominations/Reconstructionist.shtml |archivedate=24 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ILGA Japan is founded in Japan. ''[[On Our Backs]]'', the first women-run erotica magazine and the first magazine to feature [[lesbian]] [[erotica]] for a lesbian audience in the United States, was first published in 1984 by Debi Sundahl and Myrna Elana, with the contributions of [[Susie Bright]], Nan Kinney, Honey Lee Cottrell, Dawn Lewis, Happy Hyder, [[Tee Corinne]], [[Jewelle Gomez]], Judith Stein, [[Joan Nestle]], and [[Patrick Califia]].<ref>[[Patrick Califia]], \"Raising Cane\", ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'', August 1999, Vol. 8, No. 2, p.32</ref> In 1984, BiPOL sponsored the first bisexual rights rally, outside the [[Democratic National Convention]] in San Francisco. The rally featured nine speakers from civil rights groups allied with the bisexual movement.\n* '''1985'''&nbsp;\u2013 France prohibits discrimination based on lifestyle (moeurs) in employment and services; the first memorial to [[History of gay people in Nazi Germany and the Holocaust|gay Holocaust victims]] is dedicated; [[Belgium]] equalizes the age of consent; the [[Restoration Church of Jesus Christ]] (informally called the ''Gay Mormon Church'') is founded by [[Antonio A. Feliz]].<ref>[[Sunstone (magazine)|Sunstone]] March 1986 Interview with Antonio A. Feliz Pages 43\u201344</ref> Actor [[Rock Hudson]] dies of [[AIDS]]. He is the first major public figure known to have died from an AIDS-related illness.<ref>Berger, J (1985) \u2018Rock Hudson, screen idol, dies at 59\u2019. The New York Times, 3 October.</ref> [[Terry Sweeney]] becomes [[Saturday Night Live]]'s first [[coming out|openly]] [[gay]] male cast member; Sweeney was \"out\" prior to being hired as a cast member.<ref name=\"shales\">{{citation |title=Live from New York: An Uncensored History of Saturday Night Live |first=Tom |last=Shales |first2=James Andrew |last2=Miller |year=2002 |publisher=Back Bay |isbn=0-316-73565-5 |page=316}}</ref> The [[Bisexual Resource Center]] (BRC) in Massachusetts has served the bisexual community since 1985. [[LGBT culture in Liverpool|Liverpool]]-based soap opera, ''[[Brookside]]'' featured the first openly gay character on a British TV series this year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/seventy-five-years-of-british-television-89276 |title=Seventy five years of British television: The Mirror looks back at the key moments |publisher=The Mirror |date=3 November 2011 |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>\n* '''1986'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Homosexual Law Reform Act]] passed in [[New Zealand]], legalizing sex between males over 16; [[Haiti]] decriminalizes homosexuality, June in ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]'' case, U.S. Supreme Court upholds Georgia law forbidding oral or anal sex, ruling that the constitutional right to privacy does not extend to homosexual relations, but it does not state whether the law can be enforced against heterosexuals. Becky Smith and Annie Afleck became the first openly lesbian couple in America granted legal, joint adoption of a child.<ref>Christopher L. Walton. [http://www.uuworld.org/ideas/articles/2026.shtml Gay rights timeline: Major social, political, and religious milestones on the road to equality.]. uuworld.org. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> From 1 till 3 May, the 1986, [[ILGA]] Asia Conference took place in [[Japan]]'s capital [[Tokyo]].<ref>\u300c\u30aa\u30c8\u30b3\u30ce\u30b3\u30ce\u305f\u3081\u306e\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30d5\u30ec\u30f3\u30c9\u300d\uff081986\u5e74\u767a\u884c\u5c11\u5e74\u793e\u30fb\u767a\u58f2\u96ea\u6deb\u793e\uff09P200</ref> The Dutch [[Remonstrants]] are the world's first [[Christian denomination]] to perform same-sex unions and marriages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1086030/2010/01/25/Remonstranten-en-Boomsma-krijgen-homo-emancipatieprijs.dhtml|title=Remonstrants and Boomsma receive homo emancipation prize|work=[[Trouw]]|language=nl|date=25 January 2010|accessdate=4 April 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105104850/http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1086030/2010/01/25/Remonstranten-en-Boomsma-krijgen-homo-emancipatieprijs.dhtml|archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref> Canadian province [[Ontario]] passes anti-discrimination legislation. ''[[Hill Street Blues]]'' featured the first lesbian recurring character on a major network; the character was a police officer called Kate McBride, played by [[Lindsay Crouse]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Maya Salam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/arts/television/lesbian-tv-shows.html |title=The Very (Very) Slow Rise of Lesbianism on TV - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n* '''1987'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power]](ACT-UP) founded in the US in response to the US government's slow response in dealing with the AIDS crisis.<ref>ACT UP. Flyer of the demonstration on 24 March 1987.</ref> [[AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power|ACT UP]] stages its first major demonstration, seventeen protesters are arrested; U.S. Congressman [[Barney Frank]] comes out. [[Boulder, Colorado]] citizens pass the first referendum to ban discrimination based on sexual orientation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/editorials/ci_22012676/civil-rights-marching-forward | title=Civil rights, marching forward | work=Boulder Daily Camera | date=18 November 2012 | accessdate=18 November 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news   | last = Phelps  | first = Timothy  | title = Gay issues split Colorado cities  | work = Eugene Register-Guard  | page = 8A  | publisher = Newsday  | date = 8 October 1995  | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wUlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G-sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6547,1764809  | accessdate = 14 January 2012}}</ref>  In New York City a group of Bisexual [[List of LGBT rights activists|LGBT rights activist]] including [[Brenda Howard]] found the [[New York Area Bisexual Network|New York Area Bisexual Network (NYABN)]]; [[Homomonument]], a memorial to persecuted homosexuals, opens in [[Amsterdam]]. [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] is the first openly gay person to be elected to public office in the [[Republic of Ireland]]. A group of 75 bisexuals marched in the 1987 March On Washington For Gay and Lesbian Rights, which was the first nationwide bisexual gathering. The article \"[http://www.lanikaahumanu.com/OUT%20OUTRAGED.pdf The Bisexual Movement: Are We Visible Yet?]\", by [[Lani Ka'ahumanu]], appeared in the official Civil Disobedience Handbook for the March. It was the first article about bisexuals and the emerging bisexual movement to be published in a national lesbian or gay publication.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.lanikaahumanu.com/OUT%20OUTRAGED.pdf |title=OUT & OUTRAGED Non-Violent Civil Disobedience at the U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref> Canadian province of [[Manitoba]] and territory [[Yukon]] ban sexual orientation discrimination.\n* '''1988'''&nbsp;\u2013 Sweden is the first country to pass laws protecting homosexual regarding social services, taxes, and inheritances. The anti-gay [[Section 28]] passes in England and Wales; Scotland enacts almost identical legislation; [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Canadian MP]] [[Svend Robinson]] comes out; Canada lowers the age of consent for sodomy to 18; [[Belize]] and Israel decriminalize ([[de jure]]) sodomy and sexual acts between men (the relevant section in the old British-mandate law from 1936 was never enforced in Israel). After losing an [[High Court (Ireland)|Irish High Court]] case (1980) and an [[Supreme Court of Ireland|Irish Supreme Court]] case (1983), [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] takes his case (''[[Norris v. Ireland]]'') to the European Court of Human Rights. The European Court strikes down the Irish law criminalising male-to-male sex on the grounds of privacy. [[Stacy Offner]] became the first openly lesbian rabbi hired by a mainstream Jewish congregation, Shir Tikvah Congregation of Minneapolis (a Reform Jewish congregation).<ref>Dana Evan Kaplan [https://books.google.com/books?id=qQoaBa7D-9oC&pg=PA255 Contemporary American Judaism: transformation and renewal] Columbia University Press, 2009 {{ISBN|0231137281}}, p. 255</ref><ref>[http://www.shirtikvah.net/Default.aspx?pageId=675181 Our Roots]. Shir Tikvah. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> [[Robert Dover (equestrian)|Robert Dover]] became the first openly gay Olympic athlete when he came out in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outsports.com/platform/amp/2020/2/19/21138643/gay-olympic-robert-dover-equestrian-horse-riding-five-rings-athlete |title=Robert Dover, the first out gay Olympic athlete |publisher=Outsports |date= |accessdate=2020-03-11}}</ref> \n* '''1989'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Western Australia]] decriminalizes male homosexuality (but the age of consent is set at 21); [[Liechtenstein]] legalizes homosexuality; Denmark is the first country in the world to enact [[registered partnership]] laws (like a [[civil union]]) for same-sex couples, with most of the same rights as marriage (excluding the right to adoption (until June 2010) and the right to marriage in a church).\n\n==1990s==\n\n* '''1990'''\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': Czechoslovakia (see [[LGBT rights in the Czech Republic|Czech Republic]], [[LGBT rights in Slovakia|Slovakia]])\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': UK Crown Dependency of [[Jersey]] and the Australian state of [[LGBT rights in Queensland|Queensland]]\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': [[BiNet USA]] (USA), [[OutRage!]] (UK),  [[Queer Nation]] (USA), [[Humsafar Trust|The Humsafar Trust]] (India)\n** '''Homosexuality no longer an illness''': The [[World Health Organization]]\n** '''Other''': [[Justin Fashanu]] is the first professional footballer to come out in the press.\n** [[Reform Judaism]] decided to allow openly lesbian and gay rabbis and cantors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/practices/Ritual/Prayer/Synagogue_and_Religious_Leaders/What_is_a_Rabbi/Demographic_Changes.shtml |title=The Changing Face of the Rabbinate |publisher=myjewishlearning.com |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302214918/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/practices/Ritual/Prayer/Synagogue_and_Religious_Leaders/What_is_a_Rabbi/Demographic_Changes.shtml |archivedate=2 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n** [[Dale McCormick]] became the first open lesbian elected to a state Senate (she was elected to the Maine Senate).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qrd.org/QRD/www/usa/maine/bdn-1.20.98.html |title=Dale McCormick finds job as Treasurer challenging, rewarding |publisher=qrd.org |date=20 January 1998 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** In 1990, the [[Union for Reform Judaism]] announced a national policy declaring lesbian and gay Jews to be full and equal members of the religious community. Its principal body, the [[Central Conference of American Rabbis]] (CCAR), officially endorsed a report of their committee on homosexuality and rabbis. They concluded that \"all rabbis, regardless of sexual orientation, be accorded the opportunity to fulfill the sacred vocation that they have chosen\" and that \"all Jews are religiously equal regardless of their sexual orientation.\"\n** The oldest national bisexuality organization in the United States, [[BiNet USA]], was founded in 1990. It was originally called the North American Multicultural Bisexual Network (NAMBN), and had its first meeting at the first National Bisexual Conference in America.<ref name=\"binetusa_a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.binetusa.org/Pages/aboutus.html |title=All About BiNet USA including the Fine Print |publisher=BiNet USA |date= |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref><ref name=\"binetusa_a\" /><ref name=\"glbtq\">{{cite web|last=Summers |first=Claude J. |title=BiNet USA |encyclopedia=glbtq: An Encyclopedia of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Culture |publisher=glbtq, Inc. |date=2009-10-20 |url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/binet_usa.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220100127/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/binet_usa.html |archivedate=2014-02-20 }}</ref> This first conference was held in San Francisco in 1990, and sponsored by BiPOL. Over 450 people attended from 20 states and 5 countries, and the mayor of San Francisco sent a proclamation \"commending the bisexual rights community for its leadership in the cause of social justice,\" and declaring June 23, 1990 [[Celebrate Bisexuality Day|Bisexual Pride Day]].\n** The first Eagle Creek Saloon, that opened on the 1800 block of Market Street in San Francisco in 1990 and closed in 1993, was the first black-owned gay bar in the city.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whiting |first=Sam |url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/art-exhibits/art-piece-remembers-dream-of-sfs-first-black-owned-gay-bar |title=Art piece remembers dream of SF's first black-owned gay bar &#124; Datebook |publisher=Datebook.sfchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n* '''1991'''\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in the Bahamas|Bahamas]], [[LGBT rights in Hong Kong|Hong Kong]]  and [[LGBT rights in Ukraine|Ukraine]]\n** '''AIDS Related''': The [[red ribbon]] is first used as a symbol of the campaign against [[HIV/AIDS]].\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation:''' Canadian province [[Nova Scotia]] (sexual orientation)\n** Sherry Harris was elected to the City Council in Seattle, Washington, making her the first openly lesbian African-American elected official.<ref>Bonnie Zimmerman. [https://books.google.com/books?id=0EUoCrFolGcC&pg=PA258&lpg=PA258&dq=%22sherry++harris%22+%22first+african-+american+lesbian%22&source=bl&ots=NEIskdTf_5&sig=jsrQizMWcCxr7yUZNmY9JdWPYxo&hl=en&ei=cSd1TYnHDIT58Ab6m9jEDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22sherry%20%20harris%22%20%22first%20african-%20american%20lesbian%22&f=false Lesbian Histories and Cultures: An Encyclopedia, Volume 1.]</ref>\n** The first lesbian kiss on television occurred; it was on ''L.A. Law'' between the fictional characters of C.J. Lamb (played by Amanda Donohoe) and Abby (Michele Greene).<ref>[http://www.observer.com/1999/fox-plans-sapphic-smooch-party-five-steve-odonnell-lateline-lets-it-all-out Fox Plans Sapphic Smooch for Party of Five ... Steve O'Donnell of Lateline Lets It All Out | The New York Observer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616082925/http://www.observer.com/1999/fox-plans-sapphic-smooch-party-five-steve-odonnell-lateline-lets-it-all-out |date=16 June 2011 }}. Observer.com (31 January 1999). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref>\n** The [[Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame]] was created in June 1991.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rJEU4xYiWEEC&lpg=PA200&dq=%22chicago%20gay%20and%20lesbian%20hall%20of%20fame%22&pg=PA200#v=onepage&q=%22chicago%20gay%20and%20lesbian%20hall%20of%20fame%22&f=false|title=Out and Proud in Chicago: An Overview of the City's Gay Community|last=Harper|first=Jorjet|publisher=Agate Publishing|year=2009|isbn=9781572846432|editor-last=Baim|editor-first=Tracy|location=|pages=200|language=en}}</ref> The hall of fame is the first \"municipal institution of its kind in the United States, and possibly in the world.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n* '''1992'''\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Iceland|Iceland]], [[LGBT rights in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]] and [[LGBT rights in Switzerland|Switzerland]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Estonia|Estonia]] and [[LGBT rights in Latvia|Latvia]]\n** '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': UK Crown Dependency of [[LGBT rights in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] (homosexuality still illegal until 1994)\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Australia|Australia]], [[LGBT rights in Canada|Canada]]\n** '''Recriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Nicaragua|Nicaragua]] (until Mar 2008)\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation:''' Canadian provinces [[New Brunswick]] and [[British Columbia]] (sexual orientation)\n** '''[[Althea Garrison]]''' was elected as the first transgender state legislator in America, and served one term in the Massachusetts House of Representatives; however, it was not publicly known she was transgender when she was elected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials,2.html |title=Social sciences - Elected Officials |publisher=glbtq |date=13 November 2006 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714173926/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/elected_officials%2C2.html |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n** The [[Lesbian Avengers]] was founded in [[New York City]] by [[Ana Mar\u00eda Simo]], [[Sarah Schulman]], Maxine Wolfe, [[Anne-Christine d'Adesky]], Marie Honan, and [[Anne Maguire]]\n** [[Tokyo International Lesbian & Gay Film Festival]] was held in Japan.\n* '''1993'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Norway|Norway]] (without adoption until 2009, replaced with same-sex marriage in 2008/09)\n** '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': Australian Territory of [[Norfolk Island]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Belarus|Belarus]], UK Crown Dependency of [[LGBT rights in Gibraltar|Gibraltar]], [[LGBT rights in the Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], [[LGBT rights in Lithuania|Lithuania]], [[LGBT rights in Russia|Russia]] (with the exception of the [[Chechen Republic]]);\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': \n*** US state of [[Minnesota]] (gender identity) \n*** New Zealand parliament passes the Human Rights Amendment Act which outlaws discrimination on the grounds of sexual orientation or HIV\n*** Canadian province [[Saskatchewan]] (sexual orientation)\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in New Zealand|New Zealand]]\n** '''Significant LGBT Murders''': [[Brandon Teena]]\n** [[Melissa Etheridge]] came out as a lesbian.\n** The Triangle Ball was held; it was the first inaugural ball in America to ever be held in honor of gays and lesbians.\n** The first [[Dyke March]] (a march for lesbians and their straight female allies, planned by the [[Lesbian Avengers]]) was held, with 20,000 women marching.<ref>[http://www.thegully.com/essays/gaymundo/020719_lesbian_future.html Dyke March: The Next Wave]. The Gully. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baywindows.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=glbt&sc2=news&sc3=&id=61643 |title=Boisterous women chant, laugh and clap their way through Dyke March 2000 (Bay Windows) |accessdate=2012-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110612131852/http://www.baywindows.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=glbt&sc2=news&sc3=&id=61643 |archivedate=12 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n** [[Roberta Achtenberg]] became the first openly gay or lesbian person to be nominated by the president and confirmed by the U.S. Senate when she was appointed to the position of Assistant Secretary for Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity by President Bill Clinton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.browsebiography.com/bio-roberta_achtenberg.html |title=Roberta Achtenberg biography |publisher=browsebiography.com |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** [[Lea DeLaria]] was \"the first [[closeted|openly]] gay comic to break the late-night talk-show barrier\" with her 1993 appearance on ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]''.<ref name=\"EW 1993-12-10\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,308870,00.html\n|title = Trend: Gay stand-up comedians\n|last = Cagle\n|first = Jess\n|work = [[Entertainment Weekly]]\n|publisher = [[Time Warner]]\n|date = 10 December 1993\n|accessdate = 2011-06-28}}</ref>\n** In December 1993 [[Lea DeLaria]] hosted [[Comedy Central]]'s ''Out There'', the first all-gay stand-up comedy special.<ref name=\"EW 1993-12-10\" />\n** Before the \"[[Don't Ask Don't Tell]]\" policy was enacted in 1993, lesbians and bisexual women and gay men and bisexual men were banned from serving in the military.<ref name=\"prezi2003\">{{cite web|url=https://prezi.com/ytivn4zvwnrv/military-service-should-be-based-on-conduct-not-sexual-orie/|title=Military Service Should Be Based On Conduct, Not Sexual Orientation|publisher=prezi.com |author=Elizabeth Hoffman|date=2003-03-28 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> In 1993 the \"Don't Ask Don't Tell\" policy was enacted, which mandated that the military could not ask servicemembers about their sexual orientation.<ref name=\"Craig A. Rimmerman p. 249\">Craig A. Rimmerman [https://books.google.com/books?id=Go9XsJ47GswC&pg=PA249 Gay rights, military wrongs: political perspectives on lesbians and gays in the military], Garland Pub., 1996 {{ISBN|0815325800}} p. 249</ref><ref name=\"'Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Turns 15\">Thompson, Mark. (2008-01-28) [http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1707545,00.html 'Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Turns 15]. TIME. Retrieved on 2010-11-30.</ref> However, until the policy was ended in 2011 service members were still expelled from the military if they engaged in sexual conduct with a member of the same sex, stated that they were lesbian, gay, or bisexual, and/or married or attempted to marry someone of the same sex.<ref name=\"The Military Commander & the Law\">Richard A. Gittins [https://books.google.com/books?id=ENpnS9KApu8C&pg=PA215 The Military Commander & the Law], DIANE Publishing, 1996 {{ISBN|0788172603}} p. 215</ref>\n* '''1994'''\n** '''Unregistered Cohabitation recognition''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|Israel]] (without adoption, without step-adoption until 2005)\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (sexual orientation, interim constitution)\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Bermuda|Bermuda]], UK Crown Dependency of [[LGBT rights in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] and [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbia]], Commonwealth of Australia\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''':\n*** '''Partial''': [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|UK]] reduces the age of consent for homosexual men to 18;\n** '''Homosexuality no longer an illness''': [[American Medical Association]]\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': [[National Coalition for Gay and Lesbian Equality]] (South Africa)\n** '''Other''' : [[LGBT rights in Canada|Canada]] grants refugee status to homosexuals fearing for their well-being in their native country; ''[[Toonen v. Australia]]'' decided by UN Human Rights Committee; fear of persecution due to sexual orientation becomes grounds for asylum in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gesaman |first=Krista |url=http://www.newsweek.com/2009/11/29/desperately-seeking-freedom.html |title=Are More Gays, Lesbians Seeking Asylum in U.S.? |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=29 November 2009 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** [[Deborah Batts]] became the first openly gay or lesbian federal judge; she was appointed to the U.S. District Court in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/batts_da.html |title=Batts, Deborah A |publisher=glbtq.com |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002143835/http://www.glbtq.com/social-sciences/batts_da.html |archivedate=2 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>[http://www.queertheory.com/histories/b/batts_deborah.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011003321/http://www.queertheory.com/histories/b/batts_deborah.htm|date=11 October 2011}}</ref>\n** The Gay Asian Pacific Alliance and Asian Pacific Sister joined the Chinese New Year Parade in San Francisco, which was the first time that queer Asian American communities had attended in a publicly ethnic activity.<ref>Lavilla, S. (1998, Jul 09). A growing show of pride: Record Asian american presence at parade reflects a growing acceptance. ''Asianweek'' Retrieved from http://search.proquest.com/docview/367563813</ref>\n** Gay Parade was held in Japan. (8.1994)\n** '''[[Wilson Cruz]]''' became the first gay actor to play an openly gay character in a leading role in a television series (''[[My So-Called Life]]'').\n** '''[[Steve Gunderson]]''' was outed as gay on the House floor by representative [[Bob Dornan]] (R-[[California|CA]]) during a debate over federal funding for gay-friendly curricula,<ref>Chris Bull (May 3, 1994), [https://books.google.com/books?id=9GMEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA29&dq=Steve%20Gunderson%20Dornan&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false The Out House: Congressional Debate over an Education Bill Gets Personal and Nasty], ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', p. 29.</ref> making him one of the first openly gay members of the U.S. Congress and the first openly gay U.S. Republican representative.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Closeted+in+the+capital%3a+they%27re+powerful%2c+Republican%2c+and+gay.+Will...-a0116288151 |title=Closeted in the capital: they're powerful, Republican, and gay. Will the marriage battle finally get them to come out to their bosses? |publisher=The Advocate |author=Bergling, Tim |date=May 11, 2004 |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> \n** [[LGBT culture in Liverpool|Liverpool]]-based soap opera, '''''[[Brookside]]''''', broadcast the UK's first pre-watershed lesbian kiss.<ref>{{cite news|author=Monique Roffey |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/when-anna-and-beth-kissed-margaret-anna-friel-plays-brooksides-lesbian-pinup-monique-roffey-met-her-1440368.html |title=When Anna and Beth kissed Margaret: Anna Friel plays Brookside's lesbian pin-up. Monique Roffey met her |newspaper=The Independent |date=2 November 1994 |accessdate=2012-06-07 |location=London}}</ref>\n** The broadcast of '''[[Pedro Zamora]] and [[Sean Sasser]]'s [[commitment ceremony]]''' in 1994, in which they exchanged vows, was the first such same-sex ceremony in television history, and is considered a landmark in the history of the medium.<ref name=CNN>Duke, Alan; Carter, Chelsea, J. (August 8, 2013). [http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/08/showbiz/sean-sasser-death/index.html \"Sean Sasser, whose ceremony with partner on 'Real World' was TV first, dies\"]. [[CNN]].</ref><ref name=USAToday>Oldenburg, Ann (August 8, 2013). [https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2013/08/08/real-world-star-sean-sasser-dies-at-44/2632631/ \"'Real World' star Sean Sasser dies at 44\"]. ''[[USA Today]]''.</ref>\n* '''1995'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Sweden|Sweden]] (with adoption, replaced with same-sex marriage in April 2009)\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': Canadian province [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] (sexual orientation)\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Albania|Albania]] and [[LGBT rights in Moldova|Moldova]]\n** '''AIDS Related''': Triple combination therapy of drugs such as [[Lamivudine|3TC]], [[Zidovudine|AZT]] and [[Zalcitabine|ddC]] shown to be effective in treating [[HIV]], the virus responsible for [[AIDS]]<ref>The New York Times (21 November 1995) \u2018New drug to fight AIDS is approved by FDA\u2019.</ref>\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': Gay Advice Darlington/Durham was founded by local gay and bisexual men, and has developed into a Charity that works with and for the Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender (LGBT) Community of County Durham and Darlington.\n** '''Other''' : The [[Human Rights Campaign]] drops the word \"Fund\" from their title and broadens their mission to promote \"an America where gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender people are ensured equality and embraced as full members of the American family at home, at work and in every community;\"\n** [[Rachel Maddow]] became the first openly gay or lesbian American to win an international [[Rhodes Scholarship]].\n** Kings Cross Steelers, the world's first gay rugby club, was founded.<ref>{{cite news|last=McKenzie |first=Sheena |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/23/sport/world-first-gay-rugby-club-team-london/index.html?eref=rss_latest |title=World's first gay rugby club 20 years on |publisher=CNN.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref>\n** Rabbi [[Margaret Wenig]]'s essay \"Truly Welcoming Lesbian and Gay Jews\" was published in ''The Jewish Condition: Essays on Contemporary Judaism Honoring Rabbi [[Alexander M. Schindler]]''; it was the first published argument to the Jewish community on behalf of civil marriage for gay couples.<ref name=\"wenig\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:fFLO9cY0WUUJ:huc.edu/news/docs/prlinks3/Wenig%2520PR.pdf+%22miriam+frank%22+%22margaret+wenig%22+%22mentally+ill%22+first&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESi23nbt0sf9HxA42m72kp-VshCZh5JKMb3Hij-nLKXhlNPM6VasnnCORZOT3VL0e3mlKGD8ZONJvC6gk8GgLZy_ZEsA74UoazDW6WKzPULQp5hJfW7Bea6V6AqAubipRho2owD1&sig=AHIEtbR6VRH-CJYWipd-wwBi6ItCM-6UmA |title=Powered by Google Docs |date= |accessdate=2012-04-12}}</ref>\n** [[Ed Flanagan (politician)|Ed Flanagan]] served as Vermont's [[Vermont Auditor of Accounts|State Auditor]] from 1993 through 2001, becoming the first openly gay, statewide-elected official in the United States when he came out in 1995, before his 1996 reelection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outhistory.org/exhibits/show/out-and-elected/1992/edward-flanagan|title=Edward Flanagan, Vermont, 1992 \u00b7 Out and Elected in the USA: 1974-2004 \u00b7 outhistory.org|website=outhistory.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref> \n* '''1996'''\n**'''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Iceland|Iceland]] (with step-adoption, without joint adoption until 2006, replaced with same-sex marriage in 2010)\n** '''Unregistered Cohabitation recognition''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Hungary]] (replaced with registered partnerships in 2009)\n** '''Restriction of LGBT partnership rights''': [[LGBT rights in the United States|USA]], (federal, see [[DOMA]])\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Burkina Faso|Burkina Faso]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Romania|Romania]],  [[LGBT rights in North Macedonia|North Macedonia]], [[LGBT rights in Macau|Macau]]\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation:''' [[Lgbt rights in Canada|Canada]] (federal, sexual orientation)\n** The first lesbian wedding on television occurred, held for fictional characters Carol (played by Jane Sibbett) and Susan (played by Jessica Hecht) on the TV show \"Friends\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2008/8/lesbianweddings |title=Getting Hitched: Lesbian Weddings in Film and TV |publisher=AfterEllen.com |date=18 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716134253/http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2008/8/lesbianweddings |archivedate=16 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n** The first openly gay speaker at a [[Republican National Convention]] was [[Log Cabin Republicans]] member Steve Fong of California in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last=Keen |first=Lisa |url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=71747 |title=The Bay Area Reporter Online &#124; Tension between gays and GOP shrouds convention |publisher=Ebar.com |date=2016-07-21 |accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref>\n** [[Muffin Spencer-Devlin]] became the first [[LPGA]] player to come out as gay.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garrity |first1=John |last2=Nutt |first2=Amy |title=No More Disguises - Muffin Spencer-Devlin stands tall in her chosen role: the first LPGA player to declare she's gay |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1996/03/18/211002/no-more-disguises-muffin-spencer-devlin-stands-tall-in-her-chosen-role-the-first-lpga-player-to-declare-shes-gay |accessdate=February 11, 2015 |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=March 18, 1996}}</ref>\n* '''1997'''\n**'''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Fiji|Fiji]] (sexual orientation, constitution) and [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (sexual orientation, constitution)\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Russia|Russia]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Ecuador|Ecuador]], [[LGBT rights in Venezuela|Venezuela]] and the Australian state of [[LGBT rights in Tasmania|Tasmania]]\n** '''Other''' : Israeli President Ezer Weizman compares homosexuality to alcoholism in front of high school students.<ref>[[Ezer Weizman]]</ref> The UK extends immigration rights to same-sex couples akin to marriage; [[Ellen DeGeneres]] came out as a lesbian, one of the first celebrities to do so.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/9704/06/ellen/|work=CNN|title=Ellen DeGeneres tells Time she's a lesbian}}</ref> Furthermore, later that year her character Ellen Morgan came out as a lesbian on the TV show ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'', making Ellen DeGeneres the first openly lesbian actress to play an openly lesbian character on television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/People/ellen.html |title=Ellen DeGeneres: Reluctant Lesbian Icon |publisher=AfterEllen.com |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120720113652/http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/People/ellen.html |archivedate=20 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> '''[[Patria Jim\u00e9nez]]''' became the first openly gay person to win a position in the Mexican Congress, doing so for the [[Party of the Democratic Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= Mexican gays poised to make demands for change |date= 27 July 1997 |publisher= CNN interactive |url= http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9707/27/mexico.gays/ |accessdate= 17 December 2007}}</ref> The [[Gay and Lesbian Medical Association]] launched the ''Journal of the Gay and Lesbian Medical Association'', the world's first peer-reviewed, multi-disciplinary journal dedicated to LGBT health. The first open-mouth kiss between two women on prime time television occurred, on ABC's ''[[Relativity (TV series)|Relativity]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frost |first=Karen |url=https://www.afterellen.com/tv/474467-long-road-lesbian-sex-sensuality-network-tv#UjXTCyxhuYzGUkMG.99 |title=The Long Road to Lesbian Sex & Sensuality on Network TV |publisher=AfterEllen |date=2017-08-19 |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n* '''1998'''\n**'''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Ecuador|Ecuador]] (sexual orientation, constitution), [[LGBT rights in the Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] (sexual orientation) and the Canadian provinces of [[Prince Edward Island]] (sexual orientation) and [[LGBT rights in Alberta|Alberta]] ([[Vriend v Alberta|court ruling only]]; legislation amended in 2009)\n** '''Significant LGBT Murders''': [[Rita Hester]], [[Matthew Shepard]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[LGBT rights in Kazakhstan|Kazakhstan]], [[LGBT rights in Kyrgyzstan|Kyrgyzstan]], [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (retroactive to 1994), [[LGBT rights in Cyprus|Republic of Cyprus]] and [[LGBT rights in Tajikistan|Tajikistan]]\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Croatia|Croatia]] and [[LGBT rights in Latvia|Latvia]]\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Romania|Romania]], [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]]\n** [[Gender identity]] was added to the mission of '''[[Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays]]''' after a vote at their annual meeting in San Francisco.<ref name=\"bare_url_a\">{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=Community.pflag.org |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620050818/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |archivedate=20 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays]] is the first national LGBT organization to officially adopt a transgender-inclusion policy for its work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/page.aspx?pid=380 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=Community.pflag.org |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514141130/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=380 |archivedate=14 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n** [[Tammy Baldwin]] became the first openly gay or lesbian non-incumbent ever elected to Congress, and the first open lesbian ever elected to Congress, winning Wisconsin's 2nd congressional district seat over Josephine Musser.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/11/03/election/house/wisconsin.cd2/|work=CNN|title=Baldwin breaks barrier, becomes first openly lesbian House member}}</ref><ref>[http://www.now.org/nnt/winter-99/lesactn.html NOW Calls Lesbian Rights Supporters to Unite in Strategy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215112429/http://www.now.org/nnt/winter-99/lesactn.html |date=15 February 2010 }}. Now.org (4 February 1999). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref>\n** [[Dana International]] became the first transsexual to win the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], representing [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest|Israel]] with the song \"[[Diva (Dana International song)|Diva]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1998 {{!}} Year page {{!}} Eurovision Song Contest - Copenhagen 2014|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=313#Participants|publisher=Eurovision.tv|accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref> \n** [[Robert Halford]] comes out as being the first openly gay heavy metal musician.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429870/19980205/halford_rob.jhtml | date=5 February 1998 | title=Rob Halford Discusses Sexuality Publicly For The First Time | publisher=[[MTV News]] | accessdate=24 May 2010 }}</ref>\n** The first [[bisexual pride flag]] was unveiled on 5 December 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wright.edu/counseling/SafezoneSymbols.html |title=Counseling and Wellness Services - Safezone Symbols |publisher=Wright.edu |date=1998-12-05 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n** Julie Hesmondhalgh first began to play Hayley Anne Patterson, British TV's first transgender character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/01/21/coronation-street-says-goodbye-to-its-first-transgender-character/|title=Coronation Street says goodbye to its first transgender character|work=PinkNews|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** [[BiNet USA]] hosted the '''First National Institute on Bisexuality and HIV/AIDS.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.binetusa.org/binethistory.html |title=BiNet USA |publisher=BiNet USA |date= |accessdate=2015-10-30}}</ref>\n* '''1999'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US State of [[Domestic partnership in California|California]] (without adoption, without step adoption until 2001, same-sex marriage in June 2008-November 2008)\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Pacte civil de solidarit\u00e9|France]]\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Chile|Chile]]\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Finland|Finland]] (without adoption)\n** '''LGBT Organizations founded''': \"[[Queer Youth Alliance]]\" (UK)\n** '''Other''': [[LGBT rights in Israel|Israel]]'s supreme court recognizes a lesbian partner as another legal mother of her partner's biological son; [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] grants spousal immigration benefits to same-sex partners.\n**  '''[[Steven Greenberg (rabbi)|Steven Greenberg]]''' publicly came out as gay in an article in the [[Israel]]i newspaper ''[[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]]''. As he has a [[semichah|rabbinic ordination]] from the [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] rabbinical seminary of Yeshiva University ([[RIETS]]), he is generally described as the first [[openly gay]] Orthodox Jewish rabbi.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/11/national/11bishop.html?scp=4&sq=Rabbi%20Steven%20Greenberg&st=cse| title=Bishop Says Conflict on Gays Distracts From Vital Issues| work=[[The New York Times]] | date=11 September 2004| accessdate=18 November 2011 | author=Goodstein, Laurie}}<br />{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,1425657,00.html | title=Judaism and the gay dilemma | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=26 February 2005 | accessdate=16 November 2011 | author=Rocker, Simon | location=London}}\n{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/07/an-interview-with-rabbi-s_n_638679.html| title= An Interview With Rabbi Steven Greenberg: Orthodox And Gay | work=[[Huffington Post]]| date=7 July 2010| accessdate=16 November 2011 | author=Neroulias, Nicole}}<br />{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/07/an-interview-with-rabbi-s_n_638679.html\n| title= Gay And Orthodox, According To Jon Marans | work=[[The Jewish Week]]| date=19 July 2011 | accessdate=16 November 2011 | author=Merwin, Ted}}</ref> However, some Orthodox Jews, including many rabbis, dispute his being an Orthodox rabbi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algemeiner.com/2011/12/05/100-orthodox-rabbis-issue-same-sex-marriage-declaration/ |title=100 Orthodox Rabbis Issue Same Sex Marriage Declaration |publisher=algemeiner.com |date=5 December 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n** The '''[[Transgender Day of Remembrance]]''' was founded in 1999 by [[Gwendolyn Ann Smith]], a [[trans woman]] who is a graphic designer, columnist, and activist,<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=G. |title=Biography |url=http://www.gwensmith.com/background/biography.html |publisher=Gwensmith.com |accessdate=2013-11-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424004720/http://www.gwensmith.com/background/biography.html |archivedate=24 April 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> to memorialize the murder of [[Rita Hester]] in [[Allston, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Ethan|title=Remembering Rita Hester|url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=entertainment&sc=music&sc2=features&sc3&id=83392|newspaper=EDGE Boston|date=2008-11-15}}</ref> Since its inception, TDoR has been held annually on 20 November,<ref>{{cite web|title=Transgender Day of Remembrance|url=http://www.hrc.org/campaigns/transgender-day-remembrance|publisher=Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=2013-11-20}}</ref> and it has slowly evolved from the [[World Wide Web|web]]-based project started by Smith into an international day of action. \n** In 1999, the first '''[[Celebrate Bisexuality Day]]''' was organized by Michael Page, [[Gigi Raven Wilbur]], and [[Wendy Curry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.binetusa.org/bihistory2.html |title=BiNet USA |publisher=BiNet USA |date=1990-06-23 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n\n* <!--2000 is the last year of the 20th century-->'''2000'''\n** '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n*** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US State of [[Same-sex marriage in Vermont|Vermont]]\n** '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]] (discrimination, hate speech, harassment; see [[Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discrimination Act, 2000|PEPUDA]])\n** '''Revoking of discrimination legislation''': UK subdivision of [[LGBT rights in Scotland|Scotland]] ([[Section 28]])\n** '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]]. See also: [[Sexual orientation and military service]] and [[Stonewall (UK)|Stonewall]]\n** '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Belarus|Belarus]], [[LGBT rights in Israel|Israel]] and [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] (passed eff. 2001)\n** '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Azerbaijan|Azerbaijan]] and [[LGBT rights in Georgia (country)|Georgia]]\n** '''Other''': In [[LGBT rights in Germany|Germany]] the [[Bundestag]] officially apologizes to gays and lesbians persecuted under the Nazi regime, and for \"harm done to homosexual citizens up to 1969\"; Israel recognizes same-sex relations for immigration purposes for a foreign partner of an Israeli resident.\n** The '''[[Transgender Pride flag]]''' was first shown, at a pride parade in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].\n** '''[[Hillary Clinton]]''' became the first First Lady to march in an [[LGBT pride parade]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Nate White |url=https://medium.com/@natewhite11/why-hillary-s-experience-argument-actually-does-check-out-64cc9a439442#.swdfuutqn |title=Why Hillary's experience argument actually does check out \u2014 Medium |publisher=Medium.com |accessdate=2016-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821202223/https://medium.com/%40natewhite11/why-hillary-s-experience-argument-actually-does-check-out-64cc9a439442#.swdfuutqn |archivedate=21 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history]]\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history, 19th century]]\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history, 21st century]]\n* [[List of years in LGBT rights]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{LGBT history}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline Of Lgbt History}}\n[[Category:LGBT timelines| ]]\n[[Category:20th century timelines]]\n", "name_user": "TirelessLogodaedalus", "label": "safe", "comment": "add link to Ariston Bathhouse raids page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_LGBT_history,_20th_century"}
{"title_page": "Waarder", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Waarder\n| settlement_type         = Village\n| other_name              = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name             = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = nl\n| image_skyline           = Waarder Kerkelaantje.jpg\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = Waarder with the church and the medieval Kerkelaantje\n| image_flag              =\n| image_shield            =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = Map - NL - Municipality code 0595 (2009).svg\n| map_caption             =\n| image_map1              = Map NL - Reeuwijk - Waarder.png\n| map_caption1            = The village centre (dark green) and the statistical district (light green) of Waarder in the municipality of Reeuwijk.\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Netherlands -->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Netherlands\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Netherlands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of the Netherlands|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[South Holland]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of municipalities of the Netherlands|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Bodegraven-Reeuwijk]]\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| leader_party            =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|52|3|41|N|4|49|21|E|region:NL_type:city(1647)|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          =\n| established_title       =\n| established_date        =\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = 1647\n| population_as_of        = 2008\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in the Netherlands|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             =\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in the Netherlands|Dialing code]]\n| area_code               =\n| website                 =\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n'''Waarder''' is a village in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] province of [[South Holland]]. It is a part of the former municipality of [[Reeuwijk]], and lies about 5&nbsp;km southwest of [[Woerden]].\n\nIn 2001, the village of Waarder had 1143 inhabitants. The built-up area of the village was 0.18&nbsp;km\u00b2, and contained 416 residences.<ref name=\"CBS\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), [http://www.cbs.nl/nl-NL/menu/themas/milieu-natuur-ruimte/ruimte/publicaties/cartografie-geografie/geografische-data/2001-bevolkingskernen-in-nederland.htm ''Bevolkingskernen in Nederland 2001'']. (Statistics are for the continuous built-up area).</ref>\nThe statistical area \"Waarder\", which also can include the peripheral parts of the village, as well as the surrounding countryside, has a population of around 1250.<ref name=\"CBS2\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), [http://statline.cbs.nl/ ''Statline: Kerncijfers wijken en buurten 2003-2005'']. As of 1 January 2005.</ref>\n\nWaarder was a separate municipality until 1964, when it became part of [[Driebruggen]],<ref>Ad van der Meer and Onno Boonstra, \"Repertorium van Nederlandse gemeenten\", KNAW, 2006. [http://www.knaw.nl/cfdata/publicaties/detail.cfm?boeken__ordernr=20061061]</ref> which became part of [[Reeuwijk]] in 1989. Since 2011 it is part of the municipality of [[Bodegraven-Reeuwijk]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Kuyper|Waarder|zh}} Map of the former municipality in 1868.\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in South Holland]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities of South Holland]]\n\n\n{{SouthHolland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Waarder\n| settlement_type         = Village\n| other_name              = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name             = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = nl\n| image_skyline           = Waarder Kerkelaantje.jpg\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = Waarder with the church and the medieval Kerkelaantje\n| image_flag              =\n| image_shield            =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = Map - NL - Municipality code 0595 (2009).svg\n| map_caption             =\n| image_map1              = Map NL - Reeuwijk - Waarder.png\n| map_caption1            = The village centre (dark green) and the statistical district (light green) of Waarder in the municipality of Reeuwijk.\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Netherlands -->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Netherlands\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Netherlands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of the Netherlands|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[South Holland]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of municipalities of the Netherlands|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Bodegraven-Reeuwijk]]\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| leader_party            =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|52|3|41|N|4|49|21|E|region:NL_type:city(1647)|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          =\n| established_title       =\n| established_date        =\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = 1647\n| population_as_of        = 2008\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in the Netherlands|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             =\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in the Netherlands|Dialing code]]\n| area_code               =\n| website                 =\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n'''Waarder''' is a village in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] province of [[South Holland]]. It is a part of the former municipality of [[Reeuwijk]], and lies about 5&nbsp;km southwest of [[Woerden]].\n\nIn 2001, the village of Waarder had 1143 inhabitants. The built-up area of the village was 0.18&nbsp;km\u00b2, and contained 416 residences.<ref name=\"CBS\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), [http://www.cbs.nl/nl-NL/menu/themas/milieu-natuur-ruimte/ruimte/publicaties/cartografie-geografie/geografische-data/2001-bevolkingskernen-in-nederland.htm ''Bevolkingskernen in Nederland 2001'']. (Statistics are for the continuous built-up area).</ref>\nThe statistical area \"Waarder\", which also can include the peripheral parts of the village, as well as the surrounding countryside, has a population of around 1250.<ref name=\"CBS2\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), [http://statline.cbs.nl/ ''Statline: Kerncijfers wijken en buurten 2003-2005'']. As of 1 January 2005.</ref>\n\nWaarder was a separate municipality until 1964, when it became part of [[Driebruggen]],<ref>Ad van der Meer and Onno Boonstra, \"Repertorium van Nederlandse gemeenten\", KNAW, 2006. [http://www.knaw.nl/cfdata/publicaties/detail.cfm?boeken__ordernr=20061061]</ref> which became part of [[Reeuwijk]] in 1989. Since 2011 it is part of the municipality of [[Bodegraven-Reeuwijk]].\n\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Kuyper|Waarder|zh}} Map of the former municipality in 1868.\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in South Holland]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities of South Holland]]\n\n\n{{SouthHolland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waarder"}
